<HEAD>Double Amputee Cheers Her Team On</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUCYRUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When she was born, <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>'s doctors said she would never be able to walk, but the 14-year-old high school freshman has overcome congenital bone defects and is now a cheerleader. After enduring years of operations, including amputation of both feet, she attends <ORGANIZATION> Wynford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royals </ORGANIZATION> basketball games, wearing artificial limbs that fit over the calf up to the knee. `` My parents and God have helped me,'' she said before dashing onto the court at a recent basketball game. `` She has the guts and potential that are God-given,'' said her father, <PERSON> William </PERSON>. `` We take very little credit. She's done it on her own.'' At birth, <PERSON> Beth </PERSON>'s hips were dislocated and the bones in her legs were n't formed. Doctors said she would never walk. At three months, doctors wrapped her body in a full cast, hoping to straighten her hips. She wore the cast until she was 11 months old. After hundreds of treatments by specialists at <ORGANIZATION> Shriners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> for Crippled Children in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, she finally decided at age 10 to undergo amputation instead of bone fusion. After the first amputation, she walked into her fourth-grade classroom on the first day of school with a prosthesis on her right leg and a pair of crutches. She underwent the second amputation in June 1988, but only after playing for the seventh-grade girls volleyball team and trying out for cheerleading.
