<HEAD>New Yorker Gets Degree 56 Years After Fleeing Nazis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS throughout spelling of name from Rubenstein to Rubinstein.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than a half-century after fleeing the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>, 81-year-old <PERSON> Nina </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> on Monday received her doctorate in sociology at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> university. `` It's the last thing I expected in my life,'' said <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I'm elated, I'm proud, I'm surprised.'' The dean of <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Johann </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> Goethe </PERSON> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s sociology department, <PERSON> Lothar </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> was awarded the degree magna cum laude It was a big surprise for the retired <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> interpreter, who was 25 when she fled the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> in 1933, leaving behind her completed 247-page thesis for her doctorate. She first fled to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and then to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, when <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s troops marched on <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. `` I'm not particularly proud of myself in general, but I thought the dissertation was rather good,'' Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> said. It was delivered in German. `` But frankly I did not expect a magna cum laude. That was a very enormous surprise,'' she said, chuckling. Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> last week to take part in a colloquium Friday, part of 75th anniversary celebrations at the universtiy's social sciences department. `` I'm absolutely shattered. I think I never have been so exhausted, not only physically, but psychologically too, after that day on Friday,'' the soft-spoken Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> said. As part of the colloquium, Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> read several poems, taking an active part in the ceremonies, said Professor <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kettler </PERSON>, who was instrumental in arranging for her to get the degree. <PERSON> Kettler </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Trent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Peterborough </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, said it took him a year, along with <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON>'s half-sister, <PERSON> Hanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Papanek </PERSON>, to make arrangements for awarding the doctorate. `` It was like one of those ideas you suddenly have in the shower,'' <PERSON> Kettler </PERSON> said. `` This is the university facing up to its responsibility to its students and faculty. She did the work and deserves to be recognized for it.'' Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> in 1908 to parents of Jewish descent, who fled their native <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> as political exiles after the failed Russian revolution of 1905. She lived in neutral <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> from 1914 through 1917, where she had fled with her mother to avoid World War I. Later she returned to <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> to study, and in 1928 began working toward her degree under the noted sociology professor, <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Mannheim </PERSON>. Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> recalled how she enjoyed being in Mannheim's presence, and how the students used to meet him at Cafe <PERSON> Laumer </PERSON> in the university area of <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Bockenheim </LOCATION> district `` We very often met there with <PERSON> Mannheim </PERSON>. Of course, all the young ladies there adored him, he was extremely attractive, I've never forgotten that,'' she said Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> then pointed out photographs showing herself, and other students reading and chatting at the cafe with Mannheim, taken between 1930 and 1933. `` He went to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> right away'' after the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> came, Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> said. `` I never saw him again. I lost contact with him.'' <PERSON> Mannheim </PERSON>, who last worked at the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION>, had published dozens of manuscripts on sociology, including `` Man and <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> in an Age of Reconstruction,'' in 1935. He died in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> in 1947. Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> said she was ready to defend her thesis, titled `` The <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emigration </LOCATION> after 1789 _ A Contribution to the Sociology of Political Emigration,'' when the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> took over <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> university in 1933. She said a Nazi student retrieved her thesis, which she left behind on a desk in the university, before she fled to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> she worked as a translator and secretary for a literary agency, but fled again in 1940 when the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> invaded <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, leaving everything behind, including her thesis. A French neighbor kept Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON>'s belongings, and after the war traced her to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and sent the thesis to her, she said. Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON>, who worked as a simultaneous translator, `` mostly in Russian,'' for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, shelved the thesis for years until her half-sister, Ms. <PERSON> Papanek </PERSON>, a research professor of anthropology at <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, began trying to get it published. Later, efforts by Ms. <PERSON> Papanek </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kettler </PERSON>, and <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> university's <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> and Professor <PERSON> Claudia </PERSON> <PERSON> Honegger </PERSON>, arranged for Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> to finally receive her degree. Miss <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> said she will return to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Thursday. `` I'm incredibly tired and I have the feeling when I come back to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> I'm going to go to bed and stay there for a couple of days,'' she said.
