<FIRST>r w PM-DismantlingCatastrophic     12-11 0907</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dismantling Catastrophic,0928</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bureaucracy Shifts Into Reverse To Dismantle Catastrophic-Care Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal bureaucrats and private insurers are scrambling to rework health insurance benefits, adjust premiums and spread the word that the end is near for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>'s year-old catastrophic health care program. In addition, millions of senior citizens are refiguring their expected 1989 tax bills, the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is scrapping Form 8808 before it hits the printing press, and states are trying to figure out how they will cover an extra $ 300 million to $ 400 million in health care expenses for the poor. The Medicare Catastrophic Coverage Act _ expected to cost $ 48 billion in its first five years _ was enacted with fanfare in 1988 to protect 33 million elderly and disabled people against financial ruin from the staggering costs of prolonged illness. But even before most of the benefits took effect, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> voted last month to dismantle the program because of a firestorm of protest from senior citizens who complained it cost them too much. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has promised to sign the repeal measure. Under repeal, the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> must take back the extended hospitalization and nursing home coverage it has offered <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> beneficiaries for the past year and scrap plans to provide expanded coverage of drug and doctor bills and other medical expenses. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hays </PERSON>, the acting <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION> administrator, said a top priority for the agency is to get notices out to <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> beneficiaries explaining the new limits on their hospital and nursing home benefits. `` We want to make sure that there is n't confusion,'' <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> said. The agency also can forget about providing additional medical benefits that `` we had invested enormous energy and time in preparing to implement,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, have the tasks of rolling back the income tax surcharge on the elderly and the extra Medicare premium that financed the catastrophic program. The surtax was canceled completely; the extra premium will be scrapped at the end of the year. <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> said taxpayers will be instructed to ignore two lines on this year's 1040 tax forms _ lines 54 and 55 _ which refer senior citizens to the elusive Form 8808 that never got beyond the prototype stage. Higher-income senior citizens would have used 8808 to calculate their added income tax liability for the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> benefits. Senior citizens who paid extra amounts in quarterly income tax payments or through wage withholding to cover the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> surtax will get any overpayments back as part of their income tax refund, <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> said. About 40 percent of the elderly would have paid some surtax _ $ 22.50 for every $ 150 of federal income tax liability _ with about 6 percent paying the maximum amount of $ 800 per person this year. Scrapping the tax is the type of last-minute change it is easy to spring on taxpayers, <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> said. `` Everybody enjoys hearing news that they do n't have to pay a tax that was on the books,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, is complaining that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> did not give the agency enough lead time to stop withholding extra Medicare premiums that helped finance the catastrophic benefits. It may be April or May before extra payments of about $ 5.30 a month no longer are deducted from Social Security checks, with the overpayments to be refunded later. The premiums of $ 4 a month during 1989 will not be refunded. `` The bottom line is that Social Security will unscramble this egg, but we did not lay it,'' said Social Security Commissioner <PERSON> Gwendolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>. The repeal also is causing last-minute maneuvering among private insurers who will pick up some of the benefits being canned by the government. About 70 percent of elderly Americans purchase private `` medigap'' insurance to fill the gaps in their Medicare coverage. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissioners </ORGANIZATION> has until Dec. 15 to draft transition regulations for medigap policies, and private insurers have until Jan. 30 to revise their policies and premiums and notify policyholders of the changes. Any changes, however, will be retroactive to Jan. 1, when the government benefits expire. `` Insurance companies are doing their best, they're just grumbling about how long it took <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to make up their mind,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's kind of a ` We'll muddle through' situation. We just hope <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> does n't change their mind again next year.'' The association has estimated medigap premiums will rise 20 percent to 25 percent next year due to the combined effects of rising medical costs and the repeal of the catastrophic package. Fallout from the repeal also is reaching state governments. The repeal legislation left in place expanded Medicaid costs for the states, while scrapping provisions that would have offset some of the new expenses, said <PERSON> Alicia </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelrine </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> `` Grumbling is probably a tame word to describe what is going on out there,'' Ms. <PERSON> Pelrine </PERSON> said. `` States are already so maxed out on their ability to accommodate various -LRB- federal -RRB- mandates ... that a lot are saying, ` We do n't know how we're going to pay for this.''' <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Officers </ORGANIZATION>, said the original catastrophic legislation would have cost states $ 900 million, but the repeal bill boosts those costs by an additional $ 300 million to $ 400 million.
</TEXT>
