<SECOND>PM-Czech-Free Man,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freedom Overwhelms Czech Father</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a vast sea of arms outstretched in victory, <PERSON> Zdenek </PERSON> <PERSON> Machon </PERSON> joined in singing the national anthem, but, choking on emotion, he could barely get out the words. `` I can look people directly in the eye now, people from other countries,'' he said. `` We are a free people again. We are part of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> again.'' <PERSON> Machon </PERSON> was among 100,000 Czechoslovaks who on Sunday returned to <LOCATION> Wenceslas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> where only three weeks ago they first gathered to tell the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> that, after 41 years, enough was enough. On Sunday, they celebrated the naming of the first non-Communist dominated government since 1948. He is a big man with a thick mustache, but he showed no embarrassment at the tears trickling down his face. It was the students who first rose up, and <PERSON> Machon </PERSON> has three in his family. `` I am so thankful to my children for setting us free,'' he said. `` And I am so happy that they can now live their lives in freedom.'' From the towering statue of King Wenceslas on horseback to the gates of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>'s medieval <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, the distance of eight football fields end to end, Czechoslovaks shared the same thoughts. There were speeches and chants, but their message was all in their moist, red eyes. `` You have to understand how we felt in 1968,'' said <PERSON> Machon </PERSON>, now 47. `` We had one child then, and now we have three. Life will be different now.'' In 1968, a Soviet invasion brought an abrupt halt to the Czechoslovaks' last try for freedom. The people's only weapon were the `` V'' signs they aimed at the tanks. The next morning, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily, <PERSON> Rude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pravo </PERSON>, carried a picture of resisting crowds, with each person holding up two fingers. The caption said they were threatening to attack Socialist troops in two minutes. This time, there was no confusion over the `` V'' victory sign. At the first strains of the national anthem, <ORGANIZATION> Machon </ORGANIZATION>'s two thick fingers were joined by 200,000 others. At every chant, he leaned over to translate for a foreign reporter, eager that the world not miss any part of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s triumph. His wife beamed and nodded happily. `` How can I explain what this means?'' said <PERSON> Machon </PERSON>, who is a geophysicist. `` When I went abroad to meetings, I could not look at people. We were different, inferior, ashamed.'' When a Frenchwoman spoke from the fourth-floor balcony, delivering a message of support from European theater groups, he glowed. After she finished, the crowd chanted, `` Merci, Merci.'' The setting said as much as <PERSON> Machon </PERSON>'s explanation. Throughout four decades of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> rule, Czechoslovaks spoke in private of whom they were and what they would be again someday. <PERSON> Machon </PERSON> knew Sunday was that day. With the crowd, he chanted, `` We want <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>!'' demanding the now-vacant presidency for <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, the playwright who spent four of the last 20 years in prison for insisting on exposing the hypocrisy and brutality of Communist rule. As with <PERSON> Masaryk </PERSON> and others after him, Czechoslovaks in crisis rallied to a man of letters rather than a politician. `` It is a wonderful day, wonderful,'' <PERSON> Machon </PERSON> said. `` How can I say it?'' Instead of trying, he hugged the reporter and wept again.
