<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cuts in defense spending wo n't hurt the economy, analysts say, but could be traumatic for a workforce accustomed to satisfying a single complacent customer _ the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> _ instead of the competitive marketplace. A third of the nation's engineers and scientists work in defense and by some estimates 26 million people depend on the military economy, so there's considerable concern in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> about the recoil that will be felt the defense budget is sharply reduced, as seems likely. Analyst <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaufmann </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> thinks defense spending could be half its current size in 10 years. Both the new era opened by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> and the pressures of the deficit point to dismantling the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Era defense buildup. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruby </PERSON>, chief operating officer of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION>, says a number of firms are already planning `` downsizing.'' Some economists say the government also should be designing retraining, counseling, job search and relocation programs to ease the transition for defense workers. `` We put over a billion and a half dollars into building planes we did n't need'' to preserve jobs, says <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Korb </PERSON>, who was an assistant defense secretary in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. `` I'd like to see the government come up with a plan to help people in a graceful and humane way, but you talk about an industrial policy in this country and they call you a communist,'' he says. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is looking at the issue. It has scheduled hearings for Tuesday on `` the economic consequences of reduced defense spending and the winding down of the Cold War.'' `` Depending on its size and speed, a substantial cut in defense spending phased in over a number of years could be one of the best things that could happen to the economy and should not be looked on as something likely to cause recession or unemployment,'' says <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultze </PERSON>, who was President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s chief economic adviser. `` One thing this country does not have is a surplus of is skilled engineers and skilled workmen.'' But conversion of defense workers, technicians, managers and plants to the civilian economy will be trickier than it was after World War II, when <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> stopped making tanks and resumed making DeSoto automobiles without missing a step. There was enormous pent-up demand for civilian products, too. But government planners cite society's needs _ for environmental cleanup, recycling of plastics, health care _ which may be able to adopt defense industry technology. `` I hope trade associations will see the relationship between a mayor who is worried about defense cuts in his community and about waste management; if you're smart, you can walk in and say, ` I can solve them both at once,''' says <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tepper </PERSON> <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> of the Council on Economic Priorities. Defense managers have grown accustomed to working in the hothouse environment of <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> contracting, with no competition from overseas, a single, cooperative customer and cost-plus-profit accounting. `` Defense contractors are used to being told what the market is,'' says consultant <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Gansler </PERSON>, author of `` Affording Defense'' and a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> procurement official in 1972-77. `` The commercial world is n't like that.'' But <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON> <PERSON> Melman </PERSON>, retired professor of industrial engineering at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and a pioneer advocate of planned conversion, rejects the view that the economy can absorb defense budget cuts without severe dislocations. He argues for an elaborate government efforts to prepare defense workers and to create productive civilian jobs for them. `` What are they going to work at?'' he demands. `` Making shoes? Eight-five percent of our shoes are imported. Consumer electronics? All imported. Machine tools? Half are imported.'' Moreover, <PERSON> Melman </PERSON> argues, defense managers are incapable of making the leap without retraining. `` No major military-serving enterprise has demonstrated an autonomous ability to carry out the sort of occupational switch that is needed to go civilian,'' <PERSON> Melman </PERSON> wrote in his book, `` Profits Without Production.'' `` If you unleash these people, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> will turn into a third-rate economy,'' <PERSON> Melman </PERSON> says. `` They ca n't hack it. We will lose the capability of repairing the damage.'' Under a conversion legislation sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, defense contractors would be required to put 1.25 percent of receipts into a fund to pay the costs of economic adjustment. Laid-off workers might get 90 percent of their lost salaries while they are retrained for civilian jobs. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washingon </LOCATION> research outfit, says, `` Workers find work when the economy is healthy; you can plan the dickens out of what to do with a worker but when we're in a recession you ca n't do anything for him.'' <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> says although counseling, retraining and relocation programs are critical, `` income supplements, however, slow the adjustment process.''
