<HEAD>Report: Classified Study Told Bush of Soviet Reductions in May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who maintained up until a month ago that Soviet defense spending was growing, received a classified <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> report in May in which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence analysts expressed the opposite view, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> ordered the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> study of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defense strategy shortly after his election for help in dealing with Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. A 26-page executive summary of the secret report states `` there is broad agreement within the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence community'' that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> `` has decided to reverse a 20-year pattern of growth in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> military spending and force structure in order to boost the civil economy and Soviet foreign policy,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. Until a month ago, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and senior advisers criticized what they said was an increase in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> defense spending as they pressed <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to approve the nearly $ 300 billion defense budget for fiscal 1990. A White House spokesman interviewed by the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> about the classified report said, `` When it was written, people were trying to prognosticate on the basis of Soviet announcements and very early indications of Soviet behavior. In fact, at that time, our estimates were that there were few, if any changes.''
