<HEAD>New Prime Minister Out To Prove He's In Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 V.P. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, the man who reluctantly agreed to become prime minister of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, has set out to prove he's in control As head of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s first minority government, <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> does n't have a blank check to launch the revolutionary economic and social reforms that could allow <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> to join the ranks of the great powers in the next century. But political observers and associates say the 58-year-old prime minister has two things working in his favor _ a clean slate and a clean name. Within a week of taking the oath of office, <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> had reassured two embittered religious minorities they indeed have an important place in officially secular, predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Hindu </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. He appointed influential colleagues to lower-ranking Cabinet posts, thereby denying them new power bases. The more powerful posts went to men with the experience to push through change and the reputations for incorruptibility. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s five-party <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> coalition denied Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> a majority in the Nov. 22-26 elections and brought down the <PERSON> Nehru </PERSON> family dynasty that dominated Indian politics since the country became independent from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> 42 years ago. But <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> needs the continuing allegiance of both the Hindu fundamentalists and the Communists for his middle-of-the-road alliance to muster a majority in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. Given the fragilility of this alliance, many political observers are skeptical of the new government's ability to enact any major changes in the world's largest democracy, a country of 880 million people skewed between abject poverty and space-age achievements. The problems <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> inherited are enormous, but the mild-mannered, introverted politician who reluctantly agreed to head <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s newest government has not been shy about what he intends to accomplish. He lists his missions thus: to eliminate poverty, halt rising food prices that have doubled in the past year, decentralize federal power, reduce bureaucratic regulations and political meddling, open the economy to Western investors eager to do business with <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and patch up differences with neighboring <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. Foreign policy is a low priority for change. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> has said he will not deviate from the course <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has already charted between the world's superpowers. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, he said, will remain non-aligned and continue to build on its friendly relations with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The first major test of <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s government _ provided it survives a confidence vote in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> later this month _ will come during legislative elections in nine states in March and April. All but two of the states now are dominated by <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> `` If <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> loses, it will split and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> alliance will become stronger. If <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> defends its territory, it will give renewed confidence to <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and his party and weaken our coalition. Then any constructive cooperation between us and the opposition will end,'' said one <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> member, speaking on condition of anonymity. But analysts say <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s most immediate problems stem from factional disputes within his own <ORGANIZATION> Janata </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dal </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the largest group in the five-party <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. Those differences surfaced again recently during wrangling for Cabinet posts. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> appointed a Moslem as head of the powerful Home Ministry, a move seen as an attempt to span the growing rifts between the majority <PERSON> Hindus </PERSON> and the minority Moslems that erupted into riots in which at 300 people were killed this fall. Later, he visited the northern state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, the hotbed of the Sikh separatist movement, and offered prayers at the Sikhs' holiest shrine, the Golden Temple The visit by <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a Hindu, was the first by an Indian prime minister in more than five years and an effort to end the bloody secessionist campaign that has claimed more than 12,000 lives since 1982. `` A nation is not a map on a piece of paper,'' <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> later said. `` It lives in the hearts of the people, and if the hearts are divided, the nation stands divided. We will not allow this to happen.'' Despite speculation that <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> would keep the finance portfolio, which he held for two years under <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, he gave it to a veteran lawmaker who is expected to continue, if not speed up, the reforms <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> sees as needed to make <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> a competitor in the world markets. Instead, <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> kept the defense portfolio, a signal that he will wield considerable power since defense spending has received the biggest chunk of the national budget. The move prompted speculation <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> would be directly involved in investigation into controversial arms deals during the <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> administration. Government corruption was the linchpin in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>'s campaign against <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and earned <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> the nickname, `` The New Mr. Clean,'' a reference to similar promises that <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> made to clean up <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s bureacracy <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was buffeted by accusations that highly placed <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> received up to $ 50 million in kickbacks from the Swedish arms firm <ORGANIZATION> AB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION>, winner of a 1986 contract to sell $ 1.4 billion worth of howitzers to the Indian government. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s denials that any Indians profited from the <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> deal paled before detailed newspaper investigations, but the accusations have not been proved. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said there will be an investigation, but not a vendetta. `` I want to make it clear that we will not be vindictive,'' <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said. `` No scandal will be cooked up against him or anyone else. The law of the land will prevail.''
