<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Opposition March Turns Into Riot; 1 Dead, 20 Reported Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with reports of one killed, details,
quotes from witnesses. ADDS byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto MGA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MASATEPE, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A campaign march by hundreds of opposition supporters turned into a riot Sunday. Police said at least one person was killed and witnesses said 20 people were injured. Two vehicles were burned, and a private home and the local headquarters of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> were sacked. The fighting broke out during a rally by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opposition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> UNO </ORGANIZATION>, when a group of about 20 <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> loyalists and opposition followers exchanged insults and then blows in this town of 15,000 people about 30 miles south of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. Sandinistas accused sympathizers of the opposition coalition of starting the riot. Opposition leaders admitted their people took part but accused the Sandinistas of provoking the riot, saying Sandinista infiltrators posing as opposition militants encouraged the attack on the houses and vehicles. The local organizer of the opposition coalition, <PERSON> Jeremias </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahmud </PERSON>, said he saw a police officer draw his gun and shoot a man in the arm. Lt. <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Montoya </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Masatepe </LOCATION> police chief, said police were following orders in not intervening in the riot until it was nearly over. `` We had instructions not to get near the march,'' <PERSON> Montoya </PERSON> said. `` Going to the disturbances meant giving them -LRB- UNO -RRB- a pretext to say that we were there to repress them.'' National Opposition Union leaders have accused Sandinista gangs of disrupting earlier opposition rallies for the Feb. 25 elections. <PERSON> Montoya </PERSON> said one person was killed, but did not elaborate. Witnesses said at least 20 people were injured. Witnesses said groups of opposition activists attacked a house that was used by the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> as a campaign office as well as another nearby house. They said some activists set fire to a motorcycle and to a jeep with license plates from the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mahmud </PERSON>, the opposition coalition organizer, said he arrived as opposition sympathizers were stoning the Sandinista headquarters. He said a Sandinista from the nearby town of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Concepcion </LOCATION> was leading the mob. `` I told them that this man was an infiltrator and they beat him up,'' <PERSON> Mahmud </PERSON> said. `` In the fray, he dropped this pin and I grabbed it and showed it to them.'' <PERSON> Mahmud </PERSON> showed an enamel-and-gold pin commemorating the 10th anniversary of the Sandinista revolution. Such pins are awarded by the Sandinista Front for meritorious service to the party. He said the man, whose name he did not know, fled. <PERSON> Mahmud </PERSON> said by the time he tried to calm the mob, police had arrived. He said a 9-year-old girl who was walking next to him during the march was hit on the head by a rock `` which was meant for me'' and she was knocked out. He said at least three men were stabbed and other people were attacked with broken bottles and hit with stones and sticks. <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Cerda </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> campaign committee member, said he and 12 other people were in the party headquarters when it was attacked by a mob of about 200 people. He said they escaped through a back room. After destroying furniture and other articles in the Sandinista headquarters, the crowd moved to the second building, allowing its occupants to leave before stoning it. Both buildings were heavily damaged.
