<HEAD>5 Weeks After Racial Incident, MacMurray College has Quieted Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH OKESON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five weeks after racist letters were sent to black students at <ORGANIZATION> MacMurray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, the incident has prompted race-awareness activities and, some say, a new climate on the campus. `` Before the letters, there was a lot of tension, but now it's suppressed, and everybody's making an effort,'' said <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>, a black freshman at the small liberal-arts school `` I think before the letters <PERSON> MacMurray </PERSON> was to some extent a closed community with the blacks on the outside looking in,'' said <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON> <PERSON> Bragg </PERSON>, a black sophomore. `` Since the letters, I've noticed a lot more interaction between blacks and whites.'' On Nov. 2, letters containing racial slurs and threats were found in campus mailboxes of the 35 to 40 black students at the 620-student school, as well as that of the college's only black staff member. The letters were addressed to students by name and campus mail box number. They contained epithets such as `` Uncle Tom'' and slurs specifically tailored to each recipient, according to students who saw the letters. Four days later, students marched in protest across the campus of the private college in west-central <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> Police Chief <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Weeks </PERSON> says his department has n't identified a suspect, although police were able to take fingerprints from the letters `` It's pretty much a dead issue right now,'' Weeks said. Student body president <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> holds little hope that the culprit will be found. `` I do n't think we'll ever know who wrote the letters,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>, a junior majoring in education for the deaf. `` I do n't think it would be possible to fingerprint everyone on campus. Ms. <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>, who is white, said it may be best that the writer remain unknown. `` If it's a white student, it's going to cause a lot of tension between blacks and whites,'' she said. `` If it's a black student, the blacks will be embarrassed. I think many students would feel better not knowing.'' Since the letter-writing, there have n't been any racial incidents reported on campus. The college has sponsored a forum for students to talk about racism, and seminars on cultural diversity and a workshop on racism are in the works. Officials say more classes may include subjects of black interest. The student government is planning an ethnic festival and the sale of T-shirts promoting racial equality, and the administration plans to make <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s birthday a holiday. College president <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said he wants to recruit more black faculty members but that it's difficult because blacks who receive doctoral degrees are intensely sought by other colleges. `` It's just very difficult because of the small number in the pipeline and because in a school of this size and in a town this size there's just not the support network of other professional minorities,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. `` Our best hope to recruit additional role models is going to be from our own students, and that's going to take a while.'' Philosophy professor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> said the incident gave a false picture of <PERSON> MacMurray </PERSON>, which he said has traditionally welcomed black students. Black senior <PERSON> Marquita </PERSON> <PERSON> Archie </PERSON>, who said she cried each day for five days after the incident, said the letters reflected the bias that is everywhere. Ms. <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>, the student body president, said the students now realize that. `` I think it affected the majority of the students on campus and opened a lot of students' eyes about racial tension,'' she said. `` I know it opened mine.''
