<FIRST>r i PM-Czech-NewFaces     12-11 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czech-New Faces,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Government Brings Faces From Political Wilderness</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A disbarred lawyer just out of jail becomes deputy premier with partial responsibility for police. A dissident journalist who also has done time, and most recently stoked coal in a factory, is named foreign minister. A bank clerk takes over the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. The appointments Sunday show just how utterly a 3-week-old peaceful popular revolt has turned Czechoslovak politics on end. The swift, smooth revolution has ousted the leaders of the crackdown that followed the suppression of the 1968 ` Prague Spring' reforms Out are those who stripped of party membership half a million Communists deemed too reformist. Many of the persecuted also lost all access to anything but the most menial jobs. Now, those who suffered are returning with remarkable ease to take center stage in national politics. The revolt has brought the ebullient <PERSON> Jiri </PERSON> <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON>, working as a stoker since he last got out of jail in 1982, back to his original profession, journalism _ a job he lost in the crackdown on `` Prague Spring'' reforms. The only difference is that instead of writing stories, <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> gave them out, as spokesman for the Civic Forum opposition coalition. Now, he is to serve as foreign minister, a role Civic Forum thinks he is suited for because of his fluent English and French and experience in the Far East and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the mid-1960s as a correspondent for state radio. After he lost that job and his <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> membership, <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> worked in the archive department of a design institute and wrote three books published in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> but banned in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. Once he signed the Charter 77 human rights document in 1977 and became a leading member of <ORGANIZATION> VONS </ORGANIZATION>, a movement keeping track of political prisoners, <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> found himself increasingly under police harassment. In May 1979, the police arrested <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON>, <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> and other leading <ORGANIZATION> VONS </ORGANIZATION> activists. In November that year <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> was sentenced to three years in jail. Since release, he had worked as a stoker, swapping shifts in a <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> factory with another dissident, <PERSON> Petr </PERSON> <PERSON> Uhl </PERSON>. A far more recent ex-prisoner now in the government is <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carnogursky </PERSON>, a dissident barred from practicing law since 1977 and a well-known Roman Catholic activist in his native <LOCATION> Slovakia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carnogursky </PERSON> was released from jail only two weeks ago, one of the first political prisoners to be freed as the Communists scrambled to meet the demands of pro-democracy demonstrators. <PERSON> Carnogursky </PERSON>, 45, was arrested in mid-August along with four other dissidents for signing an appeal to Slovaks to lay flowers in memory of those who died in the August 1968 Soviet-led invasion that crushed the ` Prague Spring' reforms. Authorities charged <PERSON> Carnogursky </PERSON> and <PERSON> Miroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Kusy </PERSON>, another Slovak dissident named Sunday as head of a new federal office of press and information, with incitement and subversion charges that could have jailed them for up to 10 years. <PERSON> Kusy </PERSON> was released before his trial and acquittal last month, but <PERSON> Carnogursky </PERSON> was not allowed out. A bespectacled, balding man with polite, careful manners, <PERSON> Carnogursky </PERSON> won a reputation in <LOCATION> Bratislava </LOCATION> as a defense lawyer or legal adviser on human rights cases, and the publisher of the underground newspaper, <PERSON> Bratislavske </PERSON> <PERSON> Listy </PERSON>. On Sunday, he was named one of two first deputy premiers in the new government. <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Klaus </PERSON>, the new finance minister, also suffered for his beliefs. He was expelled from the country's leading institute of economic research at the age of 26 in 1970 and worked in lowly positions at the state bank through the 1970s. <PERSON> Klaus </PERSON>'s free market economic beliefs may not go down well with Czechoslovak workers, who have enjoyed a relatively cozy life for relatively little work for the past four decades. It will be up to <PERSON> Petr </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, a worker at <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>'s giant CKD heavy engineering works, to safeguard the proletarian interests as Labor Minister. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, 48, is a blacksmith by profession. He started work at <ORGANIZATION> CKD </ORGANIZATION> in 1962, and enrolled to study economics in 1969, but was thrown out the next year during the crackdown.
</TEXT>
