<HEAD>Battered And Burned By Demonstrators, Lenin Quietly Removed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs at end with Jaruzelski condemning attacks, Lenin
museum closed in Krakow.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities in the southern steel town of <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> have quietly removed a statue of <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> that youthful demonstrators have repeatedly defaced and tried to destroy. The removal was ordered Friday after demonstrations the past two Wednesdays in which youths who threw paint and flammable liquids on the monument clashed with police, who used water cannon and tear gas to disperse them. The state <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency said the 30-foot statue was emoved from its plinth and `` in perfect condition transported to the locality of Wroblowice ... For necessary conservation works.'' Its future will be be decided by the municipal and district councils, <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said, but it is unlikely that anyone in <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> will want it back. The monument to the founder of the Soviet state, placed on a central square, had been the centerpiece of the city built around a huge steel mill outside <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> in the 1950s as a model socialist community. For residents of <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION>, a Solidarity stronghold, it has long been a despised symbol of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s past forced dependence on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The attacks by the youthful demonstrators had created a delicate problem for the non-Communist government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Taduesz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>. The Solidarity-led government is trying to maintain good relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and said it would not tolerate more violence. Mediators had called on the local government to move quickly to remove the monument. The statue has suffered several ignoble attacks over the years. In 1979 it was dynamited by activists and had to be rebuilt by Communist authorities. A spokesman for Communist President <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> said the `` acts of vandalism ... met with his highest condemnation.'' `` He believes these acts are manifestations of exceptional rampant fury. They do harm to the good name of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> worldwide, not only to the good relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' said the spokesman, <PERSON> Wlodzimierz </PERSON> <PERSON> Losinski </PERSON>. The cultural commission of the <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> city council on Saturday also closed the city's <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> and another cultural institution bearing his name, the pro-Solidarity <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wyborcza </ORGANIZATION> newspaper reported today.
