<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Communists' policy-setting <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> met today following the nation's largest pro-democracy rally in which tens of thousands of people demanded that party leaders share power. Also today, the municipal court in <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION> approved the registration application of Ecoglasnost, making the environmental organization <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>'s first legal independent political group. Party leader <PERSON> Petar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mladenov </PERSON> opened the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> session with a speech on `` the situation in the country, the party and the immediate tasks,'' the state news agency <ORGANIZATION> BTA </ORGANIZATION> said. The dispatch gave no further details. About 5,000 people held a silent vigil in 14-degree temperatures earlier in the day outside party headquarters to show the Communist leadership the people were watching its work, according to organizers. On Sunday, more than 50,000 people chanted `` Democracy!'' and applauded demands for the Communist leadership to quit. It was the biggest rally of its kind since <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>'s pro-democracy movement began less than a month ago and since the party consolidated power 43 years ago. Many people held candles in the bright sunshine at today's vigil, and a white, red and green Bulgarian flag waved on a platform set up behind the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> building Police set up barriers to keep the gathering from disrupting morning traffic, and a few officers stood at a distance around the crowd. After one hour, the crowd dispersed quietly. Organizers said similar vigils would be held later today and on Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting was expected to last at least two days and focus on growing grass-roots demands f