<HEAD>Ruling Narrows Freedom of Information Act</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a decision narrowing the reach of the Freedom of Information Act, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today shielded the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> from having to give <ORGANIZATION> Grumman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> documents received from another government agency. By a 6-3 vote, the court said the documents can be withheld because they were `` compiled for law enforcement purposes'' _ and therefore are exempt from the 1966 law aimed at curtailing government secrecy. Grumman and the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Contract </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> exchanged letters in 1978. In the exchange, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> agency questioned certain accounting practices <ORGANIZATION> Grumman </ORGANIZATION> used for defense contracts. Grumman defended its practices, and no government action was taken. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> began a criminal investigation of <ORGANIZATION> Grumman </ORGANIZATION> in 1985, and the exchange of letters was sent from the audit agency to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. Grumman filed an FOIA lawsuit in 1987 seeking `` all documents that are related in any way to the subject of the -LRB- 1978 -RRB- correspondence.'' A federal judge ruled against the contractor, saying release of the documents would jeopardize a grand jury investigation. But the 2nd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> ruled that the <ORGANIZATION> FOIA </ORGANIZATION> requires release of the documents. The appeals court said the exemption for documents compiled for law enforcement purposes does not apply in this case because the letters were not originally obtained or generated for law enforcement purposes. Today, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said the appeals court was wrong about the exemption's scope. `` Documents having been compiled once for the purpose of routine audits wer not disqualified from being compiled again later for a different purpose,'' Justice <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> wrote for the court. `` We do not accept the distinction the court of appeals drew between documents that originally were assembled for law enforcement purposes and those that were not so originally assembled,'' he said. <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> said sought-after documents may fall under the FOIA exemption if they have been gathered or stored by a law enforcement agency `` when the response to the <ORGANIZATION> FOIA </ORGANIZATION> request must be made.'' <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>'s opinion was joined by Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and Justices <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. Justices <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> dissented. The case is <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Doe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Doe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1083.
