graf pvs, `Croatia's state...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leadership of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s second-largest state today for the first time called for the establishment of a multiparty system in this Communist country Communists have been slow in realizing the `` historic exhaustion of the single-party system,'' <PERSON> Stanko </PERSON> <PERSON> Stojicevic </PERSON>, head of the Croatian <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling presidium, said at the opening of a regional party congress in the Croatian capital of <LOCATION> Zagreb </LOCATION>. `` There can be no democratic socialism without political pluralism based on the right of association and competition of political -LRB- movements -RRB- and programs,'' <PERSON> Stojicevic </PERSON> said in his keynote speech carried by the state <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency. Until now the liberal northern state of <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> was the only one of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six constituent republics to openly advocate the introduction of Western-style democracy. About a dozen independent movements and parties have been set up in <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> over the past year, and the region plans to hold its first free legislative elections next March. On Sunday some 25,000 people in several Croatian cities signed a petition urging legalization of numerous parties that would make possible the holding of free elections in the republic bordering <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. `` We consider that -LRB- <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s new constitution -RRB- should provide for a political system that will include ... parties and movements representing the political interests of citizens,'' said <PERSON> Stojicevic </PERSON>, according to a report broadcast by <LOCATION> Zagreb </LOCATION> radio. <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION> and some other republics have in the past been non-committal about multiparty democracy, which is vehementl