<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Profits     12-11 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Profits,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Limits How Multinational Corporations Can Use Laws to Reduce
Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today limited the way multinational corporations can use foreign tax laws to reduce their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxes, a ruling the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration said may save the government hundreds of millions of dollars. The court ruled unanimously against <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in a case stemming from operations of <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION>'s British subsidiary in the early 1970s. The British subsidiary of the Ohio-based corporation incurred net losses in 1972 and 1973, at least under British tax law. The subsidiary's 1973 loss included British tax deductions that were not allowed under American law. As a result, the British government refunded to the subsidiary tax payments made there for 1970 and 1971. The refunds prompted the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to recompute the taxes it said <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> owed in this country. Multinationals are entitled to claim a share of taxes paid by subsidiaries overseas as credits against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxes. In <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION>'s case, since the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> said American law did not recognize the 1973 deductions permitted the company in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the corporation's loss was converted into a profit. The redetermination had the further effect of wiping out, for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tax purposes, the foreign tax credits previously allowed <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> in 1970 and 1971. As a result, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> assessed <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> $ 791,240 in taxes and interest for 1970 and 1971. <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> then filed suit in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Claims </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, saying the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> erred in applying American law instead of British law to determine the company's accumulated profits. The claims court ruled against <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION>. But a federal appeals court here reversed the decision last year. The appeals court said a multinational company is entitled to use a foreign nation's tax laws to determine accumulated profits made by a subsidiary in that country. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today overruled the appeals court. Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, in his opinion for the high court, said the approach favored by <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> would lead to unequal tax treatment for subsidiaries _ as opposed to companies set up as foreign branches of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations _ whenever a foreign government calculates income differently than in this country. That result would not square with federal laws aimed at assuring tax parity between corporations that operate through foreign subsidiaries and those that operate through foreign branches, <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said hundreds of millions of dollars are at stake, even though <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tax law was changed in 1986 to bar multinationals from using a foreign country's calculation of its accumulated profits for most future tax payments here. The department said more than 25,000 foreign subsidiaries of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies do business in more than 100 countries. The government's most recent figures show the companies claimed more than $ 9 billion in foreign tax credits in 1982. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> said it is reviewing claims for $ 150 million in refunds in such cases. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1474.
</TEXT>
