d a day when more than 7,000 people paid final respects to the victims, eight of whose white, flower-draped coffins lay in state at the university's hall of honor. `` We're sort of helpless in a way, but you feel you have to do something,'' said <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON>, an artist waiting in line with a small floral bouquet. The gunman burst into the university's engineering school late Wednesday afternoon on the last day of classes, shouting `` I want the women!'' and `` You're all a bunch of feminists. I hate feminists!'' A suicide letter showed he carried a special grudge against feminists, police said. Thirteen of those who died were students; the other was a school employee. All were between the ages of 21 and 31. The gunman also wounded nine women and four men. Their condition was reported today to be improving. The engineering school started psychological counseling for students and the victims' families and postponed exams until Wednesday. Documents obtained by the <ORGANIZATION> Montreal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION> of the divorce of <PERSON> Lepine </PERSON>'s parents, which occurred when he was seven, showed that his mother said his father beat her, the boy and his sister. The father believed `` women are not men's equals and that women are servants to men,'' the mother, <PERSON> Monique </PERSON> <PERSON> Lepine </PERSON>, said at the 1976 hearing. The father, <PERSON> Rachid </PERSON> <PERSON> Liass </PERSON> <PERSON> Gharbi </PERSON>, denied the allegations. <PERSON> Lepine </PERSON> was named <PERSON> Gamil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gharbi </PERSON> but took his mother's name when he was 18. Today's service was for <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Klueznick </PERSON>, 31; <PERSON> Genevieve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergeron </PERSON>, 21; <PERSON> Helene </PERSON> <PERSON> Colgan </PERSON>, 23; <PERSON> Nathalie </PERSON> <PERSON> Croteau </PERSON>, 23; <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Daigneault </PERSON>,