<HEAD>Honor to Revolutionary Priest Revives Old Grievances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The remains of a revolutionary priest are to be enshrined Tuesday in the hallowed Pantheon in a bicentennial ceremony that has revived 200-year-old grievances of the Roman Catholic church against the French Revolution. Church leaders are boycotting the event, the last planned in a bicentennial year in which the archbishop of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> says `` we were invited to commemorate a period when the church was violently persecuted.'' <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregoire </PERSON>, better known as the Abbe <PERSON> Gregoire </PERSON>, fought slavery, proposed the abolition of the monarchy and backed a controversial oath of allegiance to the state that clergy were forced to take. To close out a year of bicentennial parades, exhibits and fireworks, President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> decided to honor the Abbe <PERSON> Gregoire </PERSON> and two other revolutionary figures: the philosopher <LOCATION> Condorcet </LOCATION> and the mathematician <PERSON> Gaspard </PERSON> <PERSON> Monge </PERSON>. A solemn ceremony is planned Tuesday evening for the placing of their remains in the Pantheon, a disaffected church in the form of a classical temple on the <LOCATION> Left </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> where the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> honors its heroes. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> hierarchy decided not to send any representatives, although papal nuncio <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonetti </PERSON> will represent Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> at the ceremony. The church in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, while no longer the anti-republican force it once was, has not forgotten the revolution's massacres of clergy and violent desecration of churches. The Abbe <PERSON> Gregoire </PERSON> was a central figure in the drama that split the revolution and the church: the 1790 Civil Constitution of the Clergy, which required the clergy to swear allegiance to the state. Many resisted, maintaining their loyalty to the pope, and relations rapidly deteriorated. `` The Abbe <PERSON> Gregoire </PERSON> defended a conception of the church which differs from the Catholic tradition,'' Cardinal <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lustiger </PERSON>, the archbishop of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, was quoted as saying in an interview in <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monde </ORGANIZATION> in which he explained the decision not to attend the ceremony. But <PERSON> Lustiger </PERSON> said he would preside at an Office for the Dead to mark the Abbe <PERSON> Gregoire </PERSON>'s exhumation from <LOCATION> Montparnasse </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cemetery </LOCATION>, even though his predecessor as archbishop of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> refused to authorize a church funeral when <PERSON> Gregoire </PERSON> died in 1831. The papal nuncio's presence `` confirms the desire of the Holy See to help <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and French Catholics heal the wounds which may remain from the revolutionary crisis and the anti-religious violence early in this century,'' <PERSON> Lustiger </PERSON> was quoted as saying. <PERSON> Lustiger </PERSON> said he considered it worthwhile to honor the Abbe <PERSON> Gregoire </PERSON> `` because of his struggle for the emancipation of the Jews, for the rights of blacks and the abolition of slavery.'' But he also said the French bishops had tried to maintain their proper role `` with dignity'' throughout the bicentennial celebrations `` in which we were invited to commemorate a period when the church was violently persecuted.'' The French hierarchy's decision not to participate in the ceremony for the Abbe <PERSON> Gregoire </PERSON> has been questioned discreetly by other church leaders. `` The absence of bishops at the Pantheon will surprise a certain number of Christians. I understand that reaction,'' said <PERSON> Monsignor </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Delaporte </PERSON>, the bishop of <LOCATION> Cambrai </LOCATION>. The others being honored Tuesday are less controversial. <PERSON> Jean-Antoine </PERSON> <PERSON> Caritat </PERSON>, marquis de <LOCATION> Condorcet </LOCATION>, a friend of Voltaire and other `` philosophes,'' opposed the death penalty and favored equal rights for women. During the Jacobin purge of the Girondins he was arrested and died in prison in March 1794. In his case, the transfer of remains is symbolic; his body was thrown in a common grave and never recovered. <PERSON> Gaspard </PERSON> <PERSON> Monge </PERSON>, the inventor of descriptive geometry, served on the revolutionary committee that developed the metric system. He gave courses in manufacture of cannons and powder for the defense of the young republic, and later was close to <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON>, losing all his honors when <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> fell in 1814.
