 Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. AGE DISCRIMINATION The Court ruled that federal judges may help plaintiffs in age discrimination suits try to find other possible victims and seek their participation in such suits. The justices, by a 7-2 vote, ruled against <ORGANIZATION> Hoffmann-La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which is accused of bias against older workers in laying off some 1,200 employees at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> plants. The high court said judges in such `` class action'' suits may help plaintiffs locate other possible victims of discrimination, who may be unaware of the lawsuit, and solicit their participation. The case is <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Sperling </PERSON>, 88-1203. <PERSON> NOFZIGER </PERSON> The court refused to reinstate former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Lyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>'s conviction on charges of illegal lobbying after he left the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court ruling that overturned <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>'s 1988 conviction, 90-day jail sentence and $ 30,000 fine. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>, 89-719. FREEDOM OF INFORMATION The court shielded the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> from having to give <ORGANIZATION> Grumman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> documents received from another government agency, narrowing the reach of the Freedom of Information Act. By a 6-3 vote, the court said the documents can be withheld because they were `` compiled for law enforcement purposes'' and therefore are exempt from the 1966 law aimed at curtailing government secrecy. The case is <ORG