<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to DELETE reference to driver being drunk, which is
one of the charges against him. He has admitted to drinking before the
crash but has not pleaded guilty to drunken driving.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The prosecution rested today in the murder trial of a driver who crashed into a church bus, and the defense opened its case with testimony aimed at showing that the bus was n't safe. <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> Fire Marshal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> testified that the seat coverings and cushions on the bus `` were in fact combustible and will burn very rapidly when ignited.'' Lawyers for <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> contend an unsafe bus is to blame for the 27 deaths and multiple injuries in the May 14, 1988, disaster south of this <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> community. The bus was built before more stringent federal safety standards went into effect. However, not all of <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>'s testimony supported that contention. The fire marshal also testified that dense black smoke that rolled through the bus could have been caused by the burning of gasoline alone, not by the seat covers. And he said a protective cage around the bus' gas tank would n't have prevented the fire that followed the crash. <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>, who was driving a black <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> pickup, admits drinking the day of the crash, driving on the wrong side of Interstate 71 and striking the loaded church bus. He is charged with 27 counts of murder, 42 counts of wanton endangerment, 12 counts of assault and a count of drunken driving. The defense phase of the trial is expected to wind up by Friday. Last week, Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Richwalsky </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> presented a detailed reconstruction of the accident, based largely upon weeks of study by <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> trooper <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> `` Sonny'' Cease. The jury also heard testimony from relatives of 26 of the 27 victims, from police and a medical expert about <PERSON> Mahoney </P