<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     12-11 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>65 Bodies of Suspected Sinhalese Radicals Found</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities found the bodies of 65 suspected Sinhalese radicals _ some shot, others burned _ and military officials said Monday that pro-government vigilantes had done the killings. The bodies were discovered after Sinhalese radicals set fire to dozens of public buses over the weekend in central and southern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. The officials, who can not be identified under briefing rules, said the victims were believed members of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, an ultra-nationalist Sinhalese guerrilla group trying to overthrow the government for making peace overtures to Tamil secessionists in the northeast. The front began its campaign in 1987 and has continued to attack the government although its six top leaders were killed last month by government forces. On Sunday, the militants burned 32 government-owned buses in <LOCATION> Ambalantota </LOCATION>, about 90 miles south of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, a government statement said. Also Sunday, at least 16 more government-owned buses were set ablaze in other attacks and two railway engines and a railroad station were burned at <LOCATION> Gampha </LOCATION> district's <LOCATION> Yagoda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> village </LOCATION>, 15 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, the government said. To counter the militant violence, human rights groups say, the government this year set up vigilante groups which have killed hundreds of civilians suspected of associating with the front. The government denies the charge. The military officials on Monday, however, blamed pro-government vigilantes for the killings that were reported since Sunday in the Sinhalese heartland of central and southern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, where the front's campaign has focused. Military officials said 21 bodies were found in <LOCATION> Wellawaya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> village </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Monaragala </LOCATION> district, 100 miles east of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. Most of the victims were Sinhalese men between the ages 18 and 30, the officials said. They said 18 bodies were found at <LOCATION> Mavaralla </LOCATION> village in central <LOCATION> Kegalle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> district </LOCATION>, 11 at southern <LOCATION> Hakmana </LOCATION> town, six in the central town of <LOCATION> Kandy </LOCATION> and the nine in other towns. More than 6,000 people have died in the Sinhalese violence that was sparked by an India-sponsored peace accord signed by the government in July 1987 with Tamil rebels demanding a separate homeland for their minority community. The front alleged the accord too many concessions to the Tamils, who are mainly Hindus and comprise 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people. Tamils claim they are discriminated against in jobs and education by the Sinhalese who are mainly Buddhists and make up 75 percent of the population. The Sinhalese also control the government and the military. The Sinhalese rebels also opposed the presence of Indian peacekeeping troops, deployed in the north and the east to supervise the peace accord. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has begun withdrawing its soldiers from most areas ahead of a Dec. 31 deadline, but the vacuum has resulted in a power struggle among Tamil groups. Three Tamils were killed late Sunday and early Monday in fighting between two groups, the officials said. At least 10,000 Sri Lankans have died in the Tamil rebellion that started in 1983 and the post-accord violence.
