<HEAD>Court Ruling Aids Workers in Age-Bias Suits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday made employers easier targets for class action age-bias lawsuits by allowing federal judges to lend a hand in alerting possible victims of discrimination. In a 7-2 ruling, the court let judges help plaintiffs in such suits locate other possible victims and seek their participation. The decision is a boost to workers suing <ORGANIZATION> Hoffmann-La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which is accused of bias against older workers in laying off or demoting some 1,200 employees at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> plants. In other action, the court: _ Refused to reinstate former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Lyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>'s conviction on charges of illegal lobbying after he left the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> The justices declined to disturb a federal appeals court ruling that overturned <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>'s 1988 conviction, 90-day jail sentence and $ 30,000 fine. _ Shielded the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> from having to give <ORGANIZATION> Grumman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> documents received from another government agency, narrowing the reach of the Freedom of Information Act By a 6-3 vote, the court said the documents were exempt from the 1966 law aimed at curtailing government secrecy. _ Unanimously limited the way multinational corporations can use foreign tax laws to reduce their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxes, a ruling the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration said may save the government hundreds of millions of dollars _ Rejected arguments that <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s mandatory seatbelt law is unconstitutional _ Disbarred former Rep. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, from practicing law before the high court and took a first step toward disbarring former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> was convicted of racketeering and <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> of lying to a grand In the age-bias case, the court said federal law permits judges to help plaintiffs locate other possible victims of discrimination, who may be unaware of the lawsuit, and solicit their participation. In his opinion for the court, Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said judges should have leeway but not `` unbridled discretion'' to manage class action suits in this fashion. That `` serves the legitimate goal'' of avoiding multiple suits in the same case and lets the judge set uniform dates for plaintiffs to announce their participation, he said. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> cautioned that judges `` must be scrupulous to respect judicial neutrality'' and `` take care to avoid even the appearance'' they are endorsing a suit. Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> joined Justice <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> in dissent. <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON>, writing for both, said federal law does not authorize judges `` to undertake the unheard-of role of midwifing'' lawsuits against employers. <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> dismissed or demoted about 1,200 workers Feb. 4, 1985, in what was dubbed `` Black Monday'' by many veteran employees. They said a disproportionately high number of laid-off or demoted workers were over 40 years old. A group of older workers sued, alleging the company violated the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act. The group's leaders then sought to contact all fired workers over 40 eligible to join the lawsuit. Some 400 employees agreed to join, but the plaintiffs said they believed there might be 200 or more additional workers who were not aware of the suit and sought to contact them. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON> ordered the company to provide the names and addresses of all fired workers. He said that once the workers are found, they may be sent an explanation of the suit and a form seeking their consent to join the court fight. The form said the judge authorized the mailing but took no position on the merits of the case. Increasing the number of plaintiffs in such suits can be a big advantage for the workers by helping them spread out court costs. In seeking workers to join the suit against <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON>, the leaders of the court fight requested a $ 200 contribution to help defray the costs. The stakes also go up for the employer who may be forced to pay damages to more workers.
