<HEAD>Supreme Court Refuses to Reinstate Nofziger Conviction</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former White House aide <PERSON> Lyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> won a legal victory Monday when the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused to reinstate his 1988 illegal lobbying conviction. `` That kind of news is always welcome. It certainly makes the holiday season a bit brighter,'' said <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Barcella </PERSON>. The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court ruling that overturned <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>'s conviction on charges he illegally lobbied top presidential aides within a year of leaving the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Barcella </PERSON> said dropping any further prosecution of <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> represents `` the only humane course.'' But independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> declined comment, saying he would have an announcement at some future date. <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> was White House political director from 1981, when President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took office, until early 1982. He was convicted of lobbying on behalf of three private clients _ the scandal-plagued <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a maritime workers union and <ORGANIZATION> Fairchild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. He was sentenced to 90 days in jail and fined $ 30,000. Prosecutors said <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> lobbied for an Army engine contract for <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>, for the placement of civilian sailors on <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> vessels and for continued <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> purchases of an antitank aircraft made by Fairchild. He was tried under the Ethics in Government Act of 1978, which imposes a one-year ban on lobbying former colleagues after a person leaves service in the federal government's executive branch. The ban covered lobbying on any matter in which the lobbyist's former agency `` has a direct and substantial interest. <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> contended he did not violate the law because he was trying to stimulate, not influence or exploit, White House interest on issues of concern to his clients. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here ruled June 27 that <PERSON> Noziger </PERSON>'s criminal indictment should have been dismissed because it did not charge him with having `` knowingly'' lobbied on matters in which White House officials possessed a direct and substantial interest. In his appeal, independent counsel <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> said the appeals court ruling hampers <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' attempt to deal with `` the spectacle of high-level government officials using the ` revolving door' to turn their government service into lucrative lobbying businesses when the ink had barely dried on their resignations.'' Requiring prosecutors to prove a former government employee knew the subject of his lobbying was of `` direct and substantial'' interest to his former agency `` will reward purposeful ignorance or heedlessness,'' <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> argued. Lawyers for <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> said the appeals court ruling is unlikely to have any future impact because of legislation enacted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in November. The legislation, the Ethics Reform Act of 1989, eliminates the `` direct and substantial'' interest requirement to create a flat ban on government employees lobbying their former agencies within a year of their resignations.
