<TEXT>
 The holidays are here and for many people Christmas wo n't be complete until they get a piece of mail from this tiny central <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> village. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> office here is inundated with requests for a rubber-stamped symbol from the village that stakes claim as home of <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON>, the Red Nosed Reindeer. `` I think it's nifty,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayry </PERSON>, who is running the <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> post office until a permanent postmaster is found. `` I really do. It's something different.'' With a rubber stamper, post office workers press a stamp of <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> _ complete with a shiny nose _ on mail. The stamp measures 1.5 inches wide and 2 inches high and is underscored with: `` <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, Home of <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON>, The Red Nosed Reindeer.'' <PERSON> Hayry </PERSON> said some want the stamps to dress up their Christmas cards, while others want it for their stamp collections. Collectors send stamped envelopes with their addresses to the post office and ask that they be sent back with the <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> stamp, he said. Past years' requests have come from more than a dozen states. The idea and original design for the stamp came from <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON> <PERSON> Blonien </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> postmaster from 1951 to 1971. The <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> character was created in 1939 by <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> May </PERSON>, a catalog copywriter for <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, who wrote a poem about the famous reindeer. A song by <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Marks </PERSON> followed in 1949, and the res