 the incident was exhausted.'' Later, he said, <PERSON> Melnikov </PERSON> apologized for `` a slip of the tongue.'' <PERSON> Toome </PERSON>, quoted in Sunday' Noorte Haal, said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` he did not care about remaining in power'' and that his reforms were for the good of Soviets, not foreigners. `` If you really think like that, let's discuss it,'' Toome quoted <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as telling critics. <PERSON> Toome </PERSON>'s remarks in the paper were read over the phone by <PERSON> Hirv </PERSON> <PERSON> Elmar </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Estonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> ally <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON>, editor of Pravda and a newly appointed secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the Soviet leader did not make a serious offer to resign, but merely employed `` an oratorical method.'' Reaffirming his support for perestroika, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> `` definitely and emphatically indicated the solidness of this line and his personal devotion to it, and very sharply said this was the only line for him,'' <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> said. `` Can you interpret this as actually posing a question about his resignation?'' <PERSON> Frolov </PERSON> asked. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> emerged reinforced from the meeting, adding to his posts of party general secretary and Soviet president the newly created job of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief for the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> federation. All votes at the meeting, except one, were unanimous, the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> source said. Rank-and-file Communists rallied in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> three days before the plenum to support <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> against what they predicted would be a bid by hard-liners to oust him. The committee member said some sort of attempt at calling <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to account may have been in the works, but that he staved it off. `` I was ready for a shakeup,'' the official recalled. `` In the beginning, there was really a tense moment when, in discussing the agenda, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> -LRB- first secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- suggested including the current situation in the country.'' That would have turned the plenum into a tribunal passing judgment on perestroika. But the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> member said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> shortcircuited the proposal: `` Immediately, it alerted everyone, as if something really big was going to happen and <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> was no more than a pawn in someone else's game. But at that very moment, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> put the motion to a vote, saying: ` Do n't these questions we are going to discuss embrace the current situation?''' Only <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> voted in favor, the source said. `` That put everyone at ease, and the plenum proceeded as planned,'' he said. Other party chieftains, including <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Gidaspov </PERSON>, criticized the Politburo for reacting slowly to events, the greater openness in Soviet society or <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s failure to stem pro-independence movements in the Baltic and ethnic clashes and separatist drives in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION>, the source said. <PERSON> Toome </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Noorte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Haal </ORGANIZATION> `` about 30 people'' in the <ORG