o be considered when you deal with the question of German reunification. These things have to be considered and dealt with.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> will have breakfast with <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> on Tuesday, ceremonially sign the city's Golden Book, and make a low-key visit to the Berlin Wall, the concrete Cold War symbol of East-West division. Millions of East Germans have passed through the wall in the month since the Communist government lifted travel restrictions. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> then will make a speech to the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> press club in which he is expected to elaborate on his theme that German reunification should be anchored to the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organiyation </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and the 1975 <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> Agreement signed by 32 European countries, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. He said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration would like to see reunification develop in a peaceful and productive way `` Working together with all of our allies, and that includes the <LOCATION> Federal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>, and taking into consideration the concerns of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s neighbors, we can have influence on the process,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. He agreed with a reporter's suggestion that the upheaval in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> comes partly from the streets and may not be manageable by the superpowers. `` But we are doing, I think, what we should be doing, and what is responsible under the circumstances.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said.
