<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Students have turned the tables on the secret police and are keeping 24-hour watch on state security headquarters. Three students hovered close to the entrance of the police headquarters on <LOCATION> Bartolomejska </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> on Monday, serving their time on the front lines in a psychological war against the despised security force. For decades the shadowy force, known as the <ORGANIZATION> STB </ORGANIZATION>, threatened, blackmailed and used every means imaginable to control and silence citizens. A network of vicious spies and informers, the <ORGANIZATION> STB </ORGANIZATION> wove a web of phone taps and bugs and cameras set up on street corners throughout <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>. But everything in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> has suddenly been turned upside down, and those who not long ago were behind bars as dissidents are now leading the nation as ministers. <PERSON> Jiri </PERSON> <PERSON> Dienstbier </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carnogursky </PERSON>, two former dissidents, on Sunday became members of the cabinet and <PERSON> Carnogursky </PERSON> joined a three-man commission overseeing the police. Once interrogated, they now will have some questions of their own. Student leaders warn that when the locked drawers are finally opened, thousands of incriminating files may be missing. In the Moravian town of <LOCATION> Brno </LOCATION>, students began keeping an eye on police Friday after accusing them of burning documents in a nearby forest, a charge reported by the state news agency <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION>. `` To say openly what they may be trying to do is the greatest danger to a group that operates in secrecy,'' said student spokeswoman <PERSON> Monica </PERSON> <PERSON> Bajerova </PERSON>. `` Every citizen will be watching. `` The surveillance in <LOCATION> Brno </LOCATION> and here is part of the pressure we want to put on to keep the secret police under control,'' she said. But the police plead innocence. <PERSON> Jiri </PERSON> <PERSON> Bitcanek </PERSON>, chief of uniformed police for <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bohemia </LOCATION>, denied in an interview with Western reporters that any documents have been removed from his office. Trouble is, Bitcanek only took the job four days ago. His predecessor abruptly found a new career. Bitcanek voluteered to interview in place of the head of secret police. He said he did not know who was now head of the furtive force since the former chief was removed last week. He confessed that morale among his comrades has hit a new low and that the force is in shambles. `` You have to realize that this is a corps set up along military lines and that right now we are not receiving any orders,'' he said, while chanting from a small street demonstration drifted through his office window. <PERSON> Bitcanek </PERSON> said police, especially secret police, were only following orders from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> hierarchy. Now they're being held responsible `` I went down to talk to the students when they came on Friday. They photographed me,'' <PERSON> Bitcanek </PERSON> complained. `` They were taking pictures of every person who came in or out of our building.'' `` I asked them to stop. I do n't havu any guarantee that a picture of a policeman in this emotionally charged, psychotic atmosphere will not be used against the agent or his family,'' he said. The police, who are estimated to number over 100,000, are just the latest security force to come under citizen attack. On Dec. 2, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> disarmed its paramilitary force, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Militia </ORGANIZATION>. On Dec. 7, Defense Minister <PERSON> Miroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Vacek </PERSON> gave his assurance to opposition leader <PERSON> Vaclev </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> that the army, estimated by Western experts at 145,000, would never be used against the citizens. Despite such assurances, many Czechoslovaks suffer the psychic scars of the last 40 years and are finding it hard to shed their fears. They remember philosopher <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Patocka </PERSON>, the guiding spirit of the human rights group Charter 77, who died after eight hours of police interrogation 12 years ago. `` We are still nervous,'' said a 32-year-old writer who requested he not be identified. `` Maybe we are demanding too much too fast. Will the secret police stand for this?'' A student in front of the station on Monday said they did n't have any choice: `` Now it's not the Soviets, it is the people who are here.
