<FIRST>u w AM-Children-Services     12-11 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children-Services,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS, Crack and Homelessness Contribute to Rise in Foster Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Homelessness, AIDS and crack cocaine are overwhelming child welfare services nationwide and are contributing to a growing number of children in foster care, a congressional report said Monday. The report issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> majority on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Families </ORGANIZATION> said federal funding for major children's services, especially those designed to keep children in their homes, has not kept pace with the problem. `` This is <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s legacy to the 1990s,'' Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., committee chairman, said at a news conference `` This was the prescription for the 1980s and it's been a complete disaster.'' Social workers can not keep up with huge caseloads, and children are being placed on waiting lists rather than given services, he said. `` It means we are devastating hundreds of thousands of children ... These children are becoming candidates for long-term dependency on our social welfare system,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` We're really talking here about he candidates' school for future penetentiary residents.'' The report estimates that the number of children placed in foster care, juvenile detention centers and mental health facilities has grown to nearly 500,000 and could reach 840,000 by 1995. The report said its survey of 11 large states showed the number of children in foster care dropped by 9 percent between 1980 and 1985. However, the number rose 23 percent between 1985 and 1988, while federal funding for child welfare services aimed at keeping children in their homes rose 7 percent, according to the report. The number of children in public and private juvenile detention centers rose 27 percent from 1979 to 1987, as funding under the Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Prevention Act declined from $ 100 million in fiscal 1979 to $ 66.7 million in fiscal 1989, the report said. The number of children in mental health facilities soared 60 percent between 1983 and 1986, the report said. Federal block grants for mental health services provided $ 503 million to the states in fiscal 1989, $ 17 million less than the sum of programs consolidated into block grants in 1981, it said. The states surveyed were <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Among the reasons cited for the increases in foster placements and detentions was drug and alcohol abuse. The number of babies born `` drug-exposed'' reached 375,000 in 1988, a number that has quadrupled in the last three years, the report said. It also said reports of abused or neglected children rose 82 percent to 2.2 million between 1981 and 1988. Also, requests for shelter for homeless families rose 18 percent from 1987 to 1988, said the report, citing a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION> report. Republicans on the committee disputed the Democrats' projection that out-of-home placements for children will jump 73 percent over the next five years. They took issue with the report's methods of calculating the projection and basing it on an 11-state survey. `` Our concern is that the numbers are so unreliable that the message will be dismissed,'' their statement said. The dissenters said more nationwide information is needed on adoption and foster care, and they blamed the states for some of the problems in the system. Four different <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> reports have shown states have failed to implement procedures and protections established by the federal government to protect children, they said.
</TEXT>
