<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three Christian militiamen were wounded in a shootout with Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s troops on a highway Monday, sending commuters fleeing for cover and underscoring growing friction between Christian forces. Police said the three wounded men belonged to <PERSON> Samir </PERSON> <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON>'s 6,000-member Lebanese Forces, which favors an Arab League-brokered peace plan to end <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 14-year-old civil war A quarrel developed over traffic rights in the afternoon rush hour, police said. A Lebanese Forces jeep tried to overtake an army patrol at the <LOCATION> Death </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> intersection of the main coastal highway in east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. `` Militiamen in the jeep opened up with submachine guns at the patrol. The soldiers retaliated by tossing a hand grenade that blew up the jeep,'' said a police spokesman who can not be identified under standing rules. Hundreds of motorists in the bumper-to-bumper traffic panicked. Many crashed into others' cars and then leaped out to duck for cover, leaving their doors ajar, the spokesman said. It took traffic police half an hour to remove the three victims to hospital and restore order on the highway, the spokesman added. `` The incident appeared spontaneous, but the underlying tension between the two sides is unmistakable,'' the spokesman said. The Lebanese Forces and <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s army have been on a collision course since the general rejected the Arab peace plan under which a new president, <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Hrawi </PERSON>, was elected Nov. 24. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> rejected the plan for not specifying when Syrian troops would leave <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hrawi </PERSON> has fired <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> from all his posts. But the general is holding out with 20,000 loyal troops in the presidential palace, located in the Christian enclave. <PERSON> Hrawi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> and <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> are all Maronites, the Christian sect that has dominated power in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> since it gained independence from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1943. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> has rejected <PERSON> Hrawi </PERSON>'s presidency, calling him a `` Syrian puppet'' because he was elected by <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in an area controlled by the Syrian army in east <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The Syrians moved in reinforcements two weeks ago and have threatened to evict <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> by force from the <LOCATION> Baabda </LOCATION> place, five miles east of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. But tens of thousands of supporters have since formed a human wall around the hilltop palace in a massive display of pro-Aoun sentiment in the 310-square-mile Christian enclave. <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> has declared his militia would fight alongside <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s army if the enclave was attacked by the Syrians, who maintain 40,000 troops in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> But <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON> also made it plain in televised speeches to his supporters that he recognizes <PERSON> Hrawi </PERSON>'s legitimacy, always referring to him as `` President <PERSON> Hrawi </PERSON>.''
