<HEAD>Grand Jury Epected To Review 1963 Slaying Of Civil Rights Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A grand jury that convened Monday is expected to make a preliminary examination of evidence in the 1963 slaying of civil rights leader <PERSON> Medgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Evers </PERSON>. However, <LOCATION> Hinds </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Attorney </LOCATION> <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> has said he expects no indictment by this grand jury in the Evers slaying. Prosecutors say they are continuing to investigate the killing and could present more evidence to a later grand jury. `` In fact that is probably what is going to happen,'' said Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLaughter </PERSON>. `` All we wanted to do with this grand jury is advise them what has happened. It does n't mean we are quitting We have to start somewhere, sometime, and this is it.'' <PERSON> Evers </PERSON>, field director of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colored </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION>, was shot to death June 12, 1963, outside his <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> home. White supremacist <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Greenwood </PERSON> fertilizer salesman, was tried twice in <ORGANIZATION> Hinds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1964. Two all-white juries were unable to reach verdicts and the charge was dropped. Newspaper reports on Oct. 1 said he state's defunct segregation spy agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Sovereignty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, had screened potential jurors for <PERSON> Be