ave been able to demonstrate without police interference for the first time in more than 40 years, and independent groups have been allowed to function. At Monday's evening vigil, a woman caught up in an emotional debate said Bulgarians were willing to stand there around the clock until the leadership acted on reform. She and others said they believed <PERSON> Mladenov </PERSON>'s promises of change, but wanted a democracy anchored in law. `` Democracy and socialism are not compatible,'' she declared. An old man spoke of change in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, then said: `` We are a bit late, but we will catch up because we are persistent.'' State radio quoted <PERSON> Mladenov </PERSON>, formerly foreign minister, as telling the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> he favored broad dialogue with all `` who support a state of law in the framework of socialism.'' An overwhelming show of hands at Sunday's rally approved a resolution sponsored by 19 unofficial groups demanding abolition of the constitution's first paragraph, which enshrines the leading party role in <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mladenov </PERSON> has described the power monopoly as open to question and <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukanov </PERSON>, his No. 2 man, said last week the party could not claim such an exclusive right. The party daily, <PERSON> Rabotnichesko </PERSON> <PERSON> Delo </PERSON>, already had reported calls for an early congress, the only party forum that can elect a new Central Committee. It said more than 4,000 letters and telephone calls demanding reforms had been received since <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON> was dismissed. An opinion poll ordered by the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and published by the paper said only 23 percent of those responding expressed great trust in the party and only 32 percent indicated trust in any political organization. <PERSON> Rabotnichesko </PERSON> <PERSON> Delo </PERSON> said 1,513 people were questioned Nov. 28 in 127 work collectives. It concluded little trust existed because official organizations, including the party, had `` discredited themselves in the eyes of the people'' and independent groups had not been tested. The party paper said one-third of those polled said they wanted a multiparty political system, 68.9 percent supported a system based on law and 77.7 percent said economic reform was imperative.
