<HEAD>Michigan Civil Rights Commission Proposes Changes for Campuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY L. ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> colleges and universities should develop a `` zero tolerance'' policy and require a course in ethnic relations to improve campus race relations, the <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> recommended Monday. The recommendations stemmed from the commission's discussions with administrators, students and faculty from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ferris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> universities. `` It is our hope that universities will look at these recommendations as a guide and use them to implement a program of this sort on their campus,'' <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> said at a commission meeting. Racial tensions rose on several campuses this year. Sit-ins were held at <ORGANIZATION> Ferris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> State </PERSON> universities. Students demanded racial sensitivity from staff and other students, and policies against individuals who commit racist acts. The `` zero tolerance'' policy would define unlawful and unacceptable acts of racism, and authorize punishments. The ethnic-relations class would be required for all freshman to sensitize individuals to racial issues and concerns. At least seven <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> universities already require such a class. An official at one <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> institution said he did n't believe a course would solve the racial problems. `` I believe race relations should be spread around in all courses, not stuffed into one,'' <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Diether </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haenicke </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> said some <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> schools already are implementing programs. `` MSU is scheduled to begin its ethnic-relations class in 1992,'' he said. `` We would hope that they would begin earlier than that.'' <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Duderstadt </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rapids </ORGANIZATION> on Monday that all universities have a responsibility to strive for ethnic diversification because the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will become increasingly multicultural in the next century. He said he believes his school has made `` remarkable progress'' in reducing racial tension through minority recruiting. The recommendations also included setting up procedures to process discrimination complaints, developing and distributing a booklet for students on their civil rights, and periodic reviews of campus policies and their success. `` Through a concerted effort, we can develop programs that not only reduce current tension, but also prevent future unlawful acts of harassment from occurring,'' state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> said.
