<HEAD>Residents Raise Crosses in Defiance of Atheist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUCONDA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An atheist forced village officials to remove lighted crosses from two water towers, but residents are fighting back with scores of home-made crosses in businesses, front yards and windows. Christmas spirit and town unity have never been stronger, residents of this community 30 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> said Monday. `` We felt very badly that this man could come in here that does n't even live here, and say that we had to stop a tradition we've been doing for years,'' said <PERSON> Katie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolter </PERSON>. `` This is people's way of speaking out. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> official of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atheists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, contends the two disputed crosses _ which sat atop the village water towers for almost 40 years and traditionally were lighted for the Christmas season _ represented an unconstitutional mingling of church and state. He threatened to sue the village if the crosses, removed last winter for repairs, were used this Christmas season. The village board decided Nov. 21 to replace them with lighted stars rather than risk a costly legal battle. <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> said the board's decision was a `` smashing victory'' for <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atheists </ORGANIZATION>, which has challenged the use of crosses and nativity scenes on public property across the country. `` This is the first time in the history of this country that illuminated Christian crosses have been forced down from government property without necessitating a lawsuit,'' said <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON>, of the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION>. But if there are no crosses on the water towers, they've sprung up nearly everywhere else as the community of about 6,000 counters the move. One of the first appeared on top of Mers Restaurant, a block from the towers. `` When you see the crosses up, it's Christmas time,'' said restaurant co-owner <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Mers </PERSON>, a lifelong village resident. `` I'm still kind of upset that it's not on the tower I grew up with it.'' Hand-made crosses have appeared at Ms. <PERSON> Wolter </PERSON>'s jewelry store and other businesses and homes at the urging of Mayor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Keagle </PERSON> and others. The Rev. <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Maher </PERSON> has counted 95 crosses `` in just a fifth of my parish'' since he exhorted his congregation at the <ORGANIZATION> Transfiguration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> to show their faith. `` Some are on the homes, some are in the yards, some are in the windows, some people have used their TV antennas to make crosses _ they've put lights on them,'' <PERSON> Maher </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennebeck </PERSON>, vice president of Performance Paving, scaled a 110-foot telephone pole at his business to attach a 12-foot lighted cross near the top that he hopes will mark a new tradition. The effect is not just visual, <PERSON> Maher </PERSON> said. `` Many people have come and told me that there's never been such unity and Christmas spirit as there's been now,'' he said. <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> said he thinks the response is more a show of resentment toward atheists than a display of Christian faith or Christmas spirit. <PERSON> Maher </PERSON> disputes that. `` It's not attacking him at all, it is showing our Christianity,'' the priest said. `` In fact, we've got countless people here praying for him.''
