<HEAD>Czechoslovaks Ring Freedom Bells; Look for President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with former official accused, details; edits
to trip. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos XPRA1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A joyous cacophony of bells and whistles heralded a popular victory over the Communists, and Czechoslovaks settled down Monday to choosing a president from among heroes the old order called villains. A presidential contest appeared to be developing, and the people may get to decide. `` This is the end of communism!'' exulted <PERSON> Jana </PERSON> <PERSON> Navara </PERSON>, an actress in pink mukluks, adding the sound of a brass chime to the bells of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Tyn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> on Old Town Square. Her 3-year-old daughter made a triumphant `` V'' with two tiny fingers. The brief blast of noise replaced a threatened general strike, canceled after events brought to power the first government in 41 years not dominated by Communists and drove President <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Husak </PERSON> from office. Soldiers began removing barbed wire from the border with neutral <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> radio reported plans to disband Pacem im <PERSON> Terris </PERSON>, a state-controlled organization of Roman Catholic clergy. Priests outside the group often were persecuted as the state tried to impose its will. In the first official act against members of the old leadership, the prosecutor charged former party ideologue <PERSON> Vasil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilak </PERSON> for his part in crushing the 1968 <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> spring of reform, the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> reported. `` According to some opinions, his deeds can be considered treason,'' it said, but added that <PERSON> Bilak </PERSON>, now 72, could not be tried because the statute of limitations had run out. Elsewhere in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>: _ <PERSON> Petar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mladenov </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Bulgarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said free elections should be held in May and a new constitution written that does not guarantee the party a monopoly on power. _ The four Allies of World War II held their first meeting in 18 years Monday and stressed the need for stability at a time of rapid change in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. It was requested by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which is concerned about German reunification. _ More than 150,000 people held a pro-democracy rally in <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION>, a southern industrial city in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and many called for German unity. In <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> meets Tuesday and has two weeks to elect a president, but the Club of Communist Deputies, similar to a majority party caucus, said Monday it would support a referendum. A statement from the club said it would `` recommend to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> to adopt the necessary measures for an all-people's vote'' because `` the authority of the head of state is so important that only the people can decide,'' <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> reported. Earlier, Politburo member <PERSON> Ondrej </PERSON> <PERSON> Saling </PERSON> said the Communists and opposition had agreed the president should be a Czech with no party affiliation. `` In my view, the president must be someone who enjoys broad support and guarantees stability,'' he said. That seemed to suggest <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, the playwright who was jailed for opposing communism and is now the driving force behind Civic Forum, the main opposition. Posters reading `` Havel na Hrad'' _ `` <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> to the Castle,'' the presidential residence _ sprouted all over <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>. The candicacy of <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, who led the 1968 reform as party chief until Soviet tanks arrived, threw the result into doubt, however, and other names were being mentioned. In a late-evening television interview with Soviet television, shown in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> said he would keep his country in the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact. While evoking an ideal of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> `` as a peaceful community'' with no military blocs, he said `` we shall not get any closer to this ideal by any kind of individual split from the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> treaty,'' <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>'s gravelly voice rolled over a crowd of 100,000 people Sunday in <LOCATION> Wenceslas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. As he listed popular victories over the past three weeks, which the people had come to celebrate, they chanted `` We want Havel!'' and he made a very presidential bow. <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, 68, remains a popular symbol but evokes little emotion among younger Czechoslovaks, who regard him as a product of the system they intend to abolish. He also is a Slovak, as is <PERSON> Marian </PERSON> <PERSON> Calfa </PERSON>, the new premier. <PERSON> Calfa </PERSON> has said a political tradition, under which one office is held by a Slovak and the other by a Czech, would be respected. <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> joins <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in forming an administration not dominated by Communists, but unlike <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, its government is led by a member of the party. `` We have not won yet,'' <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> told the Sunday rally, which was televised live. But, he added, `` The years-long, deadly silence of a humiliated people has been drowned out by a multivoiced popular choir.'' A rally in support of <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> was held Monday at <LOCATION> Plzen </LOCATION>, west of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, and many Czechoslovaks ringing bells around the country also wore the ubiquitous blue, red and white `` Havel for President'' buttons. The burst of bell-ringing occurred three weeks to the day after students rose up, angered by brutal police assaults on peaceful demonstrators. They surged through the streets of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, stopping street cars to sound their bells, then everyone joined in. Soon afterward, a liberty bell appeared on a hill above <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> where a statue of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> once had been. In letters visible across the <LOCATION> Vltava </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, it was labeled, `` The final bell,'' the last line of every Czechoslovak fairy tale.
