<HEAD>Arens Demands U.S. Guarantees Before Talks, 14 Arabs Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with West Bank schools ordered to remain closed.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign Minister <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Arens </PERSON> said Monday <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> wants guarantees from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> will have no role in the peace process before he attends talks in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. No date has been set for the meeting between <PERSON> Arens </PERSON>, Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and Egyptian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Esmet </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel-Meguid </PERSON>. The three will discuss the composition of a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> delegation to direct talks with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials. In violence Monday in the occupied territories, troops shot and wounded 14 Palestinian protesters, Arab hospital officials said. The army said it was investigating. <PERSON> Arens </PERSON> cast some doubt Monday on his planned trip to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, saying he is concerned about reports that <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> is acting as a `` postman'' for the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. `` The Egyptians, who started the process as an independent factor, have lately presented themselves as, in effect, a postman for the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Arens </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION>. `` If this is what will be, I fear that we wo n't get very far.'' Last month, the Cabinet linked Israeli acceptance of <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s proposal for the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> meeting to assurances that the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> would play no part in the peace process Asked about the proposed <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> trip, <PERSON> Arens </PERSON> said, `` Firstly, I'm not going yet. We will first conduct contacts concerning the guarantees that our Cabinet has requested.'' Cabinet Secretary <PERSON> Eliakim </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> is scheduled to go to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this week to discuss the assurances sought by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Avi </PERSON> <PERSON> Pazner </PERSON>, a spokesman for Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>. The latest hitch in the talks followed weekend news reports that Israeli, Egyptian, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> officials were holding secret contacts to draw up a preliminary list of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> negotiators. The clashes Monday were sparked by the fatal shootings Sunday of two Palestinians, apparently by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> civilians who opened fired after their cars were stoned, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reports said. The deaths raised to 631 the number of Palestinians killed by Israelis during the two-year uprising against Israeli rule. At least 155 other Palestinians have been killed by their fellow Arabs who accused them of cooperating with Israeli authorities or involvement in prostitution or drug-dealing. Forty-three Israelis also have died. In <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, a military court sentenced four Palestinian men to prison terms ranging from 10 to 14 years for throwing firebombs at military patrols in April 1989, a military spokesman said. No one was injured in the attacks. In <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, police said they detained for questioning at least 21 Palestinian youths after the funeral of 17-year-old <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Muneir </PERSON> turned into a nationalist demonstration. <PERSON> Muneir </PERSON>'s family claims he died Sunday as a result of beatings by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers, but a police investigation reported he died of natural causes. About 500 Arab youths marched behind <PERSON> Muneir </PERSON>'s coffin, singing the Palestinian national anthem and waving the outlawed red, white, black and green Palestinian flag. Nearly 100 police and paramilitary border policemen stood guard. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s military administration of the occupied territories ordered the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> UNRWA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- to keep the 90 schools it operates for Palestinian refugees in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> closed until the new academic year begins Jan. 10. A spokesman for the administration said all 930 schools in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> will remain closed until then. The schools have been closed since the school year ended Nov. 1. <ORGANIZATION> UNRWA </ORGANIZATION> had announced its schools would reopen Monday to give students a chance to complete the past academic year. The students were unable to complete the full year because many schools have been closed frequently during the uprising.
