<HEAD>Peru in Pact with International Monetary Fund</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After four years of disagreements, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday it has reached an accord with <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> that could mean financial aid for the country if Peruvian policies meet its approval. An official of the fund, who spoke on condition he not be named, said <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> had made a payment of $ 42.3 million the $ 800 million it owes the fund. The payment covers only the arrears since September of this year. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> has been in trouble with lenders since President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> was elected in 1985 and announced that he would make only partial payments of interest on the country's debts. At that time <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> owed $ 14 billion abroad. Now the figure is closer to $ 20 billion. Its financial troubles have been worsened by the continuing rebellion of a strong leftist group, the Shining Path, and a thriving traffic in drugs. Owned by 152 governments, the fund negotiates at length with those in financial trouble. It gives its help only when the borrowing government agrees on a set of policies it approves. Usually these include cuts in government spending, especially on official payrolls and subsidies, and often a devaluation of the country's currency. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> is one of 10 countries with a total arrears of $ 3.5 billion to the fund, and so ineligible for more finanical aid from it _ and in practice, unlikely to get much from anyone else. This year the fund started a series of what it called `` shadow programs,'' under which governments promised new policies but got no immediate money. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Guayana </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> and now <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> have started such programs. If the fund finds they are doing well after a year or so, they will start getting its financial help.
