<HEAD>Bush Calls Drunken Driving a `Scourge' of the Age</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf Sullivan comment after 6th graf pvs, Skinner
said</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, calling drunken driving `` one of the most deadly scourges'' of our times, promised Monday to keep up pressures to get intoxicated drivers off the road. His transportation secretary suggested new restrictions on alcohol advertising may be necessary. Their comments came at a briefing at the White House for 150 anti-drunken driving activists plus health and safety officials. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> signed legislation declaring this National Drunk and Drugged Driving Awareness Week and issued a proclamation saying, `` As we prepare to celebrate the holidays and rejoice in the promise of the new year, it is fitting that we pause to remember the perils of drinking and driving.'' Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> was peppered with questions before <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spoke about why the government does not raise excise taxes on alcohol to discourage drinking and does not restrict brewers' and liquor manufacturers' ads. `` I'm not so sure it is n't time to revisit those issues'' of regulating advertising, said <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said people are `` not going to stop drinking,'' but said they must be stopped `` from getting behind the steering wheel.'' Health Secretary <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> was more direct, telling the briefing that the nation should `` consider some form of restrictions on the advertising of alcoholic beverages.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the public outcry in recent years against drunken drivers has been `` one of the most amazing success stories of the 1980s.'' Drunken driving deaths fell 20 percent in the last six years, although the number of miles traveled rose 25 percent, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Still, almost 500,000 Americans are injured in alcohol-related accidents and half the 50,000 fatalities on <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s highways each year are alcohol-related, `` an annual toll that would nearly fill the polished granite walls of the Vietnam Memorial,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. He called drunken driving `` one of the most deadly scourges ever to strike modern times. And it's as crippling as crack, as random as gang violence. And it's killing more kids than both combined.'' To those who have crusaded against drunken driving, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` speaking not only as president, but as a father and as a grandfather, you have my respect, my admiration and my thanks.'' On <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, meanwhile, a <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> senator urged motorists to turn on their headlights for three hours on the last day of December to remind other drivers not to drink and drive on New Year's Eve. `` And it will be a memorial to all those victims of drunk driving who will not be with us to celebrate the dawn of the new decade,'' Sen. <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON>, R-Ky., said at a news conference
