up 8th `Calls for'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEIPZIG, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 150,000 people rallied for democracy in this southern industrial city Monday night, with shouting matches breaking out for a fourth straight week over whether <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> should reunite. `` We in <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION> and those in <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> -RRB- are and will remain Germans,'' one speaker said, to roared approval from some and boos from others. `` What belongs together will grow together.'' ADN, the official news agency, said 40,000 people demonstrated at <LOCATION> Karl-Marx-Stadt </LOCATION> for a referendum on reunification before elections planned in May. It said the crowd also demanded that cells of the discredited <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> be disbanded by Dec. 15. Other rallies took place in <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neubrandenburg </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Halle </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Potsdam </LOCATION>, the agency reported. It said the <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION> crowd also divided on the reunification issue. It was the fourth week <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> unity was a central issue of <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION>'s regular Monday night rally. Dozens of West German flags waved in the crowd. Some demonstrators carried signs saying `` No Fourth Reich'' and urging East Germans not to let their country become a West German `` plantation.'' `` There are two real movements now,'' said a young woman opposed to reunification. `` It's too bad it's come to this.'' In <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> ZDF </ORGANIZATION> television said: `` The fear of a deep division within the opposition is huge, because of the different goals.'' Throughout the evening, protesters on both sides shouted at each other. Reunification has become an increasingly bitter topic for <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s New Forum opposition group, which sponsors the <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION> rallies. New Forum says reunification would mean a `` sellout'' to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Calls for and against German unity were not the only demands. Many demonstrators warned fellow East Germans against `` attacks and taking law into their own hands.'' As they press their beleaguered government to carry through with promises of reforms, East Germans have increasingly been swept up in a frenzy to root out corruption, leading to many warnings against the use of violence. Monday night's protest was sponsored by the 200,000-member New Forum, the nation's largest opposition group. The organization said Monday it will take part as a political party in the nation's first free election, slated for May 6, and will hope to form its own parliamentary group. A national congress of New Forum to launch the group as a party will be held in <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION> on Jan. 6-7. Another opposition group, <PERSON> Demokratischer </PERSON> <PERSON> Aufbruch </PERSON>, which means democratic `` start'' or `` awakening,'' called on the government to pass immediate regulations allowing foreign companies to transfer their profits out of the country and that would guarantee protection of investments. Earlier Monday, the official East German news agency <ORGANIZATION> ADN </ORGANIZATION> said new <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Gregor </PERSON> <PERSON> Gysi </PERSON> spoke by telephone with Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and that the two men had agreed to meet soon. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> praised the party's `` rejection of attempts to damage the sovereignty of the country,'' <ORGANIZATION> ADN </ORGANIZATION> said. The questions of East German sovereignty have become increasingly important with the growing turmoil in the Communist nation. There have been predictions the rapid changes could lead to steps toward unification with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is watching the East German situation with `` extraordinary attention'' and promised <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> would consider providing support `` within the current framework of conditions.'' <PERSON> Gysi </PERSON> said he is counting on Soviet backing in rebuilding the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and enacting democratic reform, <ORGANIZATION> ADN </ORGANIZATION> said. ADN did not specify a date for their meeting.
