<HEAD>Judge Approves Desegregation Settlement, Blasts School Districts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON FOURNIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge on Monday approved the $ 130 million settlement of the largest desegregation case in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> history, but blasted school districts for suggesting the money be used to retire debts. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>, saying it was `` abundantly clear'' the parties in the case could not be trusted with the money, ordered it put in an escrow account monitored by a court-appointed supervisor. `` The amount of money is meager enough,'' <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> wrote in his opinion. The judge also scaled back <ORGANIZATION> NACCP </ORGANIZATION> attorneys' fees in the case from $ 3.15 million to $ 850,000. The settlement ends seven years of litigation involving the state, three school districts in <LOCATION> Pulaski </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, which includes <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, and black students' parents. The Little Rock School District, which is mostly black, sued the state and the neighboring, mostly white <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pulaski </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> districts, alleging the defendants caused illegal segregation in Little Rock schools. The settlement was reached in March. In a special session in July, the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> agreed to spend $ 129.75 million over 10 years for desegregation programs. Woods on Monday endorsed the agreement as approved Oct. 4 by Special Master <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> McCutcheon </PERSON>. Attorneys for the county and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> districts had objected to revisions recommended by <PERSON> McCutcheon </PERSON>, saying the court should accept the settlement intact. <PERSON> McCutcheon </PERSON> recommended that the court have the right to order the construction or repair of magnet schools and that court forbid the districts from spending settlement money to retire deficits unrelated to desegregation. <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> said Monday that the districts had no right to challenge the court's jurisdiction because they'd failed to draft a constitutional student assignment plan. `` That the districts would default in their responsibilities, then attempt to bind this court by ` bargaining' with each other as to what remedies the court-appointed expert could or could not use, is incredible,'' he said. `` The parties have bound themselves. There is a settlement.'' <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> said his major objection was the North Little Rock and the <LOCATION> Pulaski </LOCATION> districts' suggestion that the money could be used to pay off debts. <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>, however, ruled that the <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> district had $ 5.5 million in debts attributed to desegregation that could be paid with settlement money and that the <LOCATION> Pulaski </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> district had $ 1.4 million in such debts. The judge refused to grant $ 2.3 million in attorneys' fees the settlement assigned to the Legal Defense Fund of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People. He said the <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> district should n't pay $ 2 million to the defense fund because the district played the leading role in pressing the lawsuit, no substantial documents or time records were filed to support the claims, and the defense fund tried to recoup fees going back to 1957. In 1957, then-Gov. <PERSON> Orval </PERSON> <PERSON> Faubus </PERSON> refused to allow nine black students to enter <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>'s all-white Central High School. President <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> ordered federal troops to Central High to keep the peace and enforce court-ordered desegregation.
