<HEAD>Croatia Joins Slovenia in Asking that Yugoslavia Go Multiparty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION>, the second largest state in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, for the first time demanded Monday that a multiparty political system be set up in this communist country. Until now, the liberal northern state of <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> had been the only one of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six constituent republics to openly advocate introduction of Western-style democracy. The Communist leadership of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, the most populous state with 42 percent of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s 23 million people, vigorously opposes the change. <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION> has about 20 percent of the population. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Monday that it was worried by rising tensions in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> and urged the people to unite in support of the reform efforts of Prime Minister Ante <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON>. <PERSON> Stanko </PERSON> <PERSON> Stojicevic </PERSON>, head of the Croatian <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling presidium -LRB- Politburo -RRB-, said Monday that Communists have been slow in realizing the `` historic exhaustion of the single-party system.'' In a keynote speech opening a regional party congress in the Croatian capital of <LOCATION> Zagreb </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Stojicevic </PERSON> said, `` There can be no democratic socialism without political pluralism based on the right of association and competition of political -LRB- movements -RRB- and programs.'' The speech was carried by the state news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION>. About a dozen independent movements and parties have been set up in <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> the past year, and the region plans to hold its first free legislative elections next March. About 25,000 Croatians in several cities signed a petition Sunday urging legalization of numerous parties that would make it possible to hold free elections in the Croatian republic, which borders <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>. In an apparent move to stifle growing democratic trends in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> this month cut all business and official ties with <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>. The action shook the foundations of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s loose federal system <PERSON> Stojicevic </PERSON> denounced <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s break with <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>, describing the consequences as `` dramatic with a possibly catastrophic outcome.'' He said, `` Ultimatums and the severance of economic relations, accusations and threats represent a direct attack on the constitutional order of the country and its economic and political integrity.'' Slovenian President <PERSON> Janez </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanovnik </PERSON> told the region's parliament on Monday that <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s move dealt a `` heavy blow to the Yugoslav federation'' and was meant to `` eliminate all those who hold differing opinions and to produce a change of the constitutional order.' At a session devoted exclusively to the break, <PERSON> Stanovnik </PERSON> told deputies, `` The blockade of <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>, therefore, represents an act of aggression against <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>.'' In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> deputy spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> said when when asked about ethnic problems in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>: `` We are greatly concerned by the growing tensions and conflicts among the republics and national groups that make up <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. Mutual respect, adherence to democratic principles, and a commitment to avoiding violence are crucial to resolving this situation. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supports and will continue to support a united federal <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> in which human rights and civil rights of all citizens are protected. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> strongly supports the ongoing efforts of ... Prime Minister <PERSON> Markovich </PERSON> to create a market-based economy and to promote greater political pluralism. We urge all Yugoslavs to put aside their differences and to focus their energies on this important reform effort.''
