 A Canadian naval destroyer Monday fired a shot across the bow of an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> scalloper that allegedly rammed it three times, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officials said. The 366-foot destroyer Sagueny fired a 3-inch round at 6:52 p.m. near <LOCATION> George </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> after chasing the 114-foot scalloper <ORGANIZATION> Concordia </ORGANIZATION> for eight hours, said Petty Officer <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON>. The Concordia did not stop or attempt to make radio contact after the warning shot was fired, said <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON>. She said the vessel continued to steam west towards <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION> and its home port of <LOCATION> Fairhaven </LOCATION>. The Sagueny followed it until 8:50 p.m., when it entered <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> waters. The scalloper was allegedly spotted fishing 2.5 miles across the <LOCATION> Hague </LOCATION> fisheries line by a Canadian aircraft, said <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON>. The Hague line divides <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Canadian waters was established by the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1984. There have been several reports this year of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> fishing boats crossing the line to the rich fishing area on the Canadian side. Lt. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Maybee </PERSON>, a Canadian Forces spokesman, said the <PERSON> Sagueny </PERSON> began tracking the <ORGANIZATION> Concordia </ORGANIZATION> after it was spotted fishing in Canadian waters on five occasions during the weekend. The smaller boat allegedly disregarded radio messages before it `` eventually turned toward <LOCATION> Sagueny </LOCATION> and stuck the right rear quarter three times,'' <PERSON> Maybee </PERSON> said. No injuries or serious damage were reported. `` Options are being weighed by the political masters in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> as to what the next step should be,'' he said. `` It is all-important that a knee-jerk reaction be avoided.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> was expected to board the craft when it reached <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> waters, <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> said. `` We will document the vessel's catch, check charts and records, and varify the identities of the master and crew,'' she said <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Concordia </ORGANIZATION> will be allowed to proceed to its home port after the boarding was completed, and any further action would have to be initiated by the Canadian government. <PERSON> Maybee </PERSON> declined to detail what kind of punitive action could be taken in the alleged ramming about 130 miles off <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> had no plans to intervene, adding, `` Canadian ships do n't usually pursue the American fishing fleet inside American waters unless they get permission from diplomatic channels.'' `` The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> has been monitoring the situation, abiding its policy of not interfering with Canadian law enforcement.''
