<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said Monday the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> should repeal its `` odious'' 1975 resolution that equates Zionism with racism in an effort to promote the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace process. He also gave Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> a check for $ 65 million in partial payment of major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arrears, an issue that has stirred anti-U.S. sentiment here. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> now owes $ 365 million for the regular budget and $ 153 million for peacekeeping. `` Repealing this resolution would re-establish the stature and moral authority of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> told reporters after a 50-minute meeting with the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief. `` Now is the time to begin discussion on substituting or getting rid of this odious resolution which equates Zionism with racism.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s comments came in answer to questions. The resolution is symbolic and not binding, but has been a sore point with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its ally, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> diplomats said that killing the resolution, or declaring it null and void, could enhance the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace process by removing an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> objection to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> involvement. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> resolution was backed by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> rivals, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOC