thcoming Nicaraguan elections and the Central American peace process. He said he briefed <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> on the <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> meeting. He said he told him `` <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> is becoming more isolated.'' He said Cuban President <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s criticism of perestroika, or reform, in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> `` is an indirect criticism of Soviet President -LRB- <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last week suffered a setback on <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> issues after it threatened to cut off all funding to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> if the world body upgraded the status of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> as an observer state, instead of an observer group. The issue was defused and the question was put off, but anti-U.S. sentiment remains. The General Assembly later adopted a package of pro-PLO, anti-Israel resolutions _ an annual event.
