<HEAD>Kenny Rogers and His Son Star in Christmas Special</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1 of Dec.9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Although `` Christmas in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>: A Love Story'' reflects parts of <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>' own life it was written before he was signed to star in the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> special. The one-hour show on Wednesday tells the story of an internationally famous photographer who reflects on his life and uses the opportunity to heal the wounds between himself and his son. The son felt his father had always put his career ahead of his family. <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION>, although best known as a singer and actor, is also an acclaimed photographer and recently patched up relations with his own son, <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who co-stars in the special as the son. <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> <PERSON> Crow </PERSON> are also in the show. `` We sent him the script to read,'' said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamner </PERSON>, who co-wrote the show with <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Sipes </PERSON>. `` I was delighted when I learned he was not only a photographer but a good photographer. <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> felt he had neglected his own son and had an estrangement.'' <PERSON> Sipes </PERSON> said, `` I think the feeling of the film is one of healing and coming together, which was reflected in <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>'s own relationship with his son.'' When the project got under way <PERSON> Hamner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sipes </PERSON> were asked to come up with a story about four periods in a man's life. `` Don and I came up with the idea of making him a photographer,'' said <PERSON> Hamner </PERSON>. `` That way we could use photos to introduce each period. The first period is childhood, when he becomes interested in photography. The next is young manhood, when he goes off to war and falls in love. Act three is his marriage and family and the development of his career and the conflicts it causes in his personal life. `` The last act is about maturity and reconciliation. It's about regeneration, which is so appropriate for this time of year. An area <PERSON> Don </PERSON> and I wanted to explore is something that is common to all of us in this society. That's the work ethic and how it can cause a man to neglect his family.'' <PERSON> Hamner </PERSON> said he also felt at ease with <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> when he learned that he's a fisherman. <PERSON> Hamner </PERSON> fished the streams of his native <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> for many years before discovering salmon fishing. `` I fish in British <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> now,'' he said. `` I caught a 50-pound fish up there last year. That's a lifetime fish. They canned it for me and the cans arrived just yesterday.'' This is the first collaboration between <PERSON> Hamner </PERSON>, best known for creating `` The Waltons'' and `` Falcon Crest,'' and <PERSON> Sipes </PERSON>, a former entertainment executive and a published novelist. `` We've known each other a long time,'' said <PERSON> Sipes </PERSON>. `` We always discussed writing because we both write. We both collect books and when we meet for lunch we arrange it near a book store. After lunch we'll go and browse for a while. I collect literature and <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> collects Americana.'' <PERSON> Hamner </PERSON> said, `` My dream is to find a rare book and buy it for $ 7.50. But the book store people all know the value of these books.'' Their next collaboration will be `` <LOCATION> Brewster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Place </LOCATION>,'' a half-hour drama for <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> starring <PERSON> Oprah </PERSON> <PERSON> Winfrey </PERSON>. It will be filmed in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, where her talk show is based, and will make its debut in April. They are also working on several cable television projects and wrote a pilot last year for <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>. `` Brewster Place'' is adapted from the book `` The Women of Brewster Place'' and the miniseries that ran on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hamner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sipes </PERSON> are making some changes in the concept because the miniseries presented such a negative image of black men. `` We'll have much more positive images,'' said <PERSON> Sipes </PERSON>. `` We're adding some new characters <PERSON> Oprah </PERSON> will play her character in her late 40s. She'll have to be aged and padded for the part.'' <PERSON> Hamner </PERSON> said he feels the television audience wants the kind of family programming represented by `` Christmas in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' `` The networks want people between 18 and 49,'' he said. `` You cut out a lot of people that way. Suppose you do a ` once upon a time' story. You can attract the 18-49 audience and everyone else, too.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: ` PINK PANTHER' _ Oscar-winning composer <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mancini </PERSON> will score the music for the new CBS series `` The Pink Panther'' that combines live action and animation. <PERSON> Mancini </PERSON> received an Academy Award nomination for composing the music for the first `` Pink Panther'' movie 26 years ago. The series, from <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, stars <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlatter </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Waltz </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dabbs </PERSON> <PERSON> Greer </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Stack </PERSON> and <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>.
