<FIRST>a i PM-Moslems-Rushdie Adv18   12-11 0864</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Moslems-Rushdie, Adv 18,0890</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday PMs, Dec. 18 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Britain's Moslems Split over Response to `The Satanic Verses'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Moslem leaders in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> agree <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> blasphemed their religion in his book, `` The Satanic Verses,'' but they differ sharply on what to do about it. One noted Moslem figure, <PERSON> Hesham </PERSON> <PERSON> El-Essawy </PERSON>, said he wanted to go to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and win a reprieve for the author, but after a <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> newspaper said `` the hanging rope'' awaited him, he stayed in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. A prominent Moslem, <PERSON> Kalim </PERSON> <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON>, supports the death sentence imposed on <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> by the late Iranian leader, <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, and thinks <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> should be hounded perpetually until his book, published 14 months ago, is withdrawn from bookshelves. <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, a Bombay-born Moslem, has been in hiding under police guard since Feb. 14. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> died in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> on June 3, but his edict endures. <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, says <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s edict is unchallengeable and that <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> got `` nothing less than he thoroughly deserved. But while favoring the death decree `` absolutely,'' he says it is `` not for Moslems living in this country to break British law to bring <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> to book.'' El-Essawy, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Promotion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tolerance </ORGANIZATION>, contends that the death sentence contradicts the Koran's teachings. `` As a Moslem, I should really suppress the human response and adopt the religious response, which is, ` Do n't punish him; leave him to God to punish or forgive him as He wishes,''' <PERSON> El-Essawy </PERSON> said in an interview. He planned a lecture tour of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> states in February to dispute <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s edict but canceled it when <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> declined to guarantee his safety and its semi-official newspaper, <PERSON> Kehan </PERSON>, warned he would be hanged. `` The death sentence is really a slur, is something that defames the religion of Islam,'' El-Essawy maintained. `` As long as the man stays in hiding, we'll stand accused of putting him there and keeping him there. We'll be regarded as potential killers.'' <PERSON> El-Essawy </PERSON> said he hoped at least to remove the $ 5.2-million bounty offered by Iranian clerics for <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s assassination, by designating it `` the tactics of gangsters and not worthy of the Islamic republic.'' El-Essawy and <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON> have never met. <PERSON> El-Essawy </PERSON>'s group seeks to identify and correct causes of intolerance toward Moslems. <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON>'s disseminates information on Moslem political thought. <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON>, came to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> in 1954; <PERSON> El-Essawy </PERSON> came from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in 1970. Both are married with three children and both are thoroughly Westernized in appearance. They share an easy humor and a mutual contempt. In a book-lined study at his house in suburban <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON>, 58, dismissed <PERSON> El-Essawy </PERSON> as an apologist. `` Totally idiotic the man is, to put it mildly,'' he said. <PERSON> El-Essawy </PERSON>, 43, seated in his ornamented dentist's office in <LOCATION> Harley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s medical row, said <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON>'s speeches verge on `` incitement to murder, but do n't let me be the judge.'' In October, at a Moslem rally in northern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON> called for a show of hands on whether the death sentence was just and virtually all 250 people in the audience were reported to have raised their hands. A BBC-TV poll published the previous night indicated only 35 percent of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 2 million Moslems were in favor of the death penalty. Police are investigating whether <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON> was guilty of incitement and have obtained a court order forcing the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> to hand over its footage of the rally. <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON> complains the British media portray him `` as a sort of rabble rouser _ the opposite to <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, as it were.'' He says Moslems have no choice but to protest and show that `` anyone who tries to go down the same road as Mr. <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> in the future will be dealt with much more severely.'' <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON> wants <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> and his publishers, <PERSON> Viking </PERSON> <PERSON> Penguin </PERSON>, to withdraw the book and that profits from the 1.2 million copies sold should be shared among relatives of 26 people who died in anti-Rushdie riots in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. `` They should make amends, and then we'll call it a day,'' <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON> said. Otherwise, `` this is going to be an issue in 50 years from now.'' <PERSON> El-Essawy </PERSON> said: `` There is not one single Moslem who is not angered by the book.'' But he thinks <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> might defuse the furor by affixing labels to his book making clear the contents are fictional. He said he met <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> on a train two weeks before the author was driven into hiding and suggested the disclaimer label, but <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> rejected it as tantamount to `` an apology.'' <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> is `` not showing any good will at all,'' <PERSON> El-Essawy </PERSON> added. `` In fact, he's doing the opposite _ he's trying to promote the campaign against him ... because he wants to sell more books.'' <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, 42, continues to write, and occasionally aims barbed comments at his opponents. In a book review he wrote recently for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Literary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supplement </ORGANIZATION>, he alluded to the public burning of his book by Moslems with this thought: `` To burn a book is not to destroy it. One minute of darkness will not make us blind.''
