<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Schools, Adv 19,0811</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday PMs, Dec. 19 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>State-run Schools Still Off-limits to South African Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DAVID CRARY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While the government pursues racial reform on several other fronts, rigid apartheid remains the rule at state-run schools, despite a growing clamor for change. For millions of black children, schools are overcrowded or unavailable. Scores of white schools have closed because of pupil shortages. Yet the government recently rebuffed a coalition of white parents, teachers and students who petitioned to establish <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s first multiracial public school. `` Amid all his encouraging moves ... President <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> has just failed an acid test,'' said The Star, the country's largest daily newspaper. `` No matter how compelling the reasons to amend that archaic policy, no matter how desperate the pleas from those affected, apartheid remains alive and kicking in the school system.'' Since taking office in mid-August, President F.W. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> repeatedly has vowed to eliminate racial discrimination. Yet his support for segregated state schools is unwavering despite official figures indicating that the government spends nearly five times as much to educate a white pupil as a black one. According to the minister in charge of white education, <PERSON> Piet </PERSON> <PERSON> Clase </PERSON>, school segregation is essential to ensure `` cultural and linguistic continuity'' between the home and the classroom.'' The `` acid test'' referred to by The Star was the fate of <ORGANIZATION> Johannesburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Girls </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, a 102-year-old institution the government targeted for closure because of declining enrollment. A substantial majority of the teachers, students and parents launched an unprecedented campaign to save the whites-only school by opening it to children of the thousands of black, mixed-race and Indian families who have moved into the inner-city neighborhood in defiance of residential segregation laws. After hinting that it might allow a experimental multiracial public school, the government decided instead on a compromise. It would allow the high school to remain in operation, but only as a private school. The state will provide a subsidy of up to 45 percent of its operating costs, but even so, few of the current pupils are expected to able to afford the projected monthly fees of 100 rand -LRB- $ 38 -RRB-. The school also is expected to lose two of its five grades because of financial constraints and will be able to cater to no more than 240 pupils, although the facility has a capacity of nearly 700. `` The creation of a private school is no victory as far as I am concerned,'' said <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> McGurk </PERSON>, a member of a provisional board of trustees for the new school. `` The new school will have nothing to do with the old.'' <PERSON> McGurk </PERSON>, the principal of a multiracial Roman Catholic school, said the government tends to lower its subsidies to private schools with relatively high proportions of black pupils. `` The state has a natural temptation to mobilize as much resources as possible for whites,'' he said. The government currently spends the equivalent of about $ 800 a year to educate a white child, compared to less than $ 200 per black child. This gap has been reduced from previous years, but the government recently abandoned a 10-year plan to equalize the per-capita education spending. In <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, the largest black township with an estimated 2.5 million residents, schools have been plagued by violence, severe overcrowding, shortages of textbooks, poor performances on exams and deteriorating facilities. In many Soweto schools, there are 40 to 50 pupils for each teacher. The South African Institute of Race Relations reported in November that 196 white schools have been closed in the past 10 years, and that remaining white schools have more than 250,000 vacant places. An estimated 1 million black children have no schools to go to, the institute said. A handful of the closed-down white schools have been made available to the education departments for Indians and mixed-race people, but most have been leased to other government agencies and 42 are unused, said the institute, an independent research organization. `` Given the crying need for school places for black pupils, this is a criminal waste of a high order,'' said a recent editorial in The Star. The campaign to integrate <ORGANIZATION> Johannesburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Girls </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> has been emulated in other cities, under the banner of a group called All Schools for All People. <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Moonda </PERSON>, a leader of the group, said that if the state does not act, a defiance campaign will be launched next year in which parents will take their children to the nearest school and demand enrollment. `` We do not want to cause disruptions, but we may be forced to,'' he said. `` The state is simply fostering illiteracy among our kids.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tuesday PMs, Dec. 19</NOTE>
