<FIRST>a w PM-WalterMears ADV12   12-11 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walter Mears, ADV12,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tues Dec 12 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Politicians Plot Greater Safety in Numbers on Risky Votes</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a political system that is supposed to thrive on competition, there's something odd happening. Politicians are starting to suggest the only way to deal with really tough issues is under a cease-fire, a truce in which they would agree to put unpopular votes out of campaign bounds. One Republican leader called it a `` suicide pact,'' and said that may be what it takes to get action to rein some politically sacrosanct spending programs _ Social Security and veterans benefits were two he mentioned. The political parties already have put one such deal into effect, agreeing that Republicans and Democrats will speak no campaign evil of each other for supporting the two-step pay raise the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted itself just before adjourning. House leaders of both parties insisted on that pledge before the vote on salaries and a 1991 ban on honoraria, finding at last a way around the political perils that have gone with raises in congressional pay for 200 years. So the chairmen of the national and congressional campaign committees agreed the pay vote `` is not an appropriate point of criticism in the coming campaigns.'' That will be fine with <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> memers who voted for the raise; dissenters and challengers who try to make it an issue will risk losing the financial and technical support they could otherwise expect from the national campaign committees. With that deal cut, other topics may start to look inviting as prospects for non-aggression pacts. That idea and some variations on the theme came up last week at a forum on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the 1990s, sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. In theory, the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> political system and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> itself should work best with ideas, issues, candidates and officeholders competing in contests that produce winners, force compromise and ultimately shape consensus. Former President <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> argued that side of the case at the <ORGANIZATION> AEI </ORGANIZATION> forum, saying it can work between the branches as well as between the parties. `` A little conflict can bring out the best,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, a former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Republican leader who went to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and vetoed bills at a record pace, 67 of them in 2 -LCB- years. `` I'm not sure that confrontation between the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is necessarily bad.'' As for political competition, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said if he had the power to draw congressional district lines, each of them would be as closely divided as possible, with party registration split no more widely than 60 percent to 40 percent for the minority. But Rep. <PERSON> Steny </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, chairman of the Democratic conference, said congressmen from closely divided districts are the most skittish on controversial votes. He said members with politically safe districts may be in better shape to make the correct but unpopular decisions that sometimes come to a member of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> whip who quit the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year, said professional, aggressive congressional campaign committees in both parties tend to make members nervous about becoming a target over a potentially unpopular vote. `` It's very organized, very controlled,'' <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> said. `` I was part of it, I recognize it.'' Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> whip, said that's why members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> back away from such risky positions as limiting Social Security benefit increases in order to chip away at the federal deficit. Republicans tried in 1982 and got creamed, he said. `` Who the hell is going to do the heavy lifting?'' he said. All sides acknowledge it will take unpopular votes to make real reductions in the federal deficit. `` Nobody gets elected saying no,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>. `` You get elected saying yes. It was <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> who suggested that a political truce might be a way to get things done, by taking the sting and risk out of votes to cut votes to cut popular spending programs. `` We ought to sit down and do the suicide pact,'' he said, agreeing members in both parties will `` go over the cliff together'' and wo n't try to punish each other later. `` It does n't take courage if we all do it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mears </PERSON>, vice president and columnist for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, has reported on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and national politics for more than 25 years.
