<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSAKA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While foreign businessmen complain of obstacles to Japanese markets, travelers complain that crowded airports are the most frustrating barriers to getting into the country. In hopes of easing the bottleneck for air travelers, the Japanese are building an island in <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> and plan to put an airport on it. But few industry insiders think it will be the answer. The project is moving smoothly along, nevertheless, in contrast to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> airport, where riot police recently battled radicals who used firebombs to defend land on which a runway was to have been completed 15 years ago. At <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION>, eight farmers still grow vegetables on and around the planned second runway, refusing to sell their land. Though police have begun to dismantle buildings erected by radicals supporting the farmers, industry sources are doubtful the second runway will be completed by the end its new deadline, two years from now. For more than 20 years, protests against <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> have left six people dead. The airport is surrounded by barbed wire and riot police. It is not connected to key rail lines to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, 40 miles away. The $ 7 billion <LOCATION> Kansai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION>, however, will be out in the bay and not likely to generate any fights with the city's residents The airport is one of the world's biggest civil engineering projects of the 1990s, but it has its critics. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is famous for its bullet trains and sparkling subways, but its links to the outside world _ international airports _ are widely considered unworthy of a great economic power. The main link, <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> airport, `` is becoming a symbol of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s closed nature,'' says <PERSON> Yasuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakakibara </PERSON>, an economics professor. New <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, as <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> is officially called, greets passengers after long trans-Pacific flights with crowds and confusion. After picking up their luggage, passengers get a choice between a $ 200, 40-mile taxi ride to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> or a wait of an hour or more for a bus. <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> handled 4 million more passengers last year than it was planned for, all squeezing through the same number of immigration counters as when the airport opened in 1978. With just one runway, <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> handles 17 million passengers a year. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> airport, with five runways, handles 10 million. `` The congestion is terrible,'' says <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jurek </PERSON>, director of <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> operations for <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. `` The day -LRB- <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> -RRB- opened it had already reached its comfortable capacity.'' The new Kansai airport, an hour's flight west of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, is supposed to relieve the problem when it opens in 1993. But industry sources say the runway is too short, the distance to <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> too far, and its link highways too narrow. An airport serving a metropolitan region that produces 2 percent of the world's economic output needs at least three runways, they say, not just one. Three were originally planned, and the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> is still hoping for them, but the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> says the country can afford only one. Industry sources predict Kansai airport will be full within a year or two of its opening. They expect growth in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s international passengers in the next few years to nearly match the more than 20 percent annual growth since 1987 Today, boats cruise in <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> where 747s will take off. Machines disgorge enough sand to fill scores of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Astrodomes </LOCATION> into a box 2.7 miles long that will be the airport's supposedly earthquake-proof base. It is one of the deepest of man-made islands, standing in 60 feet of water. On it will rise an ultra-modern terminal with people movers and indoor landscaping. A two-level bridge will carry trains and cars across 2.3 miles of water to <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION>'s shore. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> squeezes 122 million people _ half the population of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ into a habitable area about the size of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>; few of them want an airport in their backyard. That keeps airports small and inconvenient to city centers. The island airport will be an hour's bus ride from downtown <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION>. The sand used for the island is costing more than it should because of price-fixing among contractors, who were stiffly fined by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s antitrust agency. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has charged that collusive business practices like the sand cartel keep out foreign businesses; <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has made access to the airport's construction by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies a major trade issue with the Japanese After long negotiations, the airport opened bidding on construction and supplies to foreign firms, and an Italian architect won a design contest for the terminal building. Despite the prospect of problems ahead, foreign airlines are lining up for flight slots at the new airport. For many airlines, the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> are the fastest growing and most profitable markets in the world.
</TEXT>
