<FIRST>s a BC-APN--Reindeer Adv24-2Takes   12-11 0919</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Reindeer, Adv 24-2 Takes,0942</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 graphic.)</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 For 34 consecutive years, the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON> has presented readers with a Christmas story. This time he imposed on one of his friends to offer a frank, revealing, no-holds-barred recollection of what it's like growing up _ as a reindeer.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HUGH A. MULLIGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This time of year you'll find me everywhere. Even on my home turf, the North Country, I've become a profit with honor. Like today in <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>'s old city I'm the chef's special on the dinner menu at the posh Victory Hotel: <PERSON> Renstek </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON>. Across town, the food hall in the Ahlens department store is offering samples of renklamma, a delicious smoked sausage on barley bread coated with horseradish butter. In chic boutiques all over <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION>, you'll find me in a wide selection of sleeping bags, gloves, parkas, moccasins, snow boots with curled toes, primitive masks and, of course, on an endless array of Christmas cards and tree ornaments. <ORGANIZATION> Finnair </ORGANIZATION> has holiday flights to <PERSON> Tormanen </PERSON>, up near the border with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, so good little boys and girls can visit <PERSON> Korvatunri </PERSON>, `` the cave of the ears,'' where Father Christmas overhears petitions for presents under the tree. Now the Swedes are selling condominiums to the cross-country ski set in my frozen stomping ground above the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circle </LOCATION>. Would you believe one of my mates got hit in the rump with an orange golf ball the other day while shoveling away the snow with his antlers to munch on some succulent lichens? In <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> these antlers are pounded into a powder and sold as an aphrodisiac, a love potion. Well, why not? At this festive time of the year, I'm just about the most lovable critter anywhere. In case you have n't guessed, I'm a reindeer, nature's noblest, and perhaps most useful beast. There are a million like me. Maybe more, counting herds exported to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. A few Christmases ago the headline writers were composing our epitaph. That nuclear reactor explosion at Chernobyl spread cesium-137 all over our grazing territory, which stretches from <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> across <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. Experts grimly predicted that our winter food supply of lichens, which have no roots and take all their nutrients from the air, would be radioactive for 20 to 30 years. To keep our herders from going bust, the governments of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> bought up all contaminated reindeer meat at 1985 prices, dyed it a bright blue, sold some to the mink farms and buried the rest. Can you imagine me, beloved of kids around the world, winding up in a nuclear waste dump? Not to worry. Here it is another Christmas, and reindeer meat, inspected and approved, is back in the gourmet shops. And we're still going strong on the hoof, as we have been since the Stone Age when they painted our picture in shocking pink on the wall of that cave in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> In 40 centuries we have n't changed much: still 3 -LCB- feet high, about the size of a Shetland pony, and weighing in at about 300 pounds. Our distinguishing features are wide, deeply cleft hoofs for skimming across marshes and snow fields; close haired, air-filled fur to keep out the cold; a hairy muzzle that serves as a ski mask, and these velvety antlers, sweeping upward, backward and forward again into broad tips of moose-like proportions. No other branch of the deer family equips both males and females with this elegant headgear. None lives so far north where the snows are deepest and food so scarce. To brag a bit, I can run faster than a horse, outdistance a pack of wolves, float like a cork, swim the swiftest rivers, trot 15 mph with 90 pounds on my back while pulling a sled loaded with 300 pounds and cover 40 to 50 miles a day in a blizzard. Over the years, the poets, painters and songwriters have been generous with their praise, if not always accurate. Like when <PERSON> Clement </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> wrote in his classic, `` A Visit From St. Nicholas'': `` When what to my wondering eyes should appear, `` But a miniature sleigh and eight tiny reindeer.'' Actually only seven reindeer are hitched to an akjar, the sled loaded with grandma and the baby, or maybe piled high with tents, blankets and cooking pots for the spring and autumn migrations that cover hundreds of miles. `` More rapid than eagles his coursers they came,'' continued the poet. A bit of poetic license there. Eagles are a menace. They can snatch up a newborn calf quicker than a hungry bear emerging from his winter hibernation. But wolverines are the real enemy. These cunning cousins of the weasel sneak up behind a reindeer burrowing under the snow and pounce on his rump. Worst of all are the mosquitoes, midges and gadflies that sting us on the muzzle, causing colds and congestion, and plant their eggs in the soft flesh under our eyelids, weakening our already poor vision. No wonder we head for the cool mountains in summer. The Christmas card artists got it right, however, about our herders being short, stocky, cheerful folk who wear curly toed boots filled with grass, tall pointy hats with funny flaps, and bright blue, not red, parkas elaborately trimmed with fur, embroidery, ribbons and sometimes silver.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891211-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--Reindeer Adv24-1stAdd   12-11 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Reindeer, Adv 24-1st Add,0879</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>STOCKHOLM: sometimes silver.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Like the sled driver in that poem, they do have `` cheeks like roses'' and `` a nose like a cherry.'' You'd glow like that, too, if you dashed out of a night 50 below into a sauna 220 above zero. Lapps or Laplanders, these rugged people are still widely called in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, but in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> their official name is <PERSON> Sami </PERSON>. They have their own language, of remote Hungarian and Finnish origin, with 120 words for snow and 400 for reindeer. Why not? We reindeer are their whole life, culture and history. Carbon tests on petrified slats found in tundra bogs show they have been chasing us on cross-country skis since at least 2500 B.C. We are their horse, sheep, cow and general store, available in one portable compact model. Tents, blankets, boots, parkas, leggings, sleeping bags are taken out of our hide. The meat, strong and flavorful, can be jerked, smoked, boiled or barbecued. Reindeer blood pancakes are an acquired taste. Our milk is four times richer than a cow's, great for butter and cheese. Bowls, spoons and fish hooks are fashioned from our antlers. Our sinews contribute harnesses, boot laces, lassos and thread spun on looms fashioned from our bones, which also provide knife handles, pack racks and the baby's kemse or cradle, all held together with glue from our hoofs. There really are reindeer games like you hear about in that <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> song. With dice and markers made from our toe bones, the herder's family gathers in the glow of the tent stove for a board game called wolf tablo, a variant of chess in which the wolf gobbles up some reindeer pawns until he finally is cornered. Reindeer are n't driven like cattle in the American West. We call the tune. Instinct dictates where and when we'll mosey off to richer pastures. The herder and his family just follow along, listening for the jingle bells around our necks and the hollow clicking noise the herd makes on the move. Tendons stretching across our toe bones make a sound like of a bunch of schoolboys cracking their knuckles. Before <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> established border controls in 1912, reindeer used to roam from the top of the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bothania </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> meet, all the way to the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>. Herding has changed dramatically in recent years. Logging operations in <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> bases in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s unquenchable appetite for hydroelectric power have shrunk our traditional grazing ground Many herders have forsaken the old nomadic ways. They use planes, helicopters and walkie-talkie radios to follow our migrations. In <LOCATION> Rovaniemi </LOCATION>, up on the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circle </LOCATION>, a Finnish firm called <ORGANIZATION> Rova </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elektro </ORGANIZATION> is marketing `` reindeer radar'' to replace the bells around our necks. Some herd handlers these days ride the frozen range on snowmobiles. `` Tinplate geldings,'' the <PERSON> Sami </PERSON> call them. This brings up a delicate subject. A few weeks ago a militant feminist on a TV talk show called <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> a male chauvinist because only a token doe, Vixen, made his starting lineup on Christmas Eve. The awful truth is that all sled-pulling reindeer are `` harkar'' _ geldings. Castration is performed at the fall roundup, when the huge herds that summered in the mountains are sorted out by family ownership for breeding, slaughter or sled training. The other big reindeer roundup comes early in spring when the young calves still following their mothers are literally earmarked for owner identification. I'll never forget the last day of my childhood. A lasso was thrown over my antlers, and I was bulldogged to the ground like a calf at a rodeo. The next thing you know the herder's plump wife was sitting on my flanks and carving a decorative slice out of my ear with a hunting knife. This snippet, along with others, was hung from the tent pole with care in the time-honored method of reindeer bookkeeping. Swedish <LOCATION> Lapland </LOCATION> alone has more than 10,000 legally registered reindeer earmarks, all different. <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> the Red-nosed Reindeer has become what <LOCATION> Tin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alley </LOCATION> calls a Golden Oldie. Among us, he's strictly for laughs. What <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> really needed to lead the pack was a glowing taillight. On our frequent travels through frozen mist and fog, we follow the wagging white tail of the reindeer just ahead. Although St. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON>'s Day, the last Sunday in November, is the big feast in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Country </LOCATION>, Christmas is a fun time for reindeer. The air is clean and bracing, fragrant with the scent of the stunted pines. We come gaily galloping with steam rising from our muzzles when the herder clangs his ice axe into the frozen snow to dig us out some tasty holiday tidbits. The sun at noon is just an embarrassed blush on the horizon, but in the diamond-studded long winter night the Northern Lights blaze purple and red and gold, more dazzling than the Rockefeller Center tree. It makes a reindeer want to sing out like <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> _ or at least bark, which is what we do: ` Happy Christmas to all, and to all a good night.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
