<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Video Christmas, Or, How To Spend $1,500 Without Half Trying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stuck on what to buy this Christmas? Make it video! Whether you want to splurge, spree, invest or just stuff a few stockings, here are some wonderful items to buy and some excellent excuses for buying them. SPLURGE: A new television set with a 27-inch screen. If you're a typical American, you've been watching that 19-inch tube for more than a few years while new technology has been making it obsolete. This is no time to wait for High Definition TV. The best estimates put <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> at least five years away from the expensive end of the marketplace and maybe even longer before it's affordable in the mass consumer market. Japanese manufacturers are designing video and audio circuitry that tweaks the TV signal for all it's worth. They make `` enhanced definition'' with much sharper pictures, even if you live in an area where cable TV is n't available everywhere. Much of the broadcast soundtrack in major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities is in hi-fi stereo, so a tinny little speaker just is n't going to make it for the 1990s. An `` inexpensive'' 19-inch set costs about $ 200 in a discount house. It's about $ 400 for a 19-inch TV loaded with the new technology, and about $ 700 for a low-end, high-tech 27-inch tube. In areas where such electronic goods are heavily discounted, you can shop around and get a stunning, stereophonic `` cable-ready'' TV set for less than $ 1,000. We're talking automatic tuning, inputs for multiple video sources, outputs to your home stereo, a `` smart'' remote control and a picture that'll knock your eyes out. Go for it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 SPREE: A combination LaserDisc and compact disc player. If you have n't already taken the plunge into digital audio for your home stereo, you should. Compact discs do n't wear out and make any stereo system sound startlingly better. The budget-minded approach is to buy a small portable unit to start, then trade up to a full-featured model. But if you've got some Christmas money to throw around, why not get into digital audio with a machine that also plays videos? They cost around $ 500 in the discount houses, but the LaserDisc image is said to be 60 percent sharper than the best VHS player and the sound quality is just like a CD. Newly released LaserDiscs are sometimes cheaper than VHS tapes. A VHS new release that retails for $ 89.95 is in the video disc rack for $ 49.95, and some may sell for $ 29.95. And in theory LaserDiscs do n't wear out and the digital signal will never become obsolete. Also, there are certain features you ca n't get with a VCR, such as `` letterbox'' formatting that allows you to see the wide screen image. In the `` full-feature'' LaserDisc format, the producers include incredibly comprehensive supplementary material. The three-disc package for the 1936 classic musical `` Showboat'' includes excerpts from the 1929 Universal film version, excerpts of <PERSON> Ziegfield </PERSON>'s 1932 Broadway revival, interviews with stars, a color film documentary on showboats, a visual essay of 300 stills tracing the history of showboats and the history of the musical on stage, screen and radio, and enough other archival material to choke a librarian.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 INVEST: _ A VHS player Not a recorder, mind you, but a transportable, play-only machine that can run off a 12-volt car, boat or RV system and is about half the size and half the cost of a videocassette recorder. It's great to have a backup when your main VCR breaks down. It's great to have a portable VCR when you're on vacation or out of the country You have to look for these, but they're available at most video dealers and start at around $ 150. _ A four-head, hi-fi, Super VHS videocassette recorder Or, at the very least, a stereo VCR that you can pipe through your home audio system.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 STOCKING STUFFERS: _ A non-abrasive VCR head cleaner Use it only when you have significant deterioration in picture quality. Tape heads are delicate, precision devices and should not be messed with. _ Blank tapes People never have enough blank tapes and they never buy themselves high quality tapes. _ Videocassette storage racks People never have enough places to store videocassettes, which need and deserve a safe, dust-free resting place. _ A year's worth of cable TV service Surprisingly affordable. Gift certificates are available. Call your local cable company for details. _ Videocassettes Most people are surprisingly reluctant to buy themselves their favorite movies, and you usually know what your friends and relatives enjoy, from `` Teen-age Mutant Ninja Turtles'' to rock concert videos, operas and great games of the World Series. Even better, the emergence of big retail video chains and the plethora of available programming has pushed down the price of video software. Suprisingly, the monster hits of recent years are most heavily discounted. `` Batman,'' the summer megahit, is couponed, rebated and generally knocked down to less than $ 20. `` Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' lists for about $ 20; `` E.T. The Extraterrestrial'' is about $ 25. `` The Right Stuff'' lists for around $ 30, and the newly restored version of `` Lawrence of Arabia'' is $ 40. There's also an abundance of competitively priced, Christmas-oriented programming in video stores at this time of the year, from old favorites such as <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s `` Holiday Inn'' to cartoons that will hose down the kids late on Christmas Day. _ LaserDiscs Any great film makes for a great disc, and most are digitally remastered to take advantage of the technology. `` Blade Runner'' is a big favorite; so are `` Gone With the Wind'' -LRB- cropped back down to its original format and its colors restored -RRB- and `` The Godfather.'' But the hit pick for Christmas giving has to be `` Lawrence of Arabia.'' The 1962 Academy Award-winning film was restored from its original negatives under the supervision of director <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lean </PERSON>, who added 20 minutes of footage cut from the original release. The standard CLV -LRB- $ 49.95 -RRB- and the extended play -LRB- 3 discs, $ 124.95 list -RRB- contain copious supplementary material.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 SOME VIDEO DO N'Ts: _ Do n't buy for video collectors without very specific knowledge or Either they'll already have it, they'll quibble at the quality of the recording or the format, or they'll say they only wanted `` ` Ishtar,' any format, man.'' Buy them a can of compressed air for blowing dust out of their machines or a spray bottle of glass cleaner and no-lint paper towels. Buy them a videocassette rewinder -LRB- battery-powered, $ 29.95 at Radio Shack -RRB- or a bulk eraser to get rid of unwanted recordings. _ Do n't forget to buy `` Instant Fireplace,'' at $ 9.95 _ the logical culmination of a television culture Put the cassette in the VCR. Punch `` play.'' Watch the video of fire burning in fireplace. Listen to the appropriate music. Wonder about the decline of the West.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
