<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Let Love Rule'' -LRB- Virgin -RRB- _ <PERSON> Lenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Kravitz </PERSON> Quick now _ the cover of <PERSON> Lenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Kravitz </PERSON>'s `` Let Love Rule'' album pictures a black man in dreadlocks with a ring through his nose. What type of music does the cover protect? Your first guess was probably not a singer-songwriter album that owes much to the 1970s work of such artists as <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stevie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wonder </PERSON>. But confounding expectations is <PERSON> Kravitz </PERSON>'s game. His debut album is encouraging in several respects. First, it's nice to see an artist _ any artist _ break past stereotypes at a time when racial tension is high and too many people have closed-minded views about what's `` black music'' or `` white music.'' Second, it's encouraging that any company in the conservative record business will allow a brand new artist to produce, write and perform an album virtually by himself. Many established artists do n't get the same trust. Of course, the clear danger in these `` homemade'' projects is too much self-indulgence. Yes, `` Let Love Rule'' suffers from this. But what it lacks in slickness it frequently makes up for in charm and intimacy. With its overly polite, workmanlike drumming, `` Let Love Rule'' sounds much like <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON>'s first solo album. <PERSON> Kravitz </PERSON> also shows a fondness for the hippie era in his lyrics for such songs as `` I Build This Garden for Us.'' The soaring title track is one of this rookie's best moments, as is `` Mr. Cab Driver.'' In the latter, <PERSON> Kravitz </PERSON> accompanies himself on fuzztone guitar while telling of a cab driver passing him up for a ride because of his dreads and skin color. He ends with an expletive. `` My Precious Love,'' a gospel number with guest organist <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>, is another high point. `` Be'' sounds strikingly like Plastic Ono Band-era <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>. Be forewarned, though: `` Let Love Rule'' begins to get ponderous toward the end, with many arrangements crawling. <PERSON> Kravitz </PERSON> may not be the genius that this self-produced effort seems to herald. But simply dismissing him as Mr. <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonet </PERSON> -LRB- his TV-star wife -RRB- is a mistake. He's got enough talent and strength of convictions to merit watching. _ By <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Variations on a Theme by <PERSON> Hindemith </PERSON>, Symphony No. 2, by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Walton </PERSON> -LRB- EMI -RRB- _ the <ORGANIZATION> Bournemouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION>, conducted by <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Handley </PERSON> Here is a regional European orchestra that performs difficult music at the highest level. <PERSON> Handley </PERSON> elicits crackling yet controlled performances. The <LOCATION> Bournemouth </LOCATION> musicians play with the clarity and solidity typical of many British orchestras; the winds, particularly in the symphony's Andante movement, play real chamber music. <PERSON> Walton </PERSON>'s idiom, though at times reminiscent of <LOCATION> Nielsen </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Bartok </PERSON>, is highly original and produces an abundance of orchestral sounds. His music is worth getting to know. _ By <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakin </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
