<HEAD>From `Death Wish' to a New Wish: Winner's Return to Comedy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-WKD--Bullseye, b0856</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thinking back on his career, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Winner </PERSON> finds something very odd. And that is, he said, that `` a very sophisticated British chap who lives in a stately home in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> has made more films probably than most Americans in the worst slums of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' Winner is a <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> University-educated sort of chap who puffs cigars and is best known for directing the `` Death Wish'' series of movies about vigilante warfare against the punks, rapists and muggers of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Now he has gone back to trying to make people laugh. `` I sort of slipped into this bath of blood and made all those pictures, and I decided I had to do something myself to get back,'' Winner said during a break on the set of `` Bullseye,'' his comedy caper starring <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caine </PERSON>. Due for summer release and budgeted at $ 15 million, `` Bullseye'' pairs <PERSON> Caine </PERSON> and <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> for the first time on-screen, playing dual roles as con men and atom scientists. On one recent day, Winner was shooting at the west <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> location of <LOCATION> Syon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION>, home since 1594 to the Dukes of <LOCATION> Northumberland </LOCATION> and substantially redesigned two centuries later by architect <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> and master landscape-gardener Capability <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. It's a long way from Winner's urban nightmares starring <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronson </PERSON>, and the director acknowledged he was more in his element here. `` I'm more at home as we talk here in a wonderful 18th century palazzo, which is the sort of place I live in,'' said Winner, who lives in a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> mansion in the <LOCATION> Bayswater </LOCATION> district with British actress <PERSON> Jenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Seagrove </PERSON>. `` It's quite nice to be back in a more sophisticated area.'' Winner makes no apologies for the violence that has often defined his films, from `` The Mechanic'' in 1972 to the three `` Death Wish'' movies. `` I think they were good thrillers,'' said Winner, whose films have been accused of irresponsibly encouraging viewers to take the law into their own hands. `` I have many friends who are muggers in the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. They are fascinating people, underused people, who have to make do when society rejects them. I love the people there,'' he said. Winner started out as a critic and journalist. His early movies were comedies, among them a caper film `` The Jokers,'' with <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>. But his comedies on the whole have not done well, critically or financially. His 1975 `` Won Ton Ton the Dog Who Saved Hollywood'' flopped, despite a starry supporting cast including <PERSON> Henny </PERSON> <PERSON> Youngman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Blondell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Berle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergen </PERSON>. He has just come out with `` A Chorus of Disapproval,'' his film of <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayckbourn </PERSON>'s acclaimed play, to a lukewarm critical reception. The `` Bullseye'' casting coup was his idea, based, he says, on having watched <PERSON> Caine </PERSON> and <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> at dinner parties and seeing `` how wonderfully they work together as a comedy act socially. `` We've always said we must find something ... and it just happened merely by chance: I found this script that needed a lot of work but was basically a wonderful piece for them, so here we are.'' Winner said the stars' off-screen rapport was evident on screen. `` They will often carry on a scene with ad libs of their own,'' he said. `` There's a shorthand both during the shooting and during the lunch break and all the time.''
