<HEAD>The Artists: Artist Sculpts With Explosives</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sculpture is risky business for French artist <PERSON> Chantal </PERSON> <PERSON> Cottet </PERSON>. Instead of chisels, she sculpts with dynamite, hand grenades and artillery shells. <PERSON> Cottet </PERSON>, 39, is the inventor of `` blast art,'' a term she created to describe the jagged hunks of twisted steel born from her carefully planned explosions. Her studio is located on her family's farm outside <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in the middle of corn and beet root fields stretching as far as the eye can see. Yet the explosions she sets off, using between 11 and 33 pounds of dynamite, rattle windows in villages miles away. The farm is dotted with sculpture of all shapes and sizes including a giant mushroom form made from an imploded gas canister, and graceful flower pots sprouting stainless steel tulips from inside. During a recent interview, <PERSON> Cottet </PERSON> demonstrated her art. She used penthrite, the same explosive that police say was used to bomb a passenger jet of the French airline <ORGANIZATION> UTA </ORGANIZATION> last October over <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` The penthrite itself is n't dangerous. Things get risky the moment you connect the explosive to the detonator,'' she said, holding up the two-inch device. `` If this goes off before I'm ready, I'll lose three fingers and an eye. The most treacherous aspect of her work, she explained, comes from elements she can not control _ such as the random electrical current generated by high-speed trains passing by just 164 feet from the woods where she does the blasting _ and which could, in fact, ignite the explosive before she is safely away. Preparations for the explosion took more than an hour. <PERSON> Cottet </PERSON> wrapped the plastic-coated penthrite cords in a spiral design around the insides of a cylindrical steel frame that supported a vacuum-sealed aluminum can. At one point, the rusted frame tipped over, with <PERSON> Cottet </PERSON> inside, and narrowly missed the water table in which the explosion was to take place. Once the can was secured inside the frame, it was lowered into the vat. <PERSON> Cottet </PERSON> then wound up an electrical sparker that set off the blast. `` Three, two, one,'' she yelled. Yanking the lever, the loud blast sent a shower of water high into the air, wetting onlookers. Steam rose from the churning water. The frame was hoisted high in the air, and there was <PERSON> Cottet </PERSON>'s sculpture _ a dripping, crumpled aluminum can filled with dirt balls. But she is only half-pleased. `` The hardest part of my work is trying to determine how the material is going to react, given the amount of explosive used and how it is attached,'' she said. `` This is n't bad, but I think I'll explode it again to open up the top part. The second explosion _ this time on the ground _ takes visitors watching from behind a shatter-proof glass window by surprise as the can is propelled into the air behind a cloud of pungent smoke. The carcass will become a finished work of art once it is washed and polished. <PERSON> Cottet </PERSON> has been working with explosives for seven years, ever since the day she found an abandoned, rusting gas canister `` a bunch of kids probably blew up for fun.'' `` Its hollow shape was what I'd been trying to achieve in marble and wood for a long time,'' she said. `` The moment I saw the can, I knew I'd found my calling.'' She has perfected her knowledge and use of explosives during frequent seminars at French military bases. In the beginning, she was the oddball artist. Today, she is known to everyone, and is taken seriously enough to receive grants from the Culture and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> ministries. Besides penthrite and dynamite, which she stores in special, temperature and humidity-controlled closets protected by sophisticated alarm systems, <PERSON> Cottet </PERSON> sculpts with hand grenades and artillery shells. She finds out when the military base in <LOCATION> Bourges </LOCATION> is planning to fire missiles and artillery shells, and places her material in the right position so it will be blown up in the way she wants. `` Look at this piece of armored steel,'' she said caressing the hundreds of jagged dents left by bullets. `` Is n't it beautiful?'' Not everyone agrees. The artist has run into considerable opposition, not only from art institutions such as the Beaux Art academy where she trained, but also from private galleries, collectors _ and even fellow artists. `` People told me I was crazy when I began working with explosives. They might look at the sculpture and say they like it, but when they find out it was done with explosives, they shy away,'' she said. But she dismissed the idea that her work is off-putting because it bears the traces of violence, and ultimately death. `` To me, the sculpture conveys notions of power and energy latent in the metal.'' She likes being called a pioneer, but is sorry she has no students to train. `` I'm sure huge strides could be made in this field if there were more of us,'' she said.
</TEXT>
