<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: World Music for Peter Gabriel</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten years ago, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> bought his first drum machine. All he needed were rhythms to program. Bored with rock' n' roll, the former star of Genesis looked to <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and elsewhere. He could n't believe what he was hearing, the freshest grooves, the richest harmonies: spirituals from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>; African jazz from <PERSON> Tabu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Orquesta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reve </ORGANIZATION>, perfomers of `` son,'' the root of modern salsa. His music was never the same. <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> began experimenting with rhythms on his 1982 album, `` Security'' -LRB- on one track, `` Rhythm of the Heat,'' he used a Ghanian drum section -RRB-, and the same year helped form the WOMAD -LRB- World of Music Arts and Dance -RRB- festival, gathering bands from more than 60 countries. Like the Rolling Stones, who went out of their way to praise the blues musicians who influenced their records, <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> wanted to find a large audience for these exciting sounds. `` Grooves for me are physical things,'' explained the 39-year-old <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> recently to promote the release of four records on the new RealWorld label. `` They make me feel good. A bad disco groove, of which there's an awful lot, does n't make me want to dance. `` Some of the grooves we now take as commonplace rock have come from <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. They travel across the seas and become slightly different. I think quite often, white artists do n't quite get it right, and we end up coming out with a form which is new. The records just issued are `` Passion Sources,'' music from the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> heard while putting together the soundtrack for `` The Last Temptation of Christ''; `` Shahen-Shah'' by <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Nusrat </PERSON> <PERSON> Fateh </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>, one of the foremost singers of the devotional music called `` Qawwali''; `` La Explosion Del Memento'' by <PERSON> Orquestra </PERSON> <PERSON> Reve </PERSON>; and <PERSON> Tabu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ley </PERSON>'s `` Babeti Soukous.'' `` We've tried to look for performers who have a lot of soul,'' <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> said. `` I think they have strong traditions in their own countries, it's sometime unfortunate that it gets all out under a ` World Music' label. You talk to the musicians themselves, and they say, ` What the hell is this world music?' I play my music, whatever it is.''' <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> is part world musician, part traveling salesman. He knows record buyers might never even look at the selections from the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> without an old friend pointing the way. So if you happen to think of <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> while listening to the infectious grooves of <PERSON> Tabu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ley </PERSON>, well, at least that's a start. `` It's not me I'm selling, but someone else,'' he said. `` It's saying to people who are interested in my music that if you like my stuff, there's a chance you would like some of the things that really turn me on `` But it's not <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON>'s label. It's a label in which I participate. We have a rule where everyone on our committee has to like everything that goes out.'' Lyrics are not included, forcing the listener to turn his or her attention away from the songs' literal meaning and concentrate instead on the emotions of the performance. In Qawwali, for instance, words are chanted over and over to a simple rhythm, giving them a hypnotic, mantra-like effect. `` There are ways which you get into a framework where everything you hear is music, which is probably a nice place to be,'' he said. `` You can really hear the emotion and humanity. So many intrumentalists are desperately trying to speak with their instruments, are trying to run the gamut of human emotions. `` You try to listen to their soul and the feeling that comes out of it. Some of these wonderful singers from all around the world are just capable of getting the hairs up in the back of my neck: That's what I look for.'' <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON>, of course, has one advantage over the average listener: He's actually met the people on the records. Not all the local musicians, however, were impressed by the presence of a world famous rock star. `` Half knew who I was, half had no idea. One of the Qawwali groups assumed I was a guy who worked around the studio and did n't know I was a musician When they found out I could play, they were a little bit curious.'' For <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> this music suits his political ideals as well. Regional tensions, he discovered, can crumble under the power of a universal language. One of the best evenings he had was when he was improvising with a Pakistani singer and sitar player <PERSON> Ravi </PERSON> <PERSON> Shankar </PERSON>, who's from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shankar </PERSON> played double violin. `` <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> do n't normally work together and probably would n't have in other situations, but they really got turned on,'' said <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON>. `` I was contributing, but in a subsidiary role. Now I'm going to do an album with the two of them. They started out not hostile, but suspicious of each other. By the end of it, they were in love, all in the space of 40 minutes.''
</TEXT>
