<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Her Life Is Best Expressed Through Writing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> is an author, and a fairly popular one, too. But her mother wished she had taken a more secure job, such as stenography. Other family members agreed. The author can still remember her cousin, a nun, remarking how much she disliked her books. Even her beloved uncle criticized her work, calling it dirty. It's never stopped her, though. If <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> had never produced a single novel, she'd still write, perhaps keep a journal or diary, or make notes to herself if necessary. She would n't feel well otherwise; it's how she best expresses herself. Growing up in an Irish household uncomfortable with verbal communiation, writing was the only way she could imagine life outside her unhappy family. Her novels, `` Final Payments,'' `` Men and Angels'' and the new `` The Other Side'' -LRB- $ 19.95, Viking -RRB- are printed confessions, attempts at saying the unsayable, penetrations of characters who conceal their emotions. `` Irish culture does not value emotional display,'' the author said in a interview. `` So it certainly does n't value emotional articulateness. It values stoicism, it values silence and it values keeping things to yourself. `` I know that inarticulate people have very rich inner lives; they just do n't have the language for it. Some people who are educated or upper-middle-class assume that if you control language or own language, that means you have a finer inner life. But you can speak emotionally and not be revealing any true emotions.'' The imminent death of <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>, in her 90s, brings together four generations in `` The Other Side.'' But this family seems only to share unhappiness. Infidelities, casual cruelty and emotional instability have made the <ORGANIZATION> McNamaras </ORGANIZATION> incapable of supporting each other, even at this time. `` I would n't know what to write about a good family,'' <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> said. `` They do n't interest me as a writing problem. What are you going to say? ` They all got together, somebody took the leg of the chicken, somebody took the breast and somebody got the wing?' Who cares?'' But she ca n't resist a streak of creeping optimism. There's hope From <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Camille </PERSON>, two of the <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> grandchildren who seek love outside their unhappy marraiges, and <PERSON> Darci </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dan </PERSON>'s playful daughter. `` I have a lot of faith in <PERSON> Darci </PERSON>. She's got juice and she's got pizzaz. Life is probably not going to be as wonderful and glorious as she thinks it is, but she's got life, she's got life force,'' the author said. `` I think what happens to you as a child, a young child, is tremendously important. I think feeling approved of, feeling loved, feeling safe, is something that ca n't be replaced. If you do n't have that, I think you're really crippled It's as if you had to learn to walk again as an adult.'' <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>'s characters are weighted down by guilt, a belief that all earthly pleasure is undeserved, an exaggerated sense of duty. In `` Final Payments,'' a young woman shuts herself off from the outside world for years to nurse her sick father. The housekeeper in `` Men and Angels'' takes it upon herself to `` save'' her boss from the sins of humanity. Obligation drives <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON>'s husband, to leave the nursing home where he had finally found happiness to fulfill a long-forgotten promise to be at his wife's side when she dies. `` The question of what do you owe people and what you allow for yourself is very vexing, and I think the Irish are very idealistic,'' <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> said. `` They love the possibility of martyrdom looming somewhere in the future. `` They love the idea of a heroic goal that you can devote your life to. I think it's shaped their political life and it's shaped their literature.'' <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, wrote poetry until age 25 and then started on `` Final Payments,'' which came out in 1978. She takes her characters through sickness and health, faith and despair, sex and religion. Vulnerability, the dependance on uncontrollable forces, fascinates <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, and terrorizes her as well. The uncomplicated joy of <PERSON> Darci </PERSON> is shadowed by <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON>, a once formidable woman reduced to desperate howls of pain. `` One of the terrible things about aging is the way that you lived does not matter nearly so much as the way you're going to die,'' she said. `` You can live a really rich, noble life and die like a jibbering animal. You can live like a total jerk and have a nothing life, but have a rather beautiful, peaceful death.'' Words beaten into sound, that's what happens to <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> as she nears death. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>'s characters struggle between language and emotion, and for most of their lives, language wins. But in the end, emotion resurfaces. As a writer, <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> tries to weave them together. `` The rhythm of words and the physical existence of words is very important to me. I write very physically. To get the intensity of emotional experience into intensely connected language is a very, very big goal. `` I think there's always a problem with language. What does langauge actually reveal? The distance between what we want to say and what we are able to say is tragically great.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec. 22-24</NOTE>
