<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 22-24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Kentucky Headhunters Get Your Attention</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You start with the name: the <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> Headhunters. Images of barefoot, spear-carrying ruffians in loincloth. `` It makes people think we're wild, naked hillbillies,'' says <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, a member of the five-member band from <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, whose music is as intriguing as their name. The five are a newly signed recording group who play country, rock' n' roll, bluegrass, blues and jazz. `` We offer a blend of <PERSON> Merle </PERSON> <PERSON> Haggard </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> and Led <ORGANIZATION> Zeppelin </ORGANIZATION>,'' says <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelps </PERSON>, whose brother, <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, also plays in the group. `` Basically what we're doing is taking bluegrass music and making it jazzy,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> says. `` <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON> has done it and all those people over there. They would take a bluegrass song and make it up-tempo.'' Now about the name. The group, nicknamed `` the Heads,'' took the name from a music term believed to have originated from the blues great Muddy Waters. The term `` headhunters'' apparently came about when Waters' band displaced local, less proficient groups as Waters' band toured the country. The proud Kentuckians added their state to the term and their memorable name was born. `` This is the first thing that catches everybody's attention,'' <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelps </PERSON> says. Says Young: `` I called one guy at a radio station and he said he opened our record just because of the name. He said it sounded like something out of National Geographic.'' Adds group member <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> with a chuckle: `` We've got everybody scared to death. They think, ` Headhunters!''' The group, whose members are in their late 20s to mid-30s, has been together four years. Their first Mercury-Polygram album is `` Pickin' on <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>'' and the first single released from the LP is `` Walk Softly on This Heart of Mine.'' The band consists of four guitars and drums and occasionally an harmonica. `` It's aggressive music, but it's a bunch of hillbillies playing it,'' <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelps </PERSON> says. Drummer <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>'s brother, says: `` We all grew up using the outhouse.'' `` We've all run out of toilet paper out there,'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> adds. The band plays a mixture of music ranging from <PERSON> Jimi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON>'s `` Wait'til Tomorrow,'' to Cream's `` Crossroads,'' and country standards such as `` Oh Lonesome Me'' and `` <LOCATION> Wildwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Flower </LOCATION>. They close their performances by saluting their home state with `` My Old <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> Home.'' <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelps </PERSON> adds an entertaining touch to their performances by pulling an array of props out of a trunk on stage. `` It's full of toys,'' he says. `` I've got water guns in there and I wet people down. I pull out a phone and talk to <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON>. I've got some magic tricks and I throw out cheap novelties to the crowd. He also juggles bowling pins. `` Four is the most I can do, and three is plenty.'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> often plays drums shirtless, borrowing the idea from other drummers he's seen. It also saves time when he's through playing. `` I've been playing this way all my life. It gets hot back there and you do n't want to jump in the shower afterwards with your clothes on.'' Their instruments are as unpretentious as the musicians playing them. They've disdained state-of-the-art guitars and drums for instruments that are 20 years old and older. `` These drums are a complete different sound,'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> says about his set, which has `` <ORGANIZATION> Metcalfe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>'' proudly printed on them. `` I do n't ever remember tuning them.'' Before the <PERSON> Phelps </PERSON> brothers joined the group, the band was known as Itchy Brothers. This name was borrowed from the King <PERSON> Leonardo </PERSON> cartoon show in which Itchy was King <PERSON> Leonardo </PERSON>'s evil brother. `` It was a good name,'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> says. `` We thought about keeping it. The <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> Headhunters are an extension of it.''
</TEXT>
