<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--DefiningtheDeficit Adv14   12-11 0893</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Defining the Deficit, Adv 14,0912</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Dec. 14, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Congress Rethinking How Government Tallies Red Ink</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bookkeeping issue that seemingly only an accountant could love is commanding keen interest on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. The debate on how to tally the budget deficit could have big implications for Social Security. The deficit by law is defined as the difference between federal income and spending, including the billions earned and spent for Social Security benefits. So as the Social Security trust funds build big reserves to help pay for baby boomers' retirement in the next century, the official deficit tally is held down by payroll and employer taxes earmarked for Social Security benefits. Democrats and Republicans both are increasingly supporting taking Social Security's money-making trust funds out of the deficit equation, claiming that the current system masks the extent of the rest of the government's red ink. In fiscal 1988, for example, the government's $ 155 billion deficit would have been $ 194 billion if Social Security were excluded. In 1989, the official deficit fell to $ 152 billion; without <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION>, it was $ 204.5 billion. `` We are playing a game with the way we report the budget deficit each year,'' Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> told colleagues in October. `` It seems to me it is time to ` fess up to what we are doing and do something about it. <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., held up action on an urgent debt bill until congressional leaders agreed to tackle the deficit-definition issue early next year Those who favor removing Social Security from the equation say the unrealistically rosy budget picture removes pressure to cut the deficit, and that the move would help protect the trust fund reserves. `` What we're trying to do is stop the looting of that trust fund, and get truth in budgeting,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION> `` If we can save our Social Security trust fund surpluses, rather than spending them on government consumption as we do presently, we can more than double our net national savings rate,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, D-N. Critics maintain that removing Social Security from the equation would excuse a big chunk of the budget _ about 20 percent of federal spending _ from making more contributions toward reducing the deficit. They also say that once trust funds no longer are counted, politicians might spend the reserves on pet projects or bigger benefits for today's retirees, at the expense of tomorrow's. `` Every day, I and other members of the <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> answer mail asking for benefit expansions by stating that we can not further improve benefits because of the budget deficit,'' Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel recently `` This argument will be eliminated when Social Security becomes completely off-budget.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reischauer </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, shares that concern. `` It certainly would be harder to fend off proposals to raise benefits or cut payroll taxes without the discipline of deficit reduction,'' <PERSON> Reischauer </PERSON> told lawmakers. For example, he said, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> might have been unable to resist recent efforts to boost payments to `` notch babies'' _ Americans born in 1917 through 1921 _ who get lower benefits due to a change in the method of calculation. Social Security Commissioner <PERSON> Gwendolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> calls the deficit-definition debate `` one of the most specious discussions you're ever going to find in government'' since it shifts numbers on paper without altering spending. Yet she is wary of tinkering with the system. `` I have a real concern if taking it off-budget means making it more vulnerable. To pull it out, there have got to be some safeguards built around that trust fund to ensure that nobody can raid it.'' <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> believes Social Security is better off left as it is, but he has introduced legislation to help protect the trust funds if they are removed from the deficit calculations. Under the bill, a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> member could object to any legislation that increased Social Security benefits without providing for a corresponding increase in revenues. Such an objection could be overruled only by a majority vote in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> or by 60 votes in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Without such protections, <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> said, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may not have `` the political courage to say ` no' to those proposals which would increase benefits immediately but at the same time further jeopardize our children's benefits.'' Mrs. <PERSON> King </PERSON> called <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>'s bill a step `` in the right direction,'' but said it was n't strong enough to adequately protect the trust funds. Accompanying the deficit-definition debate is the broader question of whether <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> should continue stockpiling money now to meet the big retirement demands of the baby boom generation. The General Accounting Office early in 1989 said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should consider rolling back payroll tax increases because the Social Security reserves are being used `` to finance the current operations of the government and are masking the size of the on-budget deficit.'' Returning Social Security to a `` pay-as-you-go'' system would involve reducing payroll taxes in the 1990s and raising them above scheduled levels in the next century, when benefit costs will rise as the baby boomers retire. `` This would eliminate the illusory buildup of reserves that now represents little more than a mechanism for using the payroll tax to finance the general operations of government,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 14</NOTE>
