<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Dec. 14, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Active Minds Are Healthy Minds, Retirees Find</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY PEMBERTON</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The only thing wrong with retirement, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Giles </PERSON> says, is he ca n't get a day off. <PERSON> Giles </PERSON>, 68, of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, retired as a chemical engineer seven years ago. As a volunteer for the <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executives </ORGANIZATION>, he spends 10 hours a week advising small businesses on marketing and sales techniques. He also is a speaker for <ORGANIZATION> Gideons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, which distributes Bibles. <PERSON> Wes </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitchell </PERSON>, who retired as an insurance consultant in 1981, coordinates monthly business seminars for SCORE. He has been a trustee for the Masons for three years and visits once a week with patients at <ORGANIZATION> Mercy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>'s Heritage Program for Seniors. `` Some people think I'm driven, but I just get a big kick out of life,'' said <PERSON> Kitchell </PERSON>, 74, of <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kitchell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Giles </PERSON> may be getting more than just a kick out of life. `` We think differently as we get older, in a slower manner, and there is some memory loss which is a perfectly normal finding,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bender </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Mercy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geriatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinic </ORGANIZATION>. `` But there is some evidence that staying mentally active may actually help preserve brain function.'' Mental lethargy and its effects on good health can be seen most easily in nursing home patients, said Dr. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Overton </PERSON>, another gerontologist at Mercy. `` In nursing home patients, we see these pseudo dementias that are n't real dementias at all. You walk into a room and see a patient staring at the ceiling or the floor. And you think they've lost their minds but they have n't They're truly depressed,'' said <PERSON> Overton </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bender </PERSON> tells his patients to write down their talents and use them. `` Using one's talents is the epitome of mental activity which may prevent or slow down the changes in the aging brain. `` <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> did active research until the week before he died in his 70s. That shows you that we always have the capacity to learn more.'' <PERSON> Gwen </PERSON> <PERSON> Rusk </PERSON>, 79, of <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, worked as an insurance secretary for 14 years until retirement in 1980. `` Now, I stay home as a last resort,'' said <PERSON> Rusk </PERSON>, who volunteers 15 to 20 hours a week at the Retired Senior Volunteer Program. Her rule is not to spend more time playing bridge than doing volunteer work. RSVP, a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Way </ORGANIZATION> program begun in 1972, matches volunteers with jobs in the community. Program director <PERSON> Barb </PERSON> <PERSON> Wacker </PERSON> said its 1,100 volunteers donated 162,000 hours in fiscal 1988-89. <PERSON> Rusk </PERSON> and other retirees at a senior housing building make teaching aids for children in the Head Start program. They fashion balls out of fabric scraps and nylon stockings and put together jump ropes by connecting red plastic loops. `` It is n't that I do n't like my own company, but actually it can get very stale if you're not out in the world to see what's happening That's how you make friends to ensure you have friends when you become an old lady,'' <PERSON> Rusk </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> <PERSON> Cline </PERSON>, 68, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Urbandale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, is on an RSVP committee that gives advice on planning for retirement. She was co-coordinator of the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> Peace Ribbon Project in 1984 and visited <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in 1986 for the International Women's Day and to learn about problems facing women there. <PERSON> Cline </PERSON> said she has retired at least six times, but ca n't make it stick. She stays involved `` to feel like I'm worth something, have something to offer and have a place in this world.'' <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaeger </PERSON>, 65, of <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, raised two children after her divorce by working as a dental assistant. At age 60, she was forced out of her job when her boss retired. `` I tried to find work with another dentist but they all wanted to hire younger dental assistants,'' <PERSON> Yaeger </PERSON> said. She called the Retired Iowans Employment Program at the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, which placed 2,000 senior citizens in paying jobs last year. It helped her get a job as a receptionist at Crossroads, a seniors program. `` I learned to use one of these fancy memory typewriters. I learned how to get around that pretty well,'' she said. `` If you stay home you become a couch potato with your soap operas and you just do n't think like you did before. `` I'll work as long as my health holds out.''
</TEXT>
