<HEAD>Anthology Publishes Work by Older Writers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN GOESSL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ah, the stories they can tell. About a man obsessed with the education of his children. Or a love story with <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> as a backdrop. Or building a homestead in the early 1900s. `` A lot of us do memory pieces and if they're not entirely memory we might write fiction based on things we've known,'' said writer <PERSON> Garnet </PERSON> <PERSON> Garoni </PERSON>, 71, of <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruces </LOCATION>. `` There is n't a very big market for that type of story, but it's really fun to write.'' Not a big market, maybe, but Mrs. <PERSON> Garoni </PERSON> and other older New Mexicans have found an outlet in Serape, an annual anthology of poetry and short stories by senior citizens. Published by <ORGANIZATION> Nightjar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, Serape first appeared on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> bookshelves in 1983, the result of a creative writing class at a Las Cruces senior center. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> McIlvoy </PERSON>, an associate professor of English at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, is n't proud that he was surprised at the caliber of writing he found among students at Munson Senior Citizen's Center. But his thinking took a quick, sharp turn. `` I thought, ` Gee, this is powerful writing,''' says <PERSON> McIlvoy </PERSON>, who still teaches the weekly class. `` It's so strong, so powerful and so informed by those years of experience that I really wanted it to be brought to readers.'' Serape's early issues contained work by class members, but more recent editions have been open to older writers throughout the state. Some 30 pieces of work by 15 authors _ all of them 55 or older _ appear in the sixth edition of `` Serape,'' scheduled for release this month. It will be the fourth time Mrs. <PERSON> Garoni </PERSON>'s work has been published in `` Serape.'' `` Miracles Do Happen,'' a short, fictional story about a girl who leaves a <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> town for the bright lights of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` Really one of my own thoughts about <PERSON> Serape </PERSON> is what we're doing is giving exposure to people whose names are not already recognizable, but who are certainly doing important work,'' <PERSON> McIlvoy </PERSON> said. He and editors <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON>, retirees whose work has appeared in <LOCATION> Serape </LOCATION>, waded through 64 manuscripts of about 25 pages each before making the wrenching final selections for the 1989 edition. `` We get quite a massive pile of material,'' <PERSON> McIlvoy </PERSON> said. The pile could become even more massive if he is able to expand the anthology to include older writers from throughout the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION>. McIlvoy proposed the idea to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> State officials while also telling them the expansion would require higher production standards and more pages _ and therefore more funding. Serape, which sells for $ 6 and can be purchased at bookstores around the state or from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION>, now is funded mainly through sales and by the university, with 10 percent coming from donors and patrons. `` Teaching at the <ORGANIZATION> Munson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, as I have done for the last six years, and editing this anthology are for me the most important, stimulating things that I do,'' <PERSON> McIlvoy </PERSON> said. `` I work with extremely talented young writers here at the university, but the old cliche applies _ there's no replacing experience.''
</TEXT>
