market share for general-purpose terminals in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It also produces monitors and IBM-compatible personal computers. <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON> officials began a search for buyers earlier this year after the 8-year-old company suffered a loss of $ 21 million in the 1989 fiscal year ended March 31, compared with a $ 28 million profit the previous year. <ORGANIZATION> Wyse </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse </PERSON> said the acquisition `` provides shareholders an opportunity to maximize the value of their shares at this time.'' <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Wu </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Channel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, said the group's main objective will be to improve business He said he was confident demand for computer terminals would remain strong. Taiwanese businessmen have shown growing interest in acqusition of foreign firms, which they believe could help boost their business in the world market. Last month, <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hsieh </PERSON>, governor of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, proposed to use <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s foreign reserves of about $ 73 billion for loans to local enterprises for overseas acquisitions. In August, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s leading construction company, acquired <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, for an estimated $ 70 million to $ 100 million.
