<HEAD>Government's Latest Sale is 5.7 Times Oversubscribed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government's $ 8.3 billion sale of its water industry was 5.7 times oversubscribed, attracting the second highest number of applicants for a British privatization, officials said Monday. Demand for shares of the 10 water authorities of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION> was strong enough to trigger `` clawback'' provisions that will give small investors nearly half the stock instead of the previously planned 27 percent. Most investors will get far fewer shares than they asked for in the sale, which totals 5.24 billion pounds. `` It is a great success,'' Environment Minister <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. `` We have proved our critics wrong.'' Some 2.7 million people made applications, the second highest response ever for a government privatization after the 4.5 million applicants in British <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> sale. There had been concern that the sale would be unsuccessful because the stock market has been in the doldrums and the privatization has faced stiff opposition from critics who believed such a vital utility should remain government-owned. Trading in the shares officially begins Tuesday on <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> In the `` gray,'' or unofficial, market the shares were trading at 126 pence, or $ 1.99, at midday Monday. The government is selling 2.183 million shares at 240 pence, or $ 3.79, each but investors only put 100 pence down and pay the rest off in installments. Under the `` clawback'' provisions in the water sale, institutional investors now will get 39 percent of the shares, and foreign investors the remainder. Each investor everyone will get at least 100 shares. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s Conservative government has sold off billions of pounds worth of state-owned companies in the past decade to promote capitalism in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>.
