<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> plans to trim another 8,500 jobs from its work force in 1990 after cutting about 25,000 this year, the company confirmed today. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T spokesman <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said the company has been planning next year's reductions for some time and already has notified employees. `` The people in the departments that are affected by the job reductions planned for 1990 have been informed,'' he said. The Wall Street Journal reported on the cuts in today's editions and quoted unidentified sources as saying that they could be part of a wider work force reduction campaign in 1990. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> declined to characterize the reductions or to comment on how sweeping they would be. Most of the 1990 reductions will occur in <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> division, which has 37,600 workers and runs <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's long-distance network, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said Employees were told on Nov. 28 of plans to reduce the division staff by 6,000 jobs. Additionally, the company plans to cut 700 jobs in its <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> unit, 1,400 jobs in its <ORGANIZATION> Material </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ