<HEAD>National Semiconductor Reports $2.4 Million Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday it earned $ 2.4 million in the second quarter compared with a loss of $ 25.2 million for the same period last year. The company, citing progress in addressing inventory, capacity and other cost issues, said it had met its goal to return to profitability during the period, which ended Nov. 26. Earnings per common share, after payment of preferred dividends, were zero in the latest quarter in contrast to a loss of 27 cents a share a year earlier. National Semiconductor said its net sales for the second three months of fiscal 1990 rose to $ 416.8 million from $ 404.6 million. Sales for the first half of fiscal 1990 were $ 814.4 million, with a net loss of $ 19.5 million, or 24 cents a share. Sales during the first half of last year were $ 849.5 million, with a net loss of $ 55.7 million, or 58 cents a share. The chipmaker in February announced plans to close its <LOCATION> Danbury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, plant. In May, the company said it would close a plant in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, and consolidate two <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> factories in an attempt to reduce duplication created by the acquisition of Fairchild Semiconductor.
