<FIRST>a f BC-TheMoneyDecade Adv00-1stAdd   12-11 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-The Money Decade, Adv 00-1st Add,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: ... than in 1969.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Thus came the reaction. In politics, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> belied his free-trading reputation by signing legislation protecting <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> steel, autos, textiles and sugar. His administration quit its laissez-faire attitude toward the overvalued dollar, which threatened to gut American industry by making imports a better buy than goods made in the <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION> Government supervision of the savings and loans was toughened and there were moves toward re-regulation of airlines, cable television, the financial markets, clean air and job safety. Meanwhile, each foreign purchase of an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> institution _ <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Rockefeller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, Burger King _ brought fresh calls for restrictions on foreign ownership. The more liberal lawmakers even dared call for an industrial policy _ a coordinated program for rebuilding <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s economic strength that sounded to conservatives like wasteful `` lemon'' socialism. By late in the decade, polls showed Americans viewed <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> as a bigger threat than the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, proof that the Money Decade had wrought changes in attitudes about money and power. In finance, <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s revolution lost some of its luster as junk bonds became associated in the public's mind with hostile takeovers. Heavy debts from buyouts and mergers sapped momentum from the takeover rush and prompted questions about the wisdom of financing through leverage. While some takeovers promoted efficiency by forcing managers to lop off unproductive enterprises, they also forced undue emphasis on short-term profitability to pay off debt, in direct contrast to the forward-thinking Japanese. Corporations erected sophisticated defenses to ward off takeover threats and some states even passed laws to keep out raiders. The crash-rattled financial markets, meanwhile, imposed `` circuit breakers'' to forestall another collapse. The technology revolution came through mostly unscathed. Powerful personal computers seemed to be on every desk. Biotechnology gave new life to medicine and fiber optics turned the phone network into an eight-lane voice and data expressway. If the technological advances had a dark side, it was the fear that too many people were left behind by an economy based on knowledge and skill. Laborers and clerks were replaced by machinery or silicon chips. An unskilled, despairing underclass grew increasingly detached from the rest of society. The revolutions and reactions of the Money Decade echoed a historic American theme: the contest between liberty and equality. More liberty generally means less equality; less liberty means more equality. The contest, far from resolved here at home, now engages a world of players as the'90s approach. Out of desperation, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> are giving once-hated capitalism a chance in spite of the risk of upheaval. A new Soviet opinion poll shows widespread resentment of the newly rich and craving for a return to `` a strong hand'' over the economy. For those who will struggle with the choices of free enterprise in the future, the'80s left clear warnings. More growth can equal less security. With freedom comes the responsibility to manage greedy extremes. Americans lived that dilemma in the 1980s. Now the rest of the world is taking its turn.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
