<HEAD>A Timeline for the Business '80s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some of the notable events of the 1980s in business and the economy.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1980:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Jan. 3: <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> embargoes grain sales to <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. March 14: <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> responds to high inflation by imposing first peacetime credit controls in modern times. April 21: <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average hits decade low of 759.13. Dec. 19: Prime lending rate rises to 21.5 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1981:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
 April 24: <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> lifts Soviet grain embargo. May 1: <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> agrees to `` voluntary'' restraints on exports of passenger cars to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Aug. 3: Air traffic controllers begin illegal strike and are fired. Aug. 13: <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signs tax-cutting legislation; top rate drops to 50 percent from 70 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1982:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Jan. 7: <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> buys <ORGANIZATION> Marathon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 6.3 billion. Jan. 8: <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> agrees to give up 22 local telephone companies, representing $ 80 billion in assets. It is freed to enter computer business. October: Unemployment hits 10.8 percent, highest in 42 years. November: Economy hits bottom and expansion begins.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1983:    </HEAD>
<TEXT>
