<HEAD>After Decade of Deregulation, Airlines Facing Challenges</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's largest airline company is a conglomeration of big and small carriers flying under the regional banner of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Almost every other major carrier has been a target for takeover or restructuring. Airports are clogged, fares are inscrutable, and the commercial fleet is showing its age with frightening regularity. That is probably not the future the architects of deregulation imagined in 1978 when the airline industry was freed from government control over fares and routes. But that future is now, after little more than a decade of freewheeling competition. For business students of the 1980s, there was no more compelling case study of the impact of Reagan-era deregulation. No industry underwent more wrenching changes. None moved from controls to competition to consolidation as quickly. In October 1988, the airlines celebrated their first decade of freedom. Less than a year later, the industry was engulfed by a wave of takeover fever, its second since deregulation began. `` I'm uneasy about the wave of buyouts,'' said <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON>, a former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> who is widely considered the father of airline deregulation. `` The critical thing is, how does it affect competition?'' In the space of a week last August, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's second-largest carrier, was put into play by a $ 5.4 billion buyout bid for parent <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> from oilman <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>; an investor group completed its $ 3.65 billion buyout of <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, parent of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>; frequently rumored takeover target <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> completed its merger with <ORGANIZATION> Piedmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> and separately sold a major stake to `` white knight'' investor <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON>; and a manufacturing company said it might consider a takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Midway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. While the fierce competition sparked by deregulation turned many airlines into hot properties, it put others in desperate straits. In 1989, three carriers filed for bankruptcy protection under Chapter 11: <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, hit by a crippling strike in early March; <ORGANIZATION> Braniff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which filed for the second time in seven years; and <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, a feeder carrier for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>. As some companies faltered, the takeover frenzy continued to build, culminating in developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s $ 7.5 billion buyout proposal in October for <ORGANIZATION> AMR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, parent of industry leader <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. When <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> failed to assemble financing for its $ 6.75 billion pilot-management buyout _ an announcement that caused a sudden 190-point drop in the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average on Oct. 13 _ the mania subsided temporarily. But <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> talks revived, and experts said the reshaping of the industry will continue in the'90s. Airlines in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are positioning themselves to exploit the Common Market deregulation set to begin in 1992, and some are swooping down to buy pieces of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers. The prospect of foreign ownership and the heavy debts associated with takeovers have prompted warnings from officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, including <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>. Under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law, foreign airlines are n't allowed to own more than 25 percent of the voting stock of domestic carriers. In October, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> used his authority to force <ORGANIZATION> KLM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, the foreign partner in the <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> deal, to cut its $ 400 million investment by $ 225 million. For travelers, the fallout from deregulation has been even more worrisome. The number of passengers on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines jumped to around 455 million in 1988 from 275 million in 1978, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. By the year 2000, traffic is projected to be 800 million or 900 million people. There's nowhere near enough capacity in the system _ runways, airport space and air traffic control _ to handle the onslaught. The nation's commercial fleet, meanwhile, has been aging rapidly, from an average 8.5 years old in 1978 to 12.5 a decade later. Aging aircraft have been blamed for some terrifying accidents in recent years and have compelled thriving big airlines to buy new jets. To upgrade their fleets, major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers spent a record $ 67 billion in the first 11 months of 1989 on 1,600 new planes. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the largest commercial aircraft maker, can not keep pace. Its backlog, swollen further by the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union strike that ended Nov. 20, is now worth $ 85 billion. The problems, and the concern about safety they have prompted, have intensified pressure on the federal government to re-regulate the industry, <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON> and others warn. Proposals to re-regulate the airlines emerged in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in early November. The industry hopes it will be allowed to work out the problems. As for the lack of capacity, `` There's a lot of immediate things that can be done,'' Eastern President <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON> said in an interview. Bakes, a former attorney for the CAB, was influential in drawing up the 1978 deregulation law. As a sign of progress, he pointed to the first meeting in mid-October of the <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capacity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> _ a group that includes representatives of the major airlines, airport operators and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>'s department is developing a new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> transportation policy to take the country into the 21st century, and the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s new <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capacity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> will help expedite the rebuilding of the infrastructure. If those efforts fail, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> warned, `` We will lose the benefits of deregulation.''
