<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Buyouts, Shift from Industrial Pursuits Changed Face of Fortune 500</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Levi </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> disappeared from industrial <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s best-known roster, sold in a management buyout. Lone <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> became too small to qualify. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> was reclassified and appears on a separate service company list. For a variety of reasons, upwards of one-third of the companies included at the end of the 1970s on the Fortune 500 ranking of the nation's biggest industrial concerns were missing from the same list a decade later. The buyout wave of the 1980s was a major factor in the sweeping changes in the Fortune 500 list. Combined sales rose 66 percent to more than $ 2 trillion. <PERSON> Levi </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>, which was No. 177 on the list published in 1979, last appeared among the Fortune 500 in 1985 after which it was sold to management. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>, which ranked a lofty 18th on the 1979 list, changed its name that year to <ORGANIZATION> Conoco </ORGANIZATION>, then vanished from the list after <ORGANIZATION> DuPont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> acquired it in 1981. The flip side of the buyout wave has been that buyers generally moved up the list. <ORGANIZATION> DuPont </ORGANIZATION> was ranked ninth in 1989, up from No. 16 a decade earlier. Making an even bigger move was <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the cigarette manufacturer ranked 10th in 1989 and 46th in 1979. It bought <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION>, which was 41st in 1979, and <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON>, which was 39th, during the 1980s. Some companies dropped off the list, meanwhile, because they sold assets or failed to grow fast enough. Lone <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, which sold assets over the decade, was No. 248 in 1979 and last appeared in 1987. Another big factor in the changes was an increasing emphasis on service businesses. Companies must derive at least 50 percent of their sales from manufacturing or mining to qualify for the magazine's industrial rankings; otherwise they are eligible for Fortune's Service 500. That caused companies like <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION>, ranked 11th on the 1979 industrial list, to be moved to the list of diversified service companies in 1988. Other prominent companies reclassified as service concerns during the 1980s included <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, ranked 58th on the industrial list in 1979 and now known as <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and American Can, which was 66th in 1979 and is now called <ORGANIZATION> Primerica </ORGANIZATION>. The top of the Fortune 500 industrial listing has been fairly stable despite the exodus of companies lower down. Eight of the Top 10 in 1979 were still there in 1989. The dropouts are <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, now known as <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>, which was acquired by <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> in 1984. Standard Oil had been No. 6 in 1979 and Gulf Oil was ninth. <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> ranks 11th on the 1989 list. They were replaced by the acquisitive <ORGANIZATION> DuPont </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> led the 1979 list with $ 63.2 billion in sales and remained at the top in 1989 with nearly twice as much _ $ 121.1 billion. The 500th company in 1979 moved halfway up the ladder, reflecting computer industry growth in the Money Decade. Data General was 500th in 1979 with sales of $ 379.9 million and No. 272 in 1989 with sales of $ 1.36 billion.
