<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Consumers Adv00   12-11 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Consumers, Adv 00,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Is Flaunting Affluence on The Way Out?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumers bingedin the 1980s, indulging themselves with everything from fancy gourmet foods to electronic gadgets and luxury vacations. Now, on the cusp of a new decade, consumers bloated with debt are sobering up. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marketplace bore the full weight of the postwar baby boom during the'80s. Many grown-up boomers ignored the example set by thrifty parents and spent liberally, helping to fuel the longest peacetime economic expansion in American history. They were helped in their pursuit of consumer happiness by some fortuitous economic events. Inflation was tamed in the early part of the decade by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s tight money policies, and the prime lending rate, which had peaked at 21.5 percent in December 1980, fell closer to 10 percent by late 1982. A big income tax cut was engineered by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. A bull market on Wall Street kicked up piles of money for lucky investors. A strong dollar made imported goods, like Japanese electronics and German automobiles, the standards by which all good, consuming Americans were measured. `` People went shopping like crazy. We were on a spending binge in the 1980s,'' said <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaber </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` For most of the decade Americans were spared the pair of miseries that plagued the 1970s and early'80s: rampant food and fuel inflation.'' Advertising jingles proclaiming `` You deserve a break today'' or asking cheekily `` Who says you ca n't have it all?'' summarized the spendthrift mentality of yuppies, the buzzword for young, urban professionals. `` They were not into postponed gratification,'' said Florida-based consultant <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON>. Yuppies embodied'80s - style conspicuous Although representing less than an estimated 5 percent of the 76 million Americans born between 1946 and'64, they were the vanguard of the baby-boom generation, setting trends in consumer behavior. More consumers than ever before were armed with credit cards and carried the buy-now, pay-later concept to the limit. Over 606 million charge cards of all kinds, including ones offered by retailers, were held by Americans at the end of 1988, up from 380 million in 1979, according to figures compiled by the <ORGANIZATION> Bankcard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, a nonprofit group. <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, whose Chicago-based market research firm tracks trends, said shopping habits changed drastically during the decade. Dual-income families had no room for `` chief shoppers,'' whose main mission in life is keeping cupboards from going bare and keeping house. The result was more individuals shopping for themselves, giving rise to specialty retailers, each supplying specific types of merchandise. These niche merchants are expected to thrive in the'90s, <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> said. Trend spotter Faith Popcorn of the marketing consulting firm <ORGANIZATION> Brain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said consumers seemed obsessed with props during the'80s, things that made them look good or helped project a certain image. The principal consequence of all this spending was an accumulation of debt and an accompanying decline in savings. The savings rate, measured as a percentage of spendable personal income, sank to some unusually low depths in the'80s: 3.2 percent in 1987, compared with an average between 6.5 percent and 7 percent in the three prior decades. The economy in general looks a lot different than it did when the boom began. The tax cut left behind a big budget deficit. The flood of imports threw the trade balance out of whack. Inflation, spurred along by aggressive spending, poses a new threat. Against the backdrop of impending hard times, consumer tastes are beginning to change, shifting away from extravagance toward practicality, the experts believe. Furniture, not fast cars, and home computers, not glitzy trinkets, will be the people's choice of the'90s. With a larger share of baby-boomers coping with the responsibility and expense of child rearing, purchases will be more sensible, predicts Ms. Popcorn, the marketing consultant. `` The 1980s were for show and the 1990s are for go, in terms of where is it going to get me in the future,'' Ms. Popcorn said. <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> thinks of it as a shift away from abundance toward the `` precious,'' which he describes as an intense enjoyment of the things you have rather than simple gluttony. Even if belts are tightened a few notches, consumers will remain a driving force of economic activity. But their power may be channeled in different directions or diminished as the economy matures and sorts out imbalances, particularly in foreign trade. `` In the 1980s we were consuming more than we produced at home,'' Ms. <PERSON> Shaber </PERSON> said. `` Final demand in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was greater than domestic production. To close the gap, we have to do the reverse.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
