<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Firmly Rooted U.S. Automakers Bent Far Eastward in '80s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Tracker is one of those vehicles that could have existed only in the 1980s: designed in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, built in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> by a U.S.-Japanese partnership and sold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Did that make it Japanese, Canadian, or maybe American, since it was sold in Chevrolet showrooms? Its producers avoided the issue by calling it a Geo, from the Greek word for Earth. For the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> auto industry, it was a confusing, sometimes difficult and above all blurry decade. Blurriest were the definitions of what was an imported car. Scenes of angry men battering a <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> with sledgehammers faded into scenes of happy Japanese and American autoworkers toiling together on assembly plant teams. People were n't even sure what it was the companies were making. The Nissan Pathfinder was classified as a car by the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and a truck by the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. As for attitudes toward the Japanese, just ask <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> McCurry </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sales </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` Most of the prejudices have gone away,'' he said, `` but I still have some relatives where they have n't.'' The auto industry was touched, like many others, by acquisitions, joint ventures and takeovers. As in other industries, the Japanese influence shifted into high gear. Proud American automakers, industrial pillars of the West, struggled to halt their loss of market share to competitors from across the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> by forming joint ventures with Japanese companies and imitating <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s manufacturing and labor management. The Tracker typifies the partnership trend. The small sport-utility vehicle was designed by <ORGANIZATION> Suzuki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Ltd. of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> It's built in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> at a factory owned by <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. It's sold through <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Chevrolet dealers and carries the Geo nameplate. For another example, a <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plant in <LOCATION> Flat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, produces cars for <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` The Japanese certainly have provided a goad and it has been a chance for us to learn some very good things that we have learned to apply,'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON> said in a recent interview. Each of the Big Three battled back to profitability during the decade through new products, cost-cutting, union concessions and government protection from imports. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s case was the most widely publicized. In 1980, the federal government guaranteed loans to refloat the sinking automaker. The corporation paid off the loans seven years early. `` We began the decade of the'80s by taking one risk that ran against some of the most deeply ingrained economic ideals we hold in this country and it was a huge success,'' <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said in a recent speech. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 1.54 billion in 1980 but it turned into the most profitable automaker in history just eight years later when it reported a $ 5.3 billion profit. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> began an `` Action Plan'' that has a target of trimming $ 13 billion from its costs. Instead of reinvesting all their profits, the Big Three hedged their bets by going into other businesses. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> acquired <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in October 1984 and <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in June 1985. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> got into the banking business in December 1985 when it acquired San Francisco-based <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationwide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, which has become the nation's second-largest savings and loan institution. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> bought <ORGANIZATION> Gulfstream </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> in August 1985, two years before it purchased <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, for one, later decided it was spreading itself too thin Late in 1989, it announced plans to sell <ORGANIZATION> Gulfstream </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> and its military electronics business to `` concentrate resources on core car and truck operations.'' Another ploy of the automakers had an unintended side effect. The Big Three managed to obtain `` voluntary'' restraints on Japanese imports, but that only drove the Japanese into building plants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Those plants made cars even more cheaply than the ones in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Ltd. spearheaded the Japanese manufacturing assault on American soil when it began making Civics in <LOCATION> Marysville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, in November 1982 Since then, <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Subaru </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Isuzu </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> have set up assembly plants either independently or in a joint venture with one of the Big Three automakers. Those plants are adding to big problems for the industry as the 1990s get under way _ overcapacity and the potential for layoffs. The overcapacity that emerged in the 1980s seems certain to worsen in the 1990s. The plants forced to close most likely wo n't be the new Japanese-owned ones in white-dominated, `` right-to-work'' places like rural <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> They'll be the aging Big Three plants, mostly located in union strongholds and employing a disproportionate share of minority workers Under pressure from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, membership in the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union dropped during the decade from about 1.5 million to just under 1 million. While many things got blurry in the 1980s, the outlook for old-line autoworkers became starkly clear.
</TEXT>
