<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Markets Adv00   12-11 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Markets, Adv 00,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wall Street Sent Pointed Messages in the '80s</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Money Decade of the 1980s brought both heady success and egregious excess to Wall Street. The securities markets returned the favor by taking a hand in setting the economic and political course of the decade for American society. Stock traders celebrated the ascendance of deregulation, technology and global investing with a historic bull market that began in the summer of 1982 and reached new highs as late as the autumn of 1989. `` It has been a very unusual bull market _ the longest we have ever had in peacetime,'' said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVoe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a veteran analyst at the firm of <ORGANIZATION> Legg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mason </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. It outlasted several prominent participants, who by the end of the decade were serving prison terms or banished from the business for their parts in a series of scandals. In the ultimate test of its staying power, the bull market survived the worst market drop in more than half a century _ the crash of 1987 that culminated in Black Monday on Oct. 19 of that year. Wall Street in the'80s was unfailingly controversial as well. While the bull market signaled a seven-year period of economic expansion that was welcomed by many business managers and consumers, it was assailed by social critics as the emblem of an age of materialism. Many Wall Streeters themselves decried the new computerized trading techniques it helped spawn _ strategies like index arbitrage and portfolio insurance that collectively came under the label `` program trading.'' Worst of all, said some, the boom on Wall Street was financed in large part by a mountain of debt that might someday collapse with devastating consequences. Still, with all their blemishes, the 1980s lived up to their billing on the Street as `` the decade of financial assets.'' Gone were the bouts of rapid inflation and rapidly rising interest rates that depressed paper investments in the 1970s, elevating in their place tangible assets such as gold and collectibles. Stocks and bonds were back in favor as a way to participate in the growth and resilience of the American economy. As they recovered their strength, the stock and bond markets flexed their muscles, playing a newly prominent role in the shaping of government policies affecting the economy. At the beginning of the 1980s, it was the bond market's turn to play `` vigilante,'' acting as a kind of self-appointed surrogate for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> by increasing interest rates each time its traders sensed a new stirring of inflation. By the time of the 1987 crash, the stock market also had emerged as a vigilante force, impelling central bankers to ease up on credit conditions whenever it felt the threat of recession. The new breed of financial vigilante was quick to strike, sending the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials down a record 508 points on Black Monday in 1987, and administering another 190-point beating nearly two years later, on Oct. 13, 1989. Despite those rude interruptions, the net results for the decade showed emphatic advances. The Dow Jones industrials, which started the 1980s at 838.74, hovered near 2,700 in the waning weeks of the decade. That kind of performance wo n't be easy to match in the 1990s. For the average to triple again, it would have to climb past 8,000. Some observers see reason to hope for more good news. The nation's labor force is likely to grow more slowly in the 1990s, putting pressure on business to invest in greater amounts of productivity-enhancing equipment, says <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON>, chief economist at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` The net effect of increasing investment in business equipment will be a pattern of steady economic expansion through the 1990s,'' <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> asserts. Nevertheless, many analysts wonder whether more unpleasant shocks await a generation that grew up with the image of Wall Street as inexhaustible horn of plenty. As <PERSON> DeVoe </PERSON> put it: `` An awful lot of people are being seduced to the idea that we're never going to have another bear market again.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Yearend Editions</NOTE>
</DOC>
