<DOCNO> AP891211-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-11-89 2149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Decade-Computers Adv00   12-11 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Decade-Computers, Adv 00,0832</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Personal Computers Went Hand-in-Hand With Capitalism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Diebold </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in the late 1950s talking about computers when a Russian stood up in the back of the room and said computers were exactly what his country needed. Large computers would finally enable Soviet leaders to control their economy according to plan, the Russian said. Do n't be so sure, <ORGANIZATION> Diebold </ORGANIZATION> told the man. Computers can do a lot, but they ca n't run an entire economy. Nothing can. Things are too complex. That meeting in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> more than 30 years ago foreshadowed two of the most powerful developments of the 1980s: the rise of the personal computer and the decline of centrally planned economies. Western democracies prospered in the'80s because power was in the hands of the people. Personal computers helped by breaking the tyranny of the corporate data center, where men in white coats had doled out information to supplicants. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s commissars feared personal computers as much as printing presses. Their central computers were busy churning out five-year plans. It did n't work for producing steel, and it worked even less for producing ideas, the currency of the knowledge economy that emerged in the'80s. `` They always thought that if they just got one more level of sophistication in their equations, and in their models, that would make the whole thing work. It did n't,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Diebold </ORGANIZATION>, a New York-based consultant. <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> recognized the personal computer's revolutionary potential in a January 1984 commercial of a female athlete throwing a mallet through an image of Big Brother In the flash of the exploding screen, <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> announced the Macintosh and promised, `` You'll see why 1984 wo n't be like ` 1984.''' The personal computer was a phenomenon of the 1980s. While the pple II appeared in 1977, PCs did n't become a force in the business world until <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> rolled out its first model in 1981. After that, things happened quickly. In 1982, <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> introduced 1-2-3, the electronic spreadsheet that gave many people a reason to buy their first computer. <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> introduced its first <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> clone that year, and rose to the Fortune 500 faster than any company in history. 1984 was the year of the Macintosh as well as the first personal computers from newly split-up <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T. In 1985, co-founder <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Jobs </PERSON> resigned from Apple. In 1987, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> tried to distance itself from the clone-makers with its Personal System-2 line. In 1989, Jobs introduced a black magnesium cube of a workstation that he called the `` Next.'' PCs were the great levelers in the'80s. They let little guys compete for business with big guys. Owners of PCs could dig facts out of databases, analyze them and assemble them into professional-looking documents _ all from a storefront office or a corner of the bedroom. The leveling happened within the computer industry itself. For <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, PCs threatened the fat profit margins it made on minicomputers and mainframes. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> found that all the resources of <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> could not guarantee it success in the fast-moving PC industry. In 1989, it ran ads portraying itself as a <PERSON> David </PERSON> to the Goliath of <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> _ a company not even founded a decade earlier. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> invented personal computers and used them in the'80s more than any other nation, perhaps a reflection of the go-it-alone spirit of Americans. Americans dominated production of PCs as well, but that may not last for long. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> gained control of most chips, screens and other components and attained a solid position in laptop computers, the fastest-growing portion of the market. Whether or not <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> takes over the PC industry in the'90s, the critical issue will be which company, and which nation, uses computers most intelligently. The wrong way is mindless number-crunching, which was all too common in the'80s. `` You got a lot of people showing very elegant sets of figures all worked out in great plans, but with the same sorts of lack of judgment you would have had without the computer,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Diebold </ORGANIZATION>. To change that, personal computers in the'90s must be machines for ideas, argues <PERSON> Marsh </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>, an entrepreneur in <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. Society must learn to raise ideas as methodically as it raises wheat, <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> argues He has sold <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and others on a program called IdeaFisher that prods people into making odd but fruitful mental associations. `` The computer's been crunching numbers and word-processing very neatly for a lot of years,'' <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> said. `` Now we've got to move it into expanding our mind.'' That agenda is a natural for the American-born personal computer. It is definitely not what the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> had in mind.
</TEXT>
