<HEAD>Products of '80s Stressed Convenience, Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Product makers in the 1980s let people have what they wanted, even if it meant admitting a mistake. The revival of old <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> by popular demand told the story of the decade. Consumers were masters of the economic universe and they got exactly what they desired, from fax machines to oat bran. Convenience and specialization were hallmarks of'80s products. Microwave ovens had been available before the decade started, but their popularity zoomed in the'80s as lower prices and more compact construction helped make them indispensable fixtures in American kitchens. <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Langer </PERSON>, who heads her own New York-based market research firm, said the machine eased the guilt some homemakers felt about pursuing interests outside the home. The kids could easily fix their own hot meals. <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> upset some customers by changing the formula for its flagship drink in 1985. The company said it listened to consumer complaints and brought back the original as Coca-Cola Classic three months later. The old standby soon regained status as the best-selling soft drink, leaving analysts to wonder whether it was all a publicity stunt. While the microwave oven made it easier to leave home, the 1980s offered other products for those who did n't necessarily want to go to the office. From the <ORGANIZATION> Timex </ORGANIZATION> Sinclair 1000 personal computer that debuted in the early part of the decade through generations of <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> and Apple models and the <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> laptop, people had the tools to keep up and figure things out for themselves at home. The trend toward self-sufficiency was accelerated with the proliferation of cellular telephones and personal facsimile machines. Well over half of American homes installed videocassette recorders, giving people the freedom to do what they wanted and still catch their favorite movies or programs on their terms. Forget to set the timer? You can tune in the portable <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watchman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> launched its national newspaper, <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION>, in the 1980s and its colorful graphics and concise writing style influenced other papers In television, the mass media came under assault as cable networks emerged and others went after narrow audiences. Rock music fans got their <ORGANIZATION> MTV </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> was launched. Home shopping channels also debuted, peddling jewelry, porcelain dolls and gadgets around the clock. Dozens of new financial products appeared in the 1980s, including zero-coupon bonds, securities backed by payments on car loans, bank money market accounts and futures trading based on stock indexes. On the highways, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> introduced minivans, cars like <ORGANIZATION> Chevy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Camaro </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> Firebird livened up the dowdy state of auto design and convertibles made a comback. But the gull-winged DeLorean failed to fly -LRB- except in the movies -RRB-, and the <LOCATION> Yugo </LOCATION> from Eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> quickly ran out of gas. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Coolers started a rush to concocting alcoholic beverages for the adults who grew up on fizzy drinks, but the rage soon went flat. <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION> introduced LA, a low-alcohol beer that has lagged despite the trend toward moderation and health. The health craze created the environment for $ 100 sneakers from <ORGANIZATION> Nike </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Reebok </ORGANIZATION> and a revival of demand for oatmeal with its reputed cholesterol-lowering abilities. If the 1980s left you stressed, you could take some consolation from another product of the decade _ the pain reliever ibuprofen was approved for sale without prescription.
</TEXT>
