<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eight Who Shaped the Business '80s</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES M. KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>, <PERSON> Morita </PERSON> and Jobs. Of the scores who played leading roles in business and finance during the decade, these are eight who shaped the'80s. When asked to name the great business leaders of the decade, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> business writers produced a list of more than 30, including some inanimate objects like the junk bond and one obvious group, the Japanese. But some individuals stood out, their contributions so familiar that the mere mention of their last names nearly tells their stories. These are eight who set the tone. Eight who personify the most important themes of the last 10 years _ free markets, corporate restructuring, economic transformation and global competitiveness. Two of the eight, former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and ex-Federal <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, orchestrated events at the macroeconomic level, molding an economy of steady growth and low inflation. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> exploited the times, blazing trails and building fortunes in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s unfettered marketplace. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> and <PERSON> Akio </PERSON> <PERSON> Morita </PERSON> performed business miracles on opposite ends of the earth and emerged as national as well as corporate standard-bearers. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Jobs </PERSON>, as a singular sensation, proved a reassuring reminder that no matter how much change the 1980s wrought, individual creativity was still the most valuable commodity for sale in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Below are brief reflections on the marks these eight left behind:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Reagan and Volcker: Two Most Powerful</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was dubbed the great communicator, but he was an even greater deregulator and free enterpriser, who dedicated his two-term presidency to restoring <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s capitalist fervor. He will be remembered for his good fortune _ he got a recession out of the way at the beginning of his tenure _ and for maximizing his opportunities. In the midst of the downturn, he won approval for big tax cuts that launched the longest peacetime expansion in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. He held two economic tenets dear: Taxes should be cut and the federal bureaucracy should be trimmed. Because he proved a better tax cutter than program pruner, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> boom created a burgeoning federal budget deficit that kept interest rates inordinately high even as the economy expanded. Plugging the holes in Reaganomics fell to <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, who controlled the money supply _ and thus interest rates _ with the perspective of a tortoise to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s hare. Where all the president's men saw growth, the apostate <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> smelled inflation and resolved to keep a grip on monetary policy even as Reaganites jawboned for easier credit. For his steadfastness, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> chairman earned the unofficial title of `` second most powerful man in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' Oddly, <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> was never seen as a political threat to the president, perhaps because his tight-money policies kept the worst excesses of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> revolution in check. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s appeal was founded in his bold pursuit of ideals at the expense of opposing interests. Executives admired his guts when he fired the striking air controllers in 1981; labor leaders never forgave him. <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, too, was somewhat of an idealist, but he had bitter medicine for all to swallow, consumers and fat cats alike. <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> put restrictions on business in the form of tight credit. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> dismantled government regulation at every turn. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> invited all businesses to the party; <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> and his inflation-fighting successor, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, were the designated drivers. Putting an ironic twist on an old <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> saw: <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> could not have been <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, if <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> had n't been <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>. The expansion, still intact after seven years, would not have been as powerful or as enduring without the countervailing forces of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s whip and <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>'s tug on the reins.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Milken, Pickens, Lorenzo: The New Capitalists</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 By reviving laissez faire as a guiding principle of government, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> set the stage for a new brand of capitalist in 1980s. Government scrutiny was out; wheeling and dealing was in. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> became giants, not by inheritance or formal succession to the chief executive's office, but by taking full advantage of the market's new freedoms. They did n't develop any new products; they employed old tools to new ends. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, a bond trader, took high-risk corporate bonds off the junk heap and created a $ 200 billion market for debt financing. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON>, an oilman, showed how to hit gushers in the stock market by snapping up the shares of companies undervalued in comparison to their assets. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> MBA </ORGANIZATION> with a fascination for flying, assembled the nation's biggest airline empire under the banner of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> by buying up deregulated carriers and busting unions. Sympathetic biographers would label all three self-made me, but they were not the sort of cuddly entrepreneurs Americans instinctively embrace. Indeed their greatest successes prompted more cocked eyebrows than applause. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> was indicted for securities fraud. <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> was branded a `` raider.'' <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, after flying two airlines into bankruptcy and putting hundreds of union employees out of work, became known as one of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s toughest bosses. As three of the greatest risk-takers of the age, each was stalked as much as he hunted his own prey. But they were characteristically unbowed by challenge or criticism. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, a recent magazine profile noted, survived on the conviction of his own rightness. So, <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> in the face of his 1990 trial. So, <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> in his raids, most recently on a Japanese company. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s comment when he bought <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 was typical of the threesome's sober acceptance of controversy. `` There ai n't no <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claus </LOCATION>,'' he told a news conference.
</TEXT>
