<HEAD>Iacocca and Morita: National Symbols</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> and <PERSON> Morita </PERSON> were tough guys with a better press. They attracted enemies, but managed their images with aplomb. As a result, they became instant national symbols. The <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> chairman got a billion-dollar bailout from the federal government as the decade opened, but paid the debt in 1983, seven years ahead of schedule. To flaunt the extraordinary payback, he held a lavish press conference where he stood before a mammoth blowup of a check for $ 800 million, the company's final payment. His success at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, after being fired from <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in 1978, was as much a personal victory as a corporate one. He personally sold <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on the bailout and became the company's main pitchman for K-cars and minivans in national television commercials Exposure was his magic wand. When he was fired from the Statue of Liberty restoration committee in a political snit in 1986, he wrapped himself in the flag and called the ouster `` un-American.'' Most <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> fans agreed. <PERSON> Morita </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> chairman, became the Japanese answer to <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>, but with an even tougher PR challenge. Besides selling himself and his company, he had to sell a whole nation of aggressive capitalists to skeptical Americans. A natural salesman and communicator in the Iacocca mold, <PERSON> Morita </PERSON> seemed to sense what was needed to salve old postwar sores. After <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> bought <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> in 1987, he hugged recording star <PERSON> Cyndi </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauper </PERSON> for a magazine cover photo, symbolically embracing the culture. When <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> bought <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> this fall, he paid millions to get the services of a pair of American producers, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Guber </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>, creators of hits `` Batman'' and `` Rain Man.'' And, of course, <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> kept churning out gizmos for American consumers. Who could hate a guy bringing a Video Walkman to market just in time for Christmas? <PERSON> Morita </PERSON> was no softy: He frequently criticized short-term thinking in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and co-wrote a book discussing the `` decline of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' But when the book provoked a backlash in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, he apologized for promoting nationalistic views. The secret to the success of stars like <PERSON> Morita </PERSON> and <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> was their political sensitivity and their mastery of the media. Few business leaders of the age stood as tall outside the boardroom or the plant.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Jobs: Thirtysomething Entrepreneur</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 One man combined popular allure with real genius: <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Jobs </PERSON>. He was the American dream updated to the'80s. The garage inventor who struck it rich. A thirtysomething <PERSON> Horatio </PERSON> <PERSON> Alger </PERSON>. In a sense Jobs was the consummate business leader of the decade. He was young. He invented computers, the machine of the age. He walked away from a very successful company just to start another one. He built the <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> empire only to leave it in 1985 after introducing one of the hottest computer boxes of the decade, the Macintosh. Jobs left the company in a dispute with <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sculley </PERSON>, a veteran businessman whom <PERSON> Jobs </PERSON> himself had recruited to help run his growing firm. What mattered most to Jobs was not running a company, but creating hot boxes. His subsequent creation, the product of a few wizards' work, was appropriately labeled `` Next.'' His trademark long hair sometimes gave way to a yuppie trim, and he seemed to enjoy the panache of bow ties and designer suits as much as his faded blue jeans. But there was no mistaking what he represented. As the rebellious youth beating the old capitalist establishment at its own game, Jobs provided a fitting symbol for a decade that followed the'70s.
</TEXT>
