<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Success Story for the '80s: Dayton Hudson's Lauderback</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's been 10 years since <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON> hurdled society's gender and racial barriers to win her first corporate management job with the nation's fifth-largest retailing company. From a retail training program at a Gimbles department store in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, she arrived at <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Store </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> in 1975 as a merchandise buyer. Five years later, she emerged as the division head for intimate apparel and has since risen into company officer ranks as the general manager for shoes, cosmetics, accessories and intimate apparel _ the first black woman to hold such a post at the $ 1.7 billion subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` It showed me that your dreams can become reality and I knew it was just the beginning,'' <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON> said of her big promotion in 1980. In a decade noted for the pursuit of money, <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON> is among the hard-chargers who poured productive energy into the longest peacetime economic expansion in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. Her career also stands out among the thousands of women who entered the work force and moved up the corporate ladder in the'80s. Since 1982 <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON> has consistently met or surpassed sales goals for her $ 440 million division, and earlier this year she was invited to join the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> of 200 _ an elite national group of women executives. <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON> and her husband, Dr. <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION> dentist, are fixtures in the Twin Cities establishment. They have a `` status'' house in the exclusive suburb of <LOCATION> Edina </LOCATION>, an investment professional to help manage their income, a live-in caretaker with a master's degree in education to nurture their 4-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Phallon </PERSON>, and plenty of money to vacation. If only they had more time. <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON> said she's on the road up to 40 percent of the year, including trips to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the Orient. Her work week can easily mount to 60 hours. Hence the decision 2 -LCB- years ago to hire <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON>'s college friend, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, to help care for <PERSON> Phallon </PERSON>. `` It was when the pressures were getting real tight,'' <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON> said. `` She came to help us in managing our family and our future.'' <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON> said the frenzy of meshing her career with motherhood has prompted some to put her in the category of superwoman. But she detests the label for the expectations it carries. `` I do n't want that superwoman cape,'' she said. `` I'm like every other woman. I do the best I can.'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Store </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, summed up <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON>'s reputation in two words: `` High energy.'' Raised in the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> by a mother who worked as a beautician and a father who drove a truck, <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON> said she was warned not to give up on her goals in the face of racism or other adversity. Her father's tombstone reads: `` I may give out, but I'll never give up.'' `` I've had to succeed in a white world,'' <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON> said. `` But there has never been a doubt to anyone of who I am.'' Despite lofty job offers from the outside, <PERSON> Lauderback </PERSON> said she is content for now to stay with the 37-store <PERSON> Dayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> chain. Harking back to her promotion at the start of the'80s, she said she has the best of several worlds: A job, paycheck and family she loves. `` I felt like I was on a cloud then and I have stayed on that cloud for quite a while.''
</TEXT>
