<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Victims of the '80s: The Farming Kilcoins</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADAIR, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilcoin </PERSON>, a victim of the farm depression of the 1980s, says losing his farm and seeing someone else work the land was `` like watching someone else live with your wife.'' It was Oct. 19, 1987 _ a day known as `` Black Monday'' on Wall Street half a continent away _ that <PERSON> Kilcoin </PERSON> signed the deed of his farm over to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. Some of that land had been in his family for three generations. The 440-acre corn, cattle and hog operation in the rolling hills of west central <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, not far from the spot where <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> is reputed to have staged the first train robbery in the West, became another statistic in a faltering agricultural economy. `` The land is kind of attached to you. It's kind of like losing your arm,'' said <PERSON> Kilcoin </PERSON>. His wife, <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON>, interrupted, saying, `` No, it's more like losing your heart.'' <PERSON> Kilcoin </PERSON> and his wife say that after 20 straight years of making payments, they failed to meet a $ 35,000 annual mortgage installment in 1985 because new management at a local bank refused to continue a long-standing operating loan arrangement. `` We thought we had the operating money for the year put together. A couple of weeks before we needed it, we found we did n't have it,' he said <PERSON> Kilcoin </PERSON> says it was a shift in inflation policy and resulting high interest rates that did him in. In the 1970s, `` It was a common belief that inflation always would be with us,'' said <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Harl </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor and expert on agricultural economics. Inflationary expectations drove farmland values sky high, which boosted the borrowing power of farmers, who used that asset as collateral for loans. But the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s move to fight inflation with tighter credit in 1979 drove interest rates to record heights and sent land values tumbling. At the same time, a rising dollar made <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain and meat more expensive in foreign markets, cutting into farmers' traditional export earnings Drought hit in 1983, and <PERSON> Kilcoin </PERSON> says he never did catch up. Net cash farm income in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, the difference between cash earnings and cash expenses and a gauge of the money available to repay debts or invest in operations or savings, sank from about $ 2.7 billion in 1981 to around $ 1.6 billion in 1984. Farmland values in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> plummeted 71 percent from 1980 to 1987 after adjusting for inflation, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, a plunge even steeper than the 61 percent inflation-adjusted slump of 1916-1942. The slide eroded the security backing up loans held by the Kilcoins and others. `` We had a profit but interest rates ate up all profits and we had to borrow money just to pay the interest rates,'' <PERSON> Kilcoin </PERSON> said in a discussion at the table in a kitchen that has a 20-year-old stove, a used refrigerator and a dishwasher bought for $ 6 in a garage sale in the 1970s. `` It was n't that we were n't making money; we were n't making enough money.'' Now 51, <PERSON> Kilcoin </PERSON> has learned a new trade, making engine bearings. He has become a commuter who has time for his children only on weekends and goes to community college one day a week. `` I still walk though the door -LRB- at work -RRB- and the door shuts behind me and I think, ` Is this really me?''' He's far from alone in his plight, despite the rebound in the agricultural economy as the decade ended, with <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> net cash farm income shooting up to nearly $ 3.9 billion in 1987 and then settling to $ 3.4 billion last year. `` The people I work with are the same people _ either they are my age, farmed and lost or young people who wished they could farm but ca n't,'' <PERSON> Kilcoin </PERSON> said. His wife, 49, works at home assembling small parts for car and truck chassis for the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tool </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION>, earning about $ 200 a week _ enough to meet payments on a used minivan and buy the groceries. But before those jobs materialized, it was touch and go for the family with three married daughters and a 13-year-old girl and 6-year-old boy at home. For two years the couple did not know if they would keep their home, and <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> says he told his wife he was ready to leave the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> if he lost the house. But the Kilcoins negotiated to buy back the home and 13 -LCB- acres that surround it. They refused to declare bankruptcy and <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilcoin </PERSON> says, `` we will be paying the rest of our lives on our debt.'' Butnow, things are more settled. `` I do n't have to worry about the phone ringing any more. I do n't have to be afraid of going to the mailbox,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Kilcoin </PERSON> said. The couple still keeps a hand in farming, too. They fatten about 600 hogs for market under contract for a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> feedlot. They also own 18 head of cattle. <PERSON> Kilcoin </PERSON> still has worries, including fears for his country, which he sees overburdened by debt _ just as farmers were at the start of the decade. `` That puts them in the position I was,'' he said. `` Who shuts down the government?''
</TEXT>
