<HEAD>Biz Books Boomed in '80s, But Was There Wisdom in Volumes of Advice?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They wrote the book on business in the 1980s _ over and over and over, until it seemed there were fewer executives than authors telling them how to succeed. Choose your approach: Management by walking around. The flat organization. Quality circles -LRB- actually a holdover from the 1970s -RRB-. Zero defects. How `` soft'' management skills create `` hard'' business results. `` How to Give Good Phone'' was an offering from <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> <PERSON> Cool </PERSON>, `` <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> McMahon </PERSON>'s Superselling'' a tome by the <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> sidekick and <PERSON> Alpo </PERSON> pitchman. The scene for all this was set in 1982 by <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>' and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Waterman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s `` In Search of Excellence,'' which proved that critically well-received management books can also be money-makers. Then came `` Iacocca,'' followed by a string of best-sellers in the mid -'80s _ `` Megatrends,'' `` The One Minute Manager,'' `` What They Do n't Teach You at the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> `` Those three books sold between 500,000 and 1.5 million copies each, which was unheard of,'' said business book editor <PERSON> Harriet </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>. The floodgates opened. `` Publishing is definitely a follow-the-leader business, and when something works they jump on the bandwagon,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Miliot </PERSON>, editor of the B.P. Report, a publishing newsletter in <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, N.Y. `` Intrapreneuring.'' `` Thriving on Chaos.'' `` You Are the Message.'' `` Corporate Cultures.'' `` Leadership Secrets of Attila the Hun.'' <PERSON> Miliot </PERSON> said the books fit right in during the'80s, with `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, the business-is-great attitude and free enterprise at its best.'' But were they worth reading? `` Most of these books are shallow, insipid and stupid,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Drucker </PERSON>, the longtime business consultant and writer called the `` Dr. <PERSON> Spock </PERSON> for generations of American business managers'' by Business Week. `` Everyone was trying to emulate <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Drucker </PERSON>, 80, the author of 24 books, said in a telephone interview from his home in <LOCATION> Claremont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>, the book editor, agrees most of the books are `` dull and they're badly written. `` People were buying them, but they sort of used them as intellectual wallpaper, or on the desk as a placebo,'' she said. But unlike <PERSON> Drucker </PERSON>, she thinks there's a market for yet more business books in the 1990s. In fact, <PERSON> Doubleday </PERSON> has hired her as executive editor of a whole new line, Doubleday-Currency books advertised as being dedicated to business `` thinkers, not just doers,'' who `` rebel against the status quo.'' `` Who today can start a fire in our minds?'' Ms. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> writes in publicity material for the books. `` The Iacoccas succeeded in the old world of hierarchy, authority, and control, which has less relevance today.'' According to Ms. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>, `` The new hot button is no longer ` entrepreneur' or ` executive' but ` change agent.' That revolutionary is our ideal reader.'' `` Business people would buy ` In Search of Excellence,' ` Thriving on Chaos' and ` Leadership Secrets of Attila the Hun,''' Ms. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` But the books they would actually read ... were in the sciences, philosophy, pop culture,'' she said. `` They were trying to make sense of complex lives.'' The flagship publication of the new line is `` Leadership Is an Art'' by <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> DePree </PERSON>, chief executive of the <ORGANIZATION> Herman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> furniture makers, out this fall and already in its fifth printing with 65,000 copies in print. `` It's the opposite of ` Confessions of an S.O.B.,' or ` Leadership Secrets of Attila the Hun,''' said <PERSON> Doubleday </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Deval </PERSON>. `` His leadership principles are based on a concern for the health and welfare of the people working for you,'' Ms. <PERSON> Deval </PERSON> said. `` And not just for the sake of being kinder or gentler, but for overall profitability as well, the bottom line.'' <PERSON> Drucker </PERSON>, the dean of the management gurus, likes <PERSON> DePree </PERSON>'s book but hopes the business-book fad as a whole gets laid to rest. `` The boom is over _ I hope,'' <PERSON> Drucker </PERSON> said glumly. `` But I've been saying that for two years now and I've been wrong so far.
