<HEAD>In the '80s, Reaching for the Brass Ring Required a MBA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 To those who received MBAs in 1981, Wall Street beckoned like a siren's song. Although a recession gripped the nation, the securities industry and investment banks were on their way to reshaping <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businesses _ and they were hiring legions of fresh MBAs to do the job. Takeovers, restructurings and stock and bond offerings became fortune-making vehicles for an army of young people. Tales of 23-year-olds with $ 300,000 salaries plus bonuses abounded and lured flocks of people to the nation's business schools. But what a difference a decade makes. These days, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s financial district is quiet and depressed. Tens of thousands of people were let go following the Oct. 19, 1987, market collapse. The stock market's unsettling volatility this fall has hurt new hiring plans. `` No new people are coming into the securities industry,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON>, an'81 <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> MBA </ORGANIZATION> grad and vice president at the investment research boutique of <ORGANIZATION> Gerard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klauer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mattison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. Lucrative fees from megadeals withered this year as the dollar volume of takeovers slumped 28 percent from 1988's heady pace, according to <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Investment houses have scaled back commissions and shut entire departments to save money Some estimate bonuses will be trimmed by as much as 30 percent this year. The big salaries that deal people commanded during'80s `` were clearly out of line _ and they still are,'' said <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Rochman </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and 1981 MBA graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. Starting salaries for MBAs doubled over the course of the decade. <ORGANIZATION> NYU </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Stern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> said the average salary for grads entering all facets of business was $ 26,936 in 1981; the average broke the $ 50,000 mark this year. -LRB- The cost of getting the degree has nearly tripled at some schools. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> is charging $ 30,700 for the two-year MBA course that cost $ 9,600 in 1981. -RRB- A recent <ORGANIZATION> NYU </ORGANIZATION> survey shows male 1979 MBA grads are averaging $ 122,600 a year while their female classmates are making $ 87,200 on average. And the respondents _ 143 of out of 665 alumni polled _ have averaged three promotions since leaving <ORGANIZATION> NYU </ORGANIZATION>. But for those hitting the pavement in 1991, the degree that once opened doors could become an impediment at some job interviews. Some speculate that with scrutiny of the bottom line, employers may not readily embrace the high-priced grad clutching a master's of business administration degree. `` People think the MBA is a ticket to a higher life,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Corwin </PERSON>, 31, chief operating officer at the <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, consulting firm <ORGANIZATION> Caliper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` Sure, they are averaging higher salaries, but in the end it comes down to what an individual makes of an opportunity,'' said <PERSON> Corwin </PERSON>, an'81 <ORGANIZATION> NYU </ORGANIZATION> grad. As Wall Street loses its allure, more grads are seeking to work for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s corporations, and companies are carving out a greater presence on campuses recruiting students. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Avison </PERSON>, 24, expects to put in 60-hour weeks in sales or marketing for a major consumer products corporation when she graduates in 1991 from <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Amos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION>. At <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, MBA candidate <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON>, 25, said he would n't be surprised if the nation slips into a recession shortly after he graduates, but he says those who develop highly specific skills will fare well. <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> hopes to become involved in investment management for a university or charity endowment when he graduates in 1991, a far cry from investment banking. If the business climate sours in the coming decade, as many believe it will, the class of'91 `` may not have been taught, as we were n't, how to deal with it,'' <PERSON> Caliper </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Corwin </PERSON> said. He credits the hard economic times of the early'80s for teaching him more about running a business than business school ever did. `` It's much easier to manage when there's growth,'' said <PERSON> Corwin </PERSON>, who noted that his consulting firm lost a third of its business between 1981 and 1982. Current students say money is not their primary concern. `` If you work hard, the money will come,'' <PERSON> Avison </PERSON> said. But one recent <ORGANIZATION> Ivy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> grad countered that `` making money is an essential consideration, particularly for those attending expensive private schools.'' Still, financial rewards come at a high price. Long hours, broken marriages and a distorted sense of values typified business of the'80s. `` I have seen what is probably a higher incidence of divorce in our industry, I suspect because people are trying to reach for the brass ring,'' <PERSON> Rochman </PERSON> said. `` The spirit of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s presidency was one of hands-off, unfettered pursuit of wealth, even greed,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>, 37, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> CS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION>, though he believes the nation is begining to focus on more social concerns. If there is one axiom that holds true, it is, in <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON>' words, that `` the business world was tough, and it still is.''
