<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet's Dramatic Push for Western-Style Economy Marks Decade</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It was almost unimaginable. The West's most prominent banker jetting to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to advise the archenemy of capitalism But <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> recently made such a trip, a sign of the extraordinary changes that marked the'80s overseas. It was a decade marked by the pursuit of a formula for economic success, a drive that brought about wrenching changes. The big winners were the most modern, complex and open economies. Far down on the list were those dependent on natural resources and those with closed, controlled systems. In <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, some countries took their first, halting steps toward Western-style economies and integration into the world economy. In <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> finally took seriously its decision to fashion a single market of the dozen nations by 1992. The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries went on a roller-coaster ride that carried oil prices to wild levels before crashing and finally recovering. <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> was caught up in the foreign debt crisis that swept the world's developing nations in the early 1980s, sapping their economic strength and impoverishing their growing populations even more. In <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the events that captured the imagination, that seemed least likely at the start of the decade, stemmed from the Soviets' tacit acknowledgement that their economic system had failed Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who came to power in March 1985, pressed his perestroika program to restructure the backward economy, trying to wrench it from centrally planned ways to a more market-oriented system. There was talk of price reform and private enterprise, more consumer goods and fewer government subsidies. `` There can be no return to the old style of economic management,'' asserted <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shemiatenkov </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s envoy to the European Community. But <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s task remains staggering. Inflation is high and so is the government's budget deficit. Millions have been thrown out of work by the modernization efforts. Workers strike and consumers grumble. `` They do n't have a decent economic reform program yet,'' said <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanous </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> PlanEcon </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> forecasting firm. Despite the daunting challenge, reform fever is spreading in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, particularly <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, long a leader of economic reform in the communist bloc, and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, where the new Solidarity leadership plans to move swiftly to a market economy. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, once one of the most conservative members of the Soviet bloc, joined the rush. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> offered massive financial aid in return for stepped-up economic and political reforms. The European Community quickly negotiated broad trade and economic cooperation agreements with <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and a smaller pact with <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. Deals also were pursued with the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Among the Western powers, a wealth of proposals were offered for reaching their goal of a European-wide market by 1992. In contrast to the new freedoms symbolized by the crumbling <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> wall, the 1992 preparations were characterized by heated disagreements over ways to dismantle the barriers separating the Common Market allies. British Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> clashed with others in their vision of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s future. She fought proposals to create a common currency and central bank system, fearing a loss of sovereignty. `` <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s destiny lies in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' argued <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, whose October resignation as <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s top treasury official rocked the government. He urged Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> to relent and link the pound to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s other major currencies. The linkage system, the exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System, has brought the economies more in line, analysts say. With the opening of borders between the Germanys, concern was raised that the <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> government would forsake the West for the East. Government officials hastily insisted they were with the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> aggressively monitored the community's 1992 campaign, complaining of any moves to keep its products out of the new marketplace. The term `` Fortress <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'' was coined. Europeans denied protectionism was afoot. For <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>, the decade was trying. The 1979 revolution in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, a major oil-producing nation, was marked by a sharp drop in crude production. World oil prices soared above $ 40 a barrel, shocking the economies of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other industrialized nations. In late 1985, the cartel shifted strategy to defend its `` fair share'' of the world oil market. A production free-for-all sent prices crashing. Futures prices for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark American crude, plunged to near $ 10 a barrel in March 1986. Toward the decade's end, <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> pulled itself together. Key members <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, at war most of the decade, resolved some differences, and the cartel as a whole became less confrontational with consuming nations. Demand for the cartel's oil grew, and prices rebounded to around $ 20 per barrel. In <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the'80s were years of unrelieved misery. `` <LOCATION> Sub-Saharan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> as a whole has now witnessed almost a decade of falling per-capita incomes, increasing hunger and accelerating ecological degradation,'' according to a <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> report. Problems afflicting the region of 450 million people include low foreign investment, weak export sales, growing populations, increasing debt and poor agricultural and industrial performance.
</TEXT>
