<SECOND>BC-Decade-Asia, Adv 00,1004</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release in Yearend Editions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Japan Excels Economically; ``Four Tigers'' in Pursuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a decade of Asian economic success, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> piled up No. 1 labels, four other countries gained the nickname `` tigers,'' and the star performers amassed more money to fuel their advance into the 1990s. The standouts lack abundant natural resources, but have governments that encourage private business. They share a Confucian ethic stressing education, hard work and thrift. High savings rates have helped pay for new and better production facilities. Dependence on exports forced factories to hone efficiencies needed to compete in the international marketplace. Government steps to hold down inflation promoted confidence and stability. Success in the frontrunners _ including `` tigers'' <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> _ helped pull up some of the followers, like <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, both by example and by expanding trade and investment. <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s giant, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, also tried stressing a diligence-thrift ethic to make its 1 billion people more productive and less poor, but lacked the incentives of its neighbors' free-market economies and their managerial skills and education levels. Amid scarcities, spending on construction and efforts to live better ended up overheating the economy. War impoverished <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, although <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> ended the decade by withdrawing what it said were its last troops in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and trying to free its economy from some of the strictures of central planning. The <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, amid a intensifying political crisis, struggled with a legacy of foreign debt from the rule of the late President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, whose businessmen associates came to rely more on favors than initiative. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> struggled with problems of the rich as its high exports and high-profile acquisitions abroad aroused resentment. It became the world's largest creditor in 1985 and the rise of the yen inflated its international financial power. In 1987, the economic newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Nihon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Keizai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION> calculated that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> had become the world's richest nation on paper, with $ 43.7 trillion in total assets such as land, factories and stock, compared with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assets of $ 36.2 trillion. The inflated wealth, plus <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s high savings rate and its industries' new ability to finance their own investments, gave Japanese banks the funds to become major players in world finance. Japanese purchases of corporations and property in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> became a sensitive issue, although Americans continued seeking Japanese investment. The abundance of funds in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s stock markets also has given its corporations access to low-cost financing that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies can not match. American corporations with access to such funds likely would be tempted to try to buy out a competitor, said <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Rasmussen </PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> Jardine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleming </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, while Japanese firms tend to focus on productive capacity. `` Come 1991 or 1992, life could get very exciting for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies. They are going to emerge from a period of sluggish growth and long recuperation ... confronted with a flood of high-quality Japanese exports,'' he said. This will be a result of Japanese companies' strong balance sheets rather than an overall national strategy, he said. In <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, too, `` companies used to rely on banks as their main source of funds. Now they can raise more money from the stock market and do n't have to worry about banks withdrawing loans in case of an economic slowdown,'' said <PERSON> Yeh </PERSON> <PERSON> Chih-yung </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Officials said many of the 170 listed companies have used such funds to automate equipment and make more sophisticated products to overcome the impact of the rising <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> dollar In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the yen's rise since 1985 forced a major change in mid-decade, from reliance on exports to depending on the home market to fuel economic growth. But despite their country's image, most Japanese do n't feel rich, says <PERSON> Isamu </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>. He cited workdays exceeding those in the West by perhaps 600 hours a year; cramped housing and long commutes through congested traffic; and prices that, while stable, exceed other industrialized nations' by 20 percent to 30 percent. These result from government protection of agriculture and an inefficient distribution system, he said. In <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Yong </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, said curbs on government budgets and wage raises kept annual inflation between 2.3 percent and 7.1 percent, down from more than 15 percent in the previous decade. The government also encouraged competition to sharpen efficiency, and stressed technical renovation. Labor unrest has erupted in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> over the last year, however. In <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, rural production improved as the government ended factory-style commune farming and gave families a chance to do some of their own marketing and use spare time for sideline business. But in the state-run factories, efforts to boost productivity faced the `` iron rice bowl,'' a system of lifetime employment in which workers are paid the same regardless of labor performed. After cracking down on the democracy movement in June, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> promoted leaders favoring order and central planning over giving wider play to market forces. The next two largest <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> nations _ <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> _ also lag in education, with <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>'s literacy rate at 26 percent and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s at 36 percent. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> has given <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> high marks in recent years for boosting growth by encouraging the private sector with improved incentives and deregulation, and moving to shift the economy away from heavy reliance on oil exports. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s government has favored state planning in efforts to reduce income inequalities and promote rapid industrialization, but analysts say this inward-looking policy has hurt efficiency and growth. <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, which looks toward <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> in its economic activity, shares its more successful neighbors' free-market economy and high education level, but its economic performance depends more than theirs on prices for commodities. Its major exports include coal and farm products.
</TEXT>
