<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tuesday Dec. 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>Disposing of A Mighty Mountain of Trash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It is n't a pleasant subject to face around Christmas but it is appropriate to the season. The subject is trash. Americans generate mountains of the stuff, particularly around this time of year, but they do n't like to face the consequences. They like it to disappear from their property, and they do n't like to think about it thereafter. They must like to throw things away _ 3.5 pounds a day, compared with 2.7 pounds a day per person in 1960, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> _ but they do n't like to dwell on the fact that there is no `` away.'' Trash must go into recycling programs, waste-to-energy facilities that burn it or into landfills. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimates 85 percent of it goes into landfills, which are filling up and closing down all over the country. Over the past 10 years, according to an authority on the subject, more than half the 18,500 landfills that existed in 1979 have closed, and the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> now forecasts that by the 1990s only 4,000 will remain open. Conclusion: Much as they like to avoid it, <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> must face the issue of trash production, trash collection and trash disposal. <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Scarlett </PERSON>'s study might help. Already the study by <PERSON> Scarlett </PERSON>, research director of the <ORGANIZATION> Reason </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a conservative think tank based in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, has stirred interest in the industry and among policymakers. The study points out four basic options available: 1. Waste reduction policies. 2. Recycling programs. 3. Waste-to-enery facilites that burn trash. 4. Identification and construction of additional landfills. <PERSON> Scarlett </PERSON> observes that other industrialized nations already produce far less trash per person than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, `` amply illustrating that it is possible, through altered habits, to generate less trash.'' The Japanese, <PERSON> Scarlett </PERSON> states, produce only 76 percent the amount of garbage generated per person in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> produces even less, about 60 percent, and <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> only 40 percent of American waste per person. Recycling efficiency also can be improved, according to the study, which concludes that waste hauled to landfills could be reduced 25 percent. Existing programs, however, handle less than 20 percent of waste in their communities. In fact, what is referred to as recycling sometimes is n't. Much of what it earmarked for recycling merely ends up in the disposal site after all, because in some cases the market for recycled products is depressed. Why, asked a <ORGANIZATION> Reason </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, should forests be harvested when the market for recycled newsprint might be falling in price? His point: The recycling of some items might simultaneously help conserve national assets. The study states that experience with waste-to-enery facilites produces the most dramatic results, since incinerators are capable of handling up to 90 percent of the waste stream, leaving only the inert ashes for disposal. <PERSON> Scarlett </PERSON> recommends all four strategies, and that people be made aware of the costs involved, which sometimes are hidden in general real estate taxes; that customers be charged on a volume basis; and that competition be invited from private garbage collectors and disposal services. The study, available at no charge to community officials -LRB- 2716 <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Blvd. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> 90405 -RRB-, cites <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>'s recycling program as a model that works, and provides specifics on costs and savings in that city
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tuesday Dec. 12</NOTE>
