<HEAD>Wyse Technology Bought By Taiwan Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Foreign Investment Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Wyse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the world's second largest maker of computer terminals, agreed Monday to a $ 268 million buyout by a <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> group in a deal that could boost the company's flagging business. <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON>, which is based in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> but does all manufacturing in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and elsewhere overseas, began a search for buyers after losing $ 21 million in the 1989 fiscal year ended March 31. The $ 10-per-share buyout by <ORGANIZATION> Channel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, an investment group of government and local enterprises, is the largest ever of a foreign firm by <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. `` A lot of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies looked at <LOCATION> Wyse </LOCATION> but figured it was n't worth more than $ 4 or $ 5 a share,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, editor of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Technology Stockletter `` <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON> got the best price it could from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>.'' `` The acquisition is an important step for <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s electronics and computer industries to enter the world market,'' <PERSON> Koo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheng-fu </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the largest investor in the buyout, said in a news conference in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Koo </PERSON> said his group would use <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON>'s sales channels and technology personnel to promote <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s high-technology products. <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON>, an 8-year-old company that earned $ 28 million in fiscal 1988 before slumping, holds more than a 50 percent market share for general-purpose terminals in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Worldwide, <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON> trails only <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> as a supplier of terminals, said <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Blatnik </PERSON>, an industry analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>. Terminals, which can be hooked to mainframes, minicomputers or personal computers, accounted for 47 percent of <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON>'s $ 452 million in sales in fiscal 1989. Personal computers accounted for 39 percent, and screen monitors accounted for 14 percent of sales. <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON> is expected to sell 800,000 terminals worldwide by the end of 1989, nearly all to businesses, compared with just over 1 million by <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Blatnik </PERSON> said. In the first six months of fiscal 1990, ending Sept. 29, <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON> had $ 231 million in revenue and net losses of $ 7.7 million. <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON> has been less successful in selling IBM-compatible personal computers, and <PERSON> Blatnik </PERSON> said that is the area that should get the most attention from the new Taiwanese owners. `` The whole concept of the deal has to be looked at as a positive step for <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Blatnik </PERSON> said. `` It gives them financial stability, and over the long term provides them with a better focus on the PC side of their business.'' Although <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON> has a reputation for making low-priced, high-quality terminals and personal computers, its strategy in the PC market has hurt the company's growth, said <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON> has a strategy of not producing the most advanced computers,'' he said. `` They wait to see how the latest technology shakes out and then try to move in with lower prices. That has n't worked out for them They need to be more innovative.'' <ORGANIZATION> Wyse </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse </PERSON> will remain with the company as vice chairman. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Chang </PERSON>, former senior vice president <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> and former president of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instrument </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, will become chairman and chief executive officer of <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> has been serving as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit research and development organization established in 1973 to accelerate the development of advanced technology in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. He said he does n't plan significant near-term changes in <LOCATION> Wyse </LOCATION>'s product lines or its approach to business, and intends to maintain its headquarters, marketing and related operations in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> Taiwanese businessmen have shown growing interest in acquiring foreign firms, which they believe could boost their business in the world market. Last month, <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hsieh </PERSON>, governor of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, proposed using <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s foreign reserves of about $ 73 billion for loans to local enterprises for overseas acquisitions.
