<HEAD>Gold Prices Surge, Approach New 1989 High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Gold futures prices surged to within a few dollars of new 1989 highs Monday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as the market extended for a fifth day its recovery from a steep post-Thanksgiving decline. On other commodity markets, orange juice futures rose sharply on <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> freeze fears; cotton futures rebounded; energy futures gained; pork futures fell; cattle futures rose; and grains and soybeans were mixed. Gold futures settled $ 4.90 to $ 5.50 higher with the contract for delivery in December up $ 5 at $ 416.80 a troy ounce. The December contract reached an intra-day high of $ 418 an ounce, just $ 1.70 below the 1989 high of $ 419.70 reached on Nov. 24. Silver futures finished 4.5 cents to 4.9 cents higher with December at $ 5.692 a troy ounce. Analysts said that after climbing back steadily from about $ 401 in the past week, gold looked strong enough to break through $ 420 an ounce, an event that would likely trigger new waves of buying. Explanations for the recovery abounded but four market analysts queried by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> agreed the political changes occurring in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> were in some way linked to gold's strength `` The market reads this as one of the watershed geopolitical events of the 20th century,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> noted a strong correlation between the gold market and the West German mark, which he interpreted as evidence that investors expect <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> to benefit economically from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s movement away from communism <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON>, a director and chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Diversified </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, saw signs that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is preparing to issue gold-backed bonds and halt all sales of gold on the open market. Gold traders also responded to Monday's higher energy prices, typically a buy-signal for inflation-sensitive gold, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardillo </PERSON>, commodity trading adviser with <ORGANIZATION> Josephthal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Orange juice futures rose sharply on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> amid forecasts for a hard freeze in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> by the end of the week. Frozen concentrated orange juice settled 2.45 cents to 3.75 cents higher with January at $ 1.313 cents a pound. Cotton futures also climbed sharply in a move that analysts viewed as a technical correction after several sessions in which prices fell. Cotton settled .60 cent to 1.73 cent higher with March at 67.91 cents a pound. Heating oil continued to lead energy prices higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as extremely cold temperatures in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> spurred demand for fuel oil on the world market. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 15 cents to 23 cents higher with January at $ 20.70 a barrel; heating oil was .15 cent lower to .58 cent higher with January at 66.95 cents a gallon; unleaded