<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wholesale home heating oil prices rose Monday as wintry weather boosted demand. Crude oil futures also closed higher but gasoline futures finished lower. The contract for No. 2 heating oil for January delivery rose 0.58 cent to 66.95 cents a gallon on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, adding to Friday's gain of 0.90 cent Contracts for delivery during February and March ended with much smaller increases while the April contract fell slightly. Low temperatures in parts of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> spurred buying, analysts said. Buyers in the crude oil pit took a cue from heating oil traders and bid prices higher. The January contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, rose 22 cents to $ 20.70 per 42-gallon barrel after losing 3 cents on Friday. The February through April contracts ended with similar gains. Among other refined products traded on the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Merc </LOCATION>, wholesale unleaded gasoline for January delivery, which sank 0.16 cent on Friday, dropped another 0.25 cent to 52.40 cents a gallon. Other contracts closed lower also. Gasoline prices typically soften in the winter when driving tapers off due to bad weather. Energy analyst <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Simard </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said buying enthusiasm in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> spilled over into <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets. In <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, prices of gasoil _ the equivalent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> heating oil _ have firmed because of shortages and a seasonal pickup in demand. She said there were reports Monday that a drought in parts of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, which has caused low water levels on the <LOCATION> Rhine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, has reduced production of hydroelectric power. The result has been extra demand for alternative energy sources. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> now is importing more energy than it is exporting while normally the country is a net energy exporter, <PERSON> Simard </PERSON> said, citing reports circulating in the futures markets.
