<HEAD>U.S.-Dutch Securities Agreement Reached</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Wim Kok in 5th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> securities regulators have signed a pact to assist each other in conducting investigations and enforcing their respective securities laws, the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday. Officials hailed the administrative assistance agreement, signed Monday at <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hague </LOCATION>, as the most comprehensive formal securities enforcement accord yet between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and a European country. `` Each of our nations has a common interest in protecting investors at home, and in foreign markets, from fraud, manipulation and similar abusive practices,'' <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> said in written remarks prepared for the signing at The Hague. `` The agreement signed today strengthens our ability and detect these types of unlawful activities conducted across national borders,'' <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> stated. The agreement also was signed by Dutch Minister of <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Wim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kok </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investors' transactions in Dutch corporate stock increased from $ 1.9 billion to $ 4 billion between 1985 and 1988. During the the same period, Dutch transactions in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporate stock increased from $ 4 billion to $ 5.8 billion. Under the agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and Dutch finance ministry will assist each other in enforcing their respective securities laws, including obtaining information and documents, taking statements and conducting compliance examinations or inspections of securities businesses. The agreement applies only to territory of the Kingdom of the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and not in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. Mutual cooperation in criminal matters, however, will continue to governed by a 1981 mutual assistance treaty.
