<SECOND>AM-IMF-Peru,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Pact with International Monetary Fund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After four years of disagreements, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> announced on Monday that it has reached an accord with <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, raising the prospect of financial aid if Peruvian policies meet its approval. An official of the fund, who spoke on condition he not be named, said <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> had made a payment of $ 42.3 million on the $ 800 million it owes the fund. The payment covers only the arrears since September of this year. The agreement was reached last week between <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s negotiator, <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Michal </PERSON> <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON>, the fund's French managing director, the official said. Owned by 152 governments, the fund negotiates at length with governments in financial trouble. It gives its help only when the borrowing government agrees on a set of policies it approves. Usually these include cuts in government spending, especially on official payrolls and subsidies, and often a devaluation of the country's currency. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> has been in trouble with the financial world since President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> was elected in 1985 and announced that he would make only partial payments of interest on the country's debts At that time <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> owed $ 14 billion abroad. Now the figure is closer to $ 20 billion. Its financial troubles have been worsened by the continuing rebellion of a leftist guerrilla group, the Shining Path, and a thriving traffic in drugs. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> is one of 10 countries with a total arrears of $ 3.5 billion to the fund, and so ineligible for more finanical aid from it _ or much from anyone else. This year the fund started a series of what it called `` shadow programs,'' under which governments promised new policies but got no immediate money. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> and now <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> have started such programs. If the fund finds they are doing well after a year or so, they will start getting its financial help.
