<HEAD>Labor Department Orders Eastern Compliance on Health Benefits</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Monday said it has obtained an order requiring <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> to help striking and laid-off employees obtain continued health benefits. `` Employers must know that the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is serious about protecting the right of working Americans to continued health coverage in cases like <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement released in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> concerning <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and the Consolidated Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act. The consent order, which requires Eastern to report on its compliance quarterly for five years, followed an investigation by Labor officials into complaints by Eastern COBRA participants who said insurance carriers told them they were no longer covered, even though the employees had paid insurance premiums. The federal law says employers must give terminated employees the chance to obtain continued health benefits at group rates. `` As a result -LRB- officials -RRB- began a large-scale investigation into possible violations of notification and insurance claims processing provisions under COBRA,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>, assistant Labor Secretary. <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> <PERSON> Haber </PERSON>, senior general chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union that's been on strike since March 4, said employees were inappropriately rejected on claims or faced backlogs of up to six months. `` We've been having a running battle with Eastern on the COBRA violations,'' Haber said. <PERSON> Haber </PERSON> said just before the strike began, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> laid off most of its workers in the insurance department, which contributed to the backlog. <PERSON> Haber </PERSON> said employees have had better results recently. Eastern spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said claims were taking an average of four weeks to process. He said the consent order would have no financial impact on Eastern. `` We're up-to-date now,'' he said. <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> blamed initial problems on a combination of hostile union-management relations, the complications of the Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization Eastern filed for March 9, and the massive number of employees suddenly on strike o laid off. Also, he said, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> had computer problems that exacerbated the delays. `` We feel that we really reacted admirably in the unusual circumstances,'' <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said. `` The COBRA law never contemplated such wide-ranging and massive problems.'' Eastern has been operating as a much smaller airline because of the strike and bankruptcy reorganization. It reportedly is close to selling Latin American routes to <ORGANIZATION> AMR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, parent of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, for $ 300 million to $ 400 million. Neither Fort Worth-based AMR nor Eastern would discuss the deal, reported in several newspapers. But there was speculation a deal could be announced by Wednesday, when <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> is scheduled to meet with a committee of creditors. The negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> AMR </ORGANIZATION> on the Latin American routes are the second round since <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> sought Chapter 11 protection. Earlier attempts to sell the routes to <ORGANIZATION> AMR </ORGANIZATION> foundered over disagreements involving a lawsuit filed against American by <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, the other main <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary. During the strike American, the nation's largest airline, has been expanding aggressively in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> _ a key area for Eastern.
