<HEAD>Royal Crown Asks FTC for Sanctions Against Pepsi, Coke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has asked the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to invoke sanctions against bigger rivals <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for what it called `` predatory pricing'' by their company-owned bottling plants. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, president and chief operating officer of <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crown </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday that the company has asked the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> for sanctions against the two. Royal Crown has requested that <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> be prohibited from acquiring additional holdings in their franchise systems, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> disclosed at a beverage industry gathering in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In addition, he said, the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> should order the two companies to divest their interests in company-owned bottling plants and the brands other than <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> produced by those operations. Under the request, Royal Crown has asked the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> to require that the two companies each reduce their holdings in company-owned plants to 25 percent within two years _ at which time they would be sold. Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> declined comment, saying it was unaware of any <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> investigation of the issue, said spokesman <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Purchase </LOCATION>, said it has n't been contacted on the matter by the federal agency or Royal Crown. `` There's really nothing new here and certainly nothing the industry has n't heard before,'' said <PERSON> Tod </PERSON> <PERSON> MacKenzie </PERSON>, a spokesman for the company's <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cola </ORGANIZATION> operations. Royal Crown's appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> is the second time in three years the company has filed complaints with the agency against <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION>. In 1986, Royal Crown asked the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> to block <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Seven-Up </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION>'s planned buyout of Dr Pepper, claiming the purchases would violate federal antitrust laws The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> later blocked the acquisitions on antitrust grounds. Royal Crown, based in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, is a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Chesapeake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which is in turn controlled by industrialist <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>. In his talk, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> called predatory pricing the most serious problem facing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soft drink industry. Predatory pricing consists of pricing products below cost to beat competitors, then quickly hiking them back up after the action has succeeded. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> charged, for example, that it costs bottlers about 80 cents to put a two-liter bottle in a supermarket, but <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> both sold the bottles for 69 cents each last Labor Day weekend in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> has 41.1 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soft drink market, followed by <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> with 31.1 percent. Royal Crown has only 2.8 percent, according to <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Digest </ORGANIZATION>, an industry publication.
</TEXT>
