<FIRST>r f AM-ColumbiaSavings     12-11 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Columbia Savings,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>Junk Bond Proponent Resigns as Columbia Savings Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The troubled junk bond market claimed the job of one of its biggest supporters Monday when <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON> said he would quit as chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> at the end of the year. Under the leadership of <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON>, a former Wall Street trader, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> invested more heavily than any other thrift in high-yield, high-risk bonds, turning big profits on them until recently. But new federal laws forced <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> to essentially return to being a conventional mortgage lender. The thrift in October marked down the price of its junk bonds to reflect their depressed market value, as required by new federal law, taking a loss of about $ 350 million. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> plans to sell the junk bonds to a new subsidiary. Previously, thrifts did n't have to adjust the book value of their bonds to account for market price because they carried them as long-term investments. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s high-yield portfolio is now worth $ 3.8 billion, down from $ 4.3 billion at the end of last year, and <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON> said the thrift urgently needed to rid itself of the bonds. <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON> said he would work full time as a consultant to <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>, trying to line up investors for the subsidiary into which the junk bonds would be spun off. A thrift bailout bill signed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in August requires thrifts to sell their junk bonds by 1994. Under the legislation, thrifts can invest in junk bonds only through separately capitalized affiliates rather than using government-insured deposits. `` Business imperatives coupled with the publicity surrounding me led me to conclude that a new CEO with extensive banking or thrift experience was required to lead <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> into the future,'' <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON> said in a statement. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> said it already had begun interviewing potential successors. <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON> is a friend of junk bond pioneer <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, who has been indicted on racketeering and securities fraud charges. New charges against <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> reportedly will include allegations of illegal stock and bond deals with <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON> was unavailable for an interview, but <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lenore </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said he intended to hold the bonds to maturity in the new <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary. She said it was too early to describe in detail how the subsidiary would work. `` Hopefully the structure we're considering would have the effect of removing the volatility that's in the high-yield market,'' she said. <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON> said in his statement that the depressed market for junk bonds had created big opportunities. `` During the eight years in which I have been actively involved in the high-yield securities market, I have never seen better values,'' he said. <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON>, 43, noted that his family owns more than half of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s common stock. `` I believe that it is urgent that I move rapidly to preserve and enhance the value of our securities portfolio,'' he said. Fueled largely by <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON>'s investments in junk bonds, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s assets jumped to $ 13 billion this year from $ 400 million in 1974. But in the third quarter of this year <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 226 million as a result of $ 357.5 million in losses related to those bond holdings. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> said that because of problems with junk bond investments it will be unable to meet the tougher requirements for risk-based capital under the savings and loan bailout law. In order to boost its capital, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to sell nearly all its mortgage-backed securities for about $ 90 million, and to sell `` certain public and private equities'' for a gain of about $ 75 million, the thrift said in a statement. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> said it has raised $ 10 million more through various asset sales and other actions. Thrift institutions like <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> that do not meet the new capital requirements are required to file a capital plan acceptable to federal regulators by Jan. 8. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> said its plan will, as required, detail its financial strategy for compliance, but the thrift provided no details. <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON> was paid $ 5.6 million in 1987 and $ 4.1 million last year. Ms. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said his pay package as a consultant has not been determined, and she declined to estimate how much he will make this year. His high salaries have angered federal thrift regulators for years, as has his amassing of the huge portfolio of junk bonds. He also is known for his close ties to political figures. He set up the junk bond investment for former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> majority whip <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> that forced the Democrat to resign last May.
</TEXT>
