<HEAD>Continental Airlines Orders $1.4 Billion in Jet Engines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVENDALE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has ordered jet engines worth nearly $ 1.4 billion from <ORGANIZATION> CFM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> to power as many as 40 <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrie </ORGANIZATION> planes, the engine maker says. <ORGANIZATION> CFM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, a joint venture of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> SNECMA </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, said Monday that <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> ordered 20 planes powered by CF6-80E1 engines and 20 powered by CFM56-5C2 engines, with options to buy 20 more of each plane. The CF6-80E1 is set to go into service in late 1992, and the CFM56-5C2 is scheduled to go into service in 1991, the engine maker said.
