<HEAD>Pittsburgh National, First Federal Merging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The third-largest savings and loan in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> is merging with <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, which is owned by the state's largest bank holding company, officials said Monday. The merger with <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> is subject to government approval. Also needed is satisfactory completion of a review of First Federal by <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> and approval of the board of directors of <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION>'s parent company, <ORGANIZATION> PNC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's 13th-largest bank holding company The merger will not require a cash payment by <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> or the issuance of additional shares by <ORGANIZATION> PNC </ORGANIZATION> Financial since <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> is a mutual institution. Once the transaction is completed, <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> said it will have about $ 20 billion in assets. Some bank branches will be closed, but employees of those offices will be offered other jobs, said <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> National President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rohr </PERSON>. First Federal has $ 3 billion in assets, primarily comprised of mortgage-related products. It is the 88th largest thrift nationwide. First Federal has more than 700 full-time and 200 par