<HEAD>US West To Help Launch New Venture in Communications</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 U S West and three international partners have been awarded an operating license to provide a new type of portable telephone system, called Personal Communications Networks, in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>, officials said. PCNs are heralded as the next generation of mobile communications technology. They differ from the cellular phone systems of today in that they will operate on a different frequency and use more and smaller cell sites, allowing a much greater volume of calls to be supported. A cell site is an area served by a transmission tower that relays calls. The project will cost an estimated $ 1.4 billion to develop and implement over a 12-year period starting in 1992 or 1993, said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattix </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> U </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>. Other companies in the <ORGANIZATION> Unitel </ORGANIZATION> consortium are <ORGANIZATION> STC </ORGANIZATION>, a British electronics, telecommunications and information technology company and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s second-largest maker of telephones; Thorm-EMI of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, an international seller and renter of television sets, records and other telecommunications equipment; and <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bundespost </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telekom </ORGANIZATION>, the telephone company of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. U S West and <ORGANIZATION> STC </ORGANIZATION> own 30 percent of the consortium, Thorm-EMI owns 25 percent and <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bundespost </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telekom </ORGANIZATION> 15 percent. U S West is the regional telephone company based in this <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> suburb.
